<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FREEAGENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL FREE-AGENT SIGNINGS CREATE WIDE CHASMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a frenzied six weeks after the World Series, the gully
separating professional baseball's haves from the have-nots became
a canyon, prompting some owners and general managers to voice
concern about the future of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Teams have spent more than $1 billion on free agents this
offseason. And just six _ the Dodgers, Angels, Mets, Yankees,
Orioles and Diamondbacks _ have shelled out $718 million of that
total.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the capper came Dec.12, when the Dodgers signed
pitcher Kevin Brown to a $105-million, seven-year contract, making
him baseball's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   There were others:
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mo Vaughn was signed by the Angels to an
$80-million, six-year deal. The Yankees re-signed Bernie Williams
and gave him $87.5 million for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Randy Johnson got a four-year, $52.4 million deal with
the Arizona Diamondbacks; Albert Belle signed a $65-million,
five-year deal with Baltimore; former Dodgers catcher Mike Piazza
picked up $91 million to hang with the Mets through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   At least one baseball executive, Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone, defended his signing as a required response to an alarming
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lack of quality players,'' said Malone, ``so you
have to overpay for quality. There's a premium on quality. When
there's a lack of talent, it drives the price up on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: The average professional baseball player earned
$1.4 million in 1998. And how about this? The average American
earned $38,000 in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Brown signing is great for the Dodgers. After a dismal
1998, the team is now a serious contender for the National League
pennant in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As Malone put it during a recent Dodgers press conference,
``Kevin Brown is one of those special, unique players that can
elevate a team and make them that much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to experts such as former Dodgers vice president
and general manager Fred Claire, there's a considerable downside
when teams begin paying astronomical amounts to some players and
peanuts to others. In fact, Brown, with his guaranteed $105
million, will make more than the cumulative payrolls of Cincinnati,
Florida, Minnesota, Montreal, Oakland and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The escalation has been so great over a relatively short
period of time that the biggest concern for baseball should be the
disparity of payrolls,'' Claire said. ``These are the things that
are not good for the game. The leaders better be careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem lies in the very key element of competitive
balance. Baseball is so far off course that it's not even pretty to
look at the tremendous disparity in team payrolls. The result is a
tremendous amount of disparity in the abilities of teams to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   In Malone's eyes, nothing is quite that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about money,'' he said. ``Money might be a part
of the problem, but a lot of the problem with some of these teams
is they haven't put the right personnel together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying it's the money that creates the disparity _ that's an
easy out. A lot of people can claim that. I had the lowest payroll
(as general manager) in Montreal in 1994 and I had the best team in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's not the answer to all the questions or solution to all
the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, higher salaries mean more costly tickets. In fact, both
the Dodgers and Angels have raised ticket prices for the 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   Claire, who will next month begin teaching a class at USC on
sports business and the media, said he is also worried about how
fans will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more important than the fan base,'' Claire
said. ``The last thing you want to do is have the fan in a position
where he cannot afford the game and he's turned off by the salaries
of the star players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of balance right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On that point, Malone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system we work with has no structure or guidelines,'' he
said. ``A general manager is asked to make the best team possible
and do it in a way that doesn't have a bad effect on the industry.
You try to do what's in the best interest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, my primary responsibility is to make the Dodgers
the best team possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love baseball as much as anybody in the game; I care about
it as much or more than anybody. If we don't sign Kevin Brown, does
that rectify the problems in the industry? No. I'm here to win.
Fortunately we have the resources to make the financial commitments
to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
