   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BELARUS (Moscow) _ The presidents of Russia and Belarus
said Friday that they intend to begin unifying their currencies and
much of their economies next year, an action stopping just short of
a political merger which would again extend Russian territory to
the border of Poland. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-OUTLOOK (Solo, Indonesia) _ Seven months after student
demonstrations toppled the country's longtime ruler, Indonesia
remains in precarious shape, with its economy in a shambles,
political reforms stalled and the student movement unappeased. A
Special Report by Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FIGHTING (Gornja Lapastica, Yugoslavia) _ The ethnic
Albanian commander in this region refused an offer that would stop
fighting in this part of northern Kosovo on Friday. Now, the chance
for more combat is high, Western diplomats say. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AMNESIAC (Toronto) _ What James Edward Brighton knows for
sure is that sometime after midnight on Oct. 12 he awoke in a
Montreal parking lot, naked, dazed and without a clue to who he was
or how he got there. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
