<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAREND-ANDERSON-COLU     12-26 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-ANDERSON-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the Olympics.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees also created a debate: Was this the best baseball
team ever? They rolled to a 114-48 record during the season; swept
the Texas Rangers in the division playoff, 3-0; eliminated the
Cleveland Indians in the American League Championship Series, 4-2,
and dominated the San Diego Padres in the World Series, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander David Wells pitched a perfect game during his
18-4 season, the right-hander David Cone was 20-7, Derek Jeter
sparkled at shortstop, the Cuban refugee Orlando (El Duque)
Hernandez was 12-4, center fielder Bernie Williams hit .339 for the
AL batting title. Darryl Strawberry underwent colon cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner was close to selling the Yankees to
Cablevision for a reported $600 million until he bragged about how
he would still control the operation of the team (and maybe the
Knicks and the Rangers too), prompting Charles Dolan to put the
negotiations on hold. The Los Angeles Dodgers were sold to Rupert
Murdoch for $311 million.
</P>
<P>
   When a 500-pound beam fell in Yankee Stadium, the Yankees had to
play one game at Shea in April. But Steinbrenner, although often
declaring that he would address the future of Yankee Stadium once
the season ended, has yet to discuss his plans publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In the National League, the Padres, relying on Brown, Tony Gwynn
and the slugger Greg Vaughn (who hit 50 homers), ousted Houston and
Atlanta in the playoffs. The Mets, who obtained the slugger Mike
Piazza in June, stayed in the wild-card race until the final
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza signed a seven-year, $91 million contract with the Mets
even before the frantic free-agent auctions. In addition to Brown's
$105 million deal, Williams returned to the Yankees for $87.5
million over seven years, Mo Vaughn moved to Anaheim for $80
million over six years, Albert Belle joined Baltimore for $65
million over five years and Randy Johnson went to Arizona for $52.4
million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood, the Cubs' 20-year-old rookie right-hander, struck
out 20 Astros, tying the major league record, Cal Ripken Jr. ended
his consecutive-game streak at 2,632, and the club owners
officially elected Allan (Bud) Selig as commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Denver Is Undone While Jets Fly to Top &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the first season of the National Football League's
eight-year, $17.6 billion television contracts, the Broncos arrived
in Giants Stadium at 13-0 with a chance to go 19-0 if they could
repeat as Super Bowl champions. But the Broncos were upset, 20-16,
and the Giants celebrated one of the most memorable victories in
their history. The 1972 Dolphins also celebrated; their 17-0 season
was still unique.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, with quarterback Vinny Testaverde throwing 25
touchdown passes going into Sunday's finale, soared into the
playoffs as a divisional champion. Curtis Martin, signed to a
six-year, $36 million deal, rushed for more than 1,000 yards; wide
receivers Wayne Chrebet and Keyshawn Johnson each caught passes for
more than 1,000 yards; Testaverde, Johnson, Mo Lewis and Aaron
Glenn made the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, weakened by the preseason loss of cornerback Jason
Sehorn to knee surgery, struggled until Coach Jim Fassel benched
quarterback Danny Kanell and used Kent Graham. With a 7-8 record
before Sunday's season finale, the Giants still had a playoff
chance, but they needed to win in Philadelphia while both Tampa Bay
and Arizona lost. Michael Strahan and Jessie Armstead made the Pro
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings, bolstered by the rookie wide receiver
Randy Moss and the comeback of quarterback Randall Cunningham,
jumped to a 14-1 record and the Atlanta Falcons were 13-2 as the
National Conference's best. Dan Reeves, the Falcons' coach, needed
heart-bypass surgery on Dec. 14, and returned to the hospital on
Dec. 20, but hoped to be on the sideline in the playoffs.
Controversial calls provoked a campaign to return instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut legislators voted to build a $375 million stadium in
Hartford that the New England Patriots plan to occupy in 2001, and
Al Lerner, a credit-card magnate, was chosen as owner of the
expansion Cleveland Browns franchise for $530 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under college football's new Bowl Championship Series format,
the University of Tennessee (12-0) and Florida State (11-1) were
selected for the Fiesta Bowl title game Jan. 4 that will determine
the successor to the mythical co-champions, Michigan and Nebraska.
But the worthiness of Ohio State (10-1), Kansas State (11-1) and
UCLA (10-1) had BCS critics demanding a playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Not Surprisingly, It's All About Michael &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls did what they have done six straight times when
Michael Jordan played a full season _ win the NBA title. In the
final, they muted the Utah Jazz in six games. But with the labor
dispute, Jordan has yet to announce if he will resume his career or
retire. Phil Jackson resigned as the Bulls' coach; Tim Floyd, from
Iowa State, succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, with Patrick Ewing out with a damaged shooting wrist
for most of their inconsistent 43-39 season, happily got past Miami
and the former Knick coach Pat Riley in the first round of the
playoffs. Larry Johnson and Heat center Alonzo Mourning were
suspended for the decisive fifth game after a fight that had Jeff
Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach, hanging onto one of Mourning's legs
on the Garden court.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, more rusty than ready, returned for the second game of
the series with Indiana, but the Pacers won in six, then forced the
Bulls to a Game 7 in the conference finals, enough to elect Larry
Bird as the coach of the year. The Nets, with Jayson Williams
averaging 14 rebounds, also had a 43-39 record in Coach John
Calipari's second season but drew the Bulls in the first round of
the playoffs, and were swept.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Latrell Sprewell, who had choked his Golden State
coach, P.J. Carlesimo, early in the season, appealed his one-year
NBA suspension and the Warriors' termination of his $28 million
contract. John Feerick, the NBA arbitrator, reduced the suspension
to seven months and restored the final three years of the contract.
Sprewell is expected to be traded after the lockout ends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
