<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAREND-ANDERSON-COLU     12-26 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-ANDERSON-COLUMN-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: lockout ends.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett, the Minnesota Timberwolves' 22-year-old forward
who skipped college, raised the NBA market, signing a seven-year,
$125 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   In college basketball, Kentucky, with its first African-American
coach, Tubby Smith, won its second national championship in three
years and its seventh over all with a 78-69 victory over Utah in
the title game. Antawn Jamison of North Carolina dominated the
player of the year awards. St. John's, after dismissing its coach,
Fran Fraschilla, hired Mike Jarvis, a longtime success at George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In women's pro basketball, the Houston Comets repeated as the
Women's National Basketball Association champions and the Columbus
Quest repeated as the American Basketball League champions, but the
ABL folded last Tuesday. The Comets defeated Phoenix, 2-1, in the
title series; their Cynthia Cooper repeated as the season's most
valuable player. The Quest won the decisive fifth game of its title
playoff with Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hasek Dominates, Street Overcomes Injury &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the first Olympic women's hockey tournament, the United
States edged Canada, 3-1, in the gold-medal game. The Czech
Republic, with goaltender Dominik Hasek dominating a 1-0 final over
Russia, won the men's tournament, which used National Hockey League
players for the first time. The United States team failed to
qualify for the medal round; some players then embarrassed
themselves by trashing a dorm room and declining to identify the
culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Picabo Street, skiing on a surgically rebuilt knee, won the gold
in the super-G by 0.01 seconds, the closest Alpine race in Olympic
history. Norway's Bjorn Dahlie won three cross-country gold medals,
boosting his career total to 12 medals, including eight golds.
After a spectacular spill in the downhill, Austria's Hermann Maier
skied to the gold in the giant slalom and the Super G.
</P>
<P>
   In the National Hockey League, the Dallas Stars had the most
regular-season points, 109, but the Red Wings repeated as Stanley
Cup champions, sweeping the Washington Capitals in the final. The
Devils, the Atlantic Division winner with 107 points, were put out
in the first round by the Ottawa Senators, prompting Coach Jacques
Lemaire to resign; Robbie Ftorek succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who were on a midseason treadmill to miss the
playoffs, changed coaches _ John Muckler replaced Colin Campbell.
The Islanders, who finished 2 points ahead of the Rangers,
evacuated the Nassau Coliseum before the current season in a
dispute with Nassau County officials. After firing Rick Bowness,
Mike Milbury has combined coaching the Islanders with his general
manager's duties and induced Ziggy Palffy back into uniform last
week for $5.5 million annually over five years.
</P>
<P>
   In boxing, Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis finally agreed to
unify the three heavyweight titles this March 13 in Madison Square
Garden. Holyfield retained the World Boxing Association and
International Boxing Federation belts with a 12-round decision over
Vaughn Bean; Lewis kept the World Boxing Council title by stopping
Andrew Golota and Shannon Briggs, and outpointing Zeljko Mavrovic.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Jones Jr., WBC and WBA light-heavyweight champion, and Oscar
de la Hoya, the WBC welterweight titleholder, remained undefeated
in their duel to be the best, pound for pound. Promoter Don King
was acquitted of insurance fraud in a retrial, but was sued for at
least $100 million in damages by Mike Tyson, who alleged that his
former promoter had bilked him of millions over the years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; World Cup Champs On the Champs-Elysees &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In golf's majors, Mark O'Meara won the Masters and the British
Open, Lee Janzen the United States Open and Fiji's Vijay Singh the
Professional Golfers' Association Championship. David Duval emerged
as the leading money winner with a record $2,591,031. In the
Presidents Cup team matches, the International pros trounced the
Americans, 20{-11{, at Royal Melbourne in Australia. Annika
Sorenstam was the women's tour's top money winner, with $1,092,748.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Novotna and Davenport, six other players won
Grand Slam tennis events: Pete Sampras at Wimbledon, Patrick Rafter
at the United States Open, Petr Korda and Martina Hingis at the
Australian Open, and the Spanish duo of Carlos Moya and Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario at the French Open. Sweden retained the Davis Cup,
but many of the world's best players disdained competing.
</P>
<P>
   At soccer's World Cup, France ignited a national celebration
with its 3-0 surprise of Brazil in the final. The United States
team had a disappointing 0-3 record, losing to Germany, Iran and
Yugoslavia for a quick return home. Steve Sampson was dismissed as
the United States coach; his successor is Bruce Arena, the coach of
the two-time Major League Soccer champion D.C. United, which lost
to Chicago in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Pantani, an Italian cyclist, won the Tour de France. A
drug scandal during the race embarrassed France, prompting a
campaign for a nine-member French state council, rather than the
cycling federation, to test and discipline riders.
</P>
<P>
   In thoroughbred racing, Real Quiet, trained by Bob Baffert, won
the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness, but his Triple Crown bid was
thwarted by Victory Gallop in a Belmont Stakes photo finish. Skip
Away, who approached Cigar's earnings record with nine straight
victories, loomed as the Horse of the Year. Muscles Yankee won
harness racing's Hambletonian, the fifth for the driver John
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who won 13 stock-car races, earned $9.3 million in
prize money and his third Winston Cup title. Eddie Cheever Jr. took
the Indianapolis 500; Greg Moore won the U.S. 500 in Michigan after
three spectators were killed when a wheel from a car sailed into
the stands. The Formula One title went to Finland's Mika Hakkinen.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones, the first woman in half a century to win three
individual events in the United States track and field
championships, swept the 100-meter and 200-meter dashes and the
long jump. For the season, she was undefeated in 35 events. John
Kagwe of Kenya and Franca Fiacconi of Italy shared the New York
Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   And in the year's sweetest snapshot, during the hometown parade
honoring the Toms River Little League champions from New Jersey,
12-year-old Chris Cardone, who hit the title-winning home run in
the 12-9 victory over Kashima, Japan, was the subject of a banner:
``Marry me, Chris Cardone. Love, Alexa.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexa Manforti was 7 years old.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
