<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Dec. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS-LUKASHENKO (Minsk, Belarus) _ For four long years,
President Alexander Lukashenko has pursued an unlikely obsession:
to raise tiny Belarus from the shards of the sundered Soviet Union
and remake it into a model socialist state. Lately, it seems he has
succeeded all too well. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-AMERICANS (Baghdad, Iraq) _ Officials in Washington say
that they have no quarrel with the Iraqi people and that the recent
bombing of Iraqi targets are aimed solely at President Saddam
Hussein and his regime. That argument rings hollow to many Iraqis.
Nonetheless, they are remarkably friendly to Americans who venture
here. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-CONDOMS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Out of the depths
of the AIDS epidemic sweeping Africa, an ugly truth is emerging:
Some condom makers have been dumping their substandard wares here
and Africans have been risking their lives on brittle, leaky or
ill-fitting condoms. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-CONGO (Gisenyi, Rwanda) _ Here in Rwanda's turbulent
northwest, there is evidence everywhere of the unfinished business
of the attempt in 1994 to kill every Tutsi in the country. Here too
is the best place to see why Rwanda is fighting so furiously in
Congo, why Rwanda helped spur a rebellion there in August that has
now widened into a war involving at least six outside nations. By
Ian Fisher. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-MENDES (Xapuri, Brazil) _ In his life, Francisco
``Chico'' Mendes, the outspoken defender of rubber tappers and the
Amazon rain forest, cut a larger figure around the globe than he
did around the corner. His murder at the age of 44, 10 years ago
this month, brought even more international attention to his cause.
A decade later, Mendes' Workers' Party has won control of city hall
and of the governor's palace in the state capital. By Diana Jean
Schemo. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-WOMAN-PRESIDENT (Bern, Switzerland) _ A profile of Ruth
Dreifuss, Switzerland's new president-elect _ the first woman and
first Jew to occupy the largely ceremonial top post. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   GEN-ZINNI-PROFILE (Prince Sultan Air Base, Saudi Arabia) _ Gen.
Anthony C. Zinni, a square-jawed, square-shouldered Marine, has
been in the middle of some of the nation's least traditional
military campaigns. As commander in chief of the U.S. Central
Command, Zinni oversees all American forces in a troubled region
that stretches from the Sudan to Pakistan. By Steven Lee Myers.
(With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Two of the last
three longtime aides of the late Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot, have
emerged from their jungle hideouts in the hope of becoming
``ordinary citizens,'' the government announced Saturday. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-QUEEN (Toronto) _ Canada has its queen and, as some
politicians are discovering, God save those who would try to sever
the country from its monarch. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CODE-WARRIORS _ Tens of thousands of programmers throughout
the world are racing to head off the havoc that could ensue because
many of the computers that underpin today's wired society do not
understand that a year can begin with a number other than 19. By
Barnaby J. Feder and Andrew Pollack. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-SALARIES (Bedford, Mass.) _ The old rule _ that a
strong economy enables a strong military _ has twisted in the
current gale of prosperity. An economy this strong, with
unemployment this low, becomes an impediment to the military's
efforts to recruit and retain soldiers. In Defense Secretary
William Cohen's words, ``It's very hard to compete against a robust
economy such as we have.'' By Carey Goldberg. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   ALPHA-CHRISTIANS (Woonsocket, R.I.) _ A look at the Alpha
course, a novel approach to Christian education that seeks to
introduce newcomers to the Christian faith and to re-establish ties
with wayward parishioners through a 10-week videotaped crash course
in the basics of Christianity. By Tom Verde. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ROSE-PARADE (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Here in the shaded glades
of live oaks and, yes, December roses, one of California's oldest
civic traditions lives on in these cold nights and crisp mornings.
This is the place where thousands of square feet of chicken wire,
hundreds of gallons of glue and acres of seeds, plants and flowers
somehow become the Tournament of Roses Parade each New Year's Day.
By Todd S. Purdum. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-REALITIES (Washington) _ As the Clinton administration
finishes drawing up its tax and spending proposals for the next
fiscal year, it is confronting the perplexing but painful reality
that despite mounting federal budget surpluses there is little
money for new programs, and some areas could face cuts. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ When, as now seems likely, William
Rehnquist, the chief justice of the United States, opens the
impeachment trial of President Clinton early next year, there will
be no time devoted to jury selection. Nor will the jury be
impartial. By Alison Mitchell. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Rarely has a new Congress had
its future shaped so firmly by its predecessor. With only a few
days left of its old life, the 105th Congress seems to have frozen
the early agenda and tone of the 106th. By Adam Clymer. (With a
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INFECTIOUS-DISEASE (Washington) _ President Clinton will soon
propose a $25 million initiative to combat the spread of infectious
diseases, including virulent new strains of microbes that resist
treatment by antibiotics and other drugs, administration officials
said Saturday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On New Year political retreats. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ On the resurgence of New York's Jets. By bob
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
