<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Sunday, Dec. 27, Page 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Supervisor is
Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail: hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-REALITIES (Washington) _ As the Clinton administration
finishes drawing up its tax and spending proposals for the next
fiscal year, it is confronting the perplexing but painful reality
that despite mounting federal budget surpluses there is little
money for new programs, and some areas could face cuts. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 12:15 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CODE-WARRIORS _ Tens of thousands of programmers throughout
the world are racing to head off the havoc that could ensue because
many of the computers that underpin today's wired society do not
understand that a year can begin with a number other than 19. By
Barnaby J. Feder and Andrew Pollack. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BELARUS-LUKASHENKO (Minsk, Belarus) _ For four long years,
President Alexander Lukashenko has pursued an unlikely obsession:
to raise tiny Belarus from the shards of the sundered Soviet Union
and remake it into a model socialist state. Lately, it seems he has
succeeded all too well. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-AMERICANS (Baghdad, Iraq) _ Officials in Washington say
that they have no quarrel with the Iraqi people and that the recent
bombing of Iraqi targets are aimed solely at President Saddam
Hussein and his regime. That argument rings hollow to many Iraqis.
Nonetheless, they are remarkably friendly to Americans who venture
here. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   THEME-RESTAURANT-DECLINE (New York) _ Theme restaurants, which
exploded across the urban skyline three or four years ago with
promises of untold profits from a slickly packaged blend of eating,
shopping and entertainment, are collapsing. Even former Wall Street
favorites like Hard Rock Cafe, Planet Hollywood and Rainforest Cafe
have seen sales tumble as diners go elsewhere. By Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-CONDOMS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Out of the depths
of the AIDS epidemic sweeping Africa, an ugly truth is emerging:
Some condom makers have been dumping their substandard wares here
and Africans have been risking their lives on brittle, leaky or
ill-fitting condoms. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
