<HEADLINE>
NFL OPENS A PATH FOR BLACK COACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League is currently taking its most
drastic _ and some say productive _ steps ever to correct what is
viewed as one of the biggest problems facing professional football:
the lack of black head coaches and coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   The key part of the league's new attack on an old obstacle is a
pilot project in which an independent consulting company will
videotape interviews of selected assistant coaches, most of them
black, who have been recommended by teams as having high potential
to become head coaches and coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews will be conducted in the next several weeks.
Tapes of the interviews, along with accompanying resumes, will
serve as a sort of coaching database and be available to any team
in search of top coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, approved by the eight owners, general managers and
coaches of the league's competition committee, is to introduce
owners and team executives to new faces.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue wrote this month to the presidents
of the NFL's 31 teams about the new initiatives. In the memo,
obtained by The New York Times from a team executive, Tagliabue
wrote that the league was simply trying to identify ``a deep and
diverse talent pool'' for head coaching and coordinator positions.
Tagliabue has also met with some owners to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically the commissioner is trying to encourage teams to be
fair,'' said one team executive, who asked not to be identified.
``The league is taking some very good steps here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently three black head coaches in the NFL:
Philadelphia's Ray Rhodes, Minnesota's Dennis Green and Tampa Bay's
Tony Dungy. Rhodes, whose team can finish no better than 4-12, is
considered likely to be fired at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, there have been more than two dozen
head coaching vacancies, and none has been filled by an
African-American. Last year, the NFL was roundly criticized when
retread white coaches, like Dick Vermeil in St. Louis and Jim Mora
in Indianapolis, were hired instead of black coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the NFL is taking new measures to try to change the
situation, with one owner saying the ideas have the potential to
``put fairness back in the NFL's hiring practices.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the pilot project, the NFL spent months speaking
to teams about potential candidates and recorded hundreds of names.
The league office then whittled down the group to some 20 to 30
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the program is for owners to become familiar with
candidates they might otherwise know little about, which is why
former NFL coaches and current college coaches are excluded from
this phase. Although the project is aimed at black coaches, white
coaches will also participate.
</P>
<P>
   Each interview will focus on the candidate's background,
experience and general philosophy, but will not involve more
detailed questions on the technical aspects of coaching or the
circumstances of particular NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   According to several owners and team executives, some coaches
who may take part in the program include the Giants' defensive
coordinator, John Fox, who is white; the Giants' defensive backs
coach, Johnnie Lynn; Oakland's defensive coordinator, Willie Shaw,
and the Jets' running backs coach, Maurice Carthon, all of whom are
black. There is also interest in Sam Clancy, the black defensive
line coach of NFL Europe's Barcelona Dragons, who has coached for
three different NFL teams under the league's internship program.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Reynolds Associates, a New York company that helps
corporations find candidates for top management jobs, will conduct
the hourlong interviews. Some black coaches under consideration in
the past have complained that they were poorly interviewed, and
teams have complained that some black coaches have interviewed
poorly, so the league hopes to standardize the process.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL does not expect a team to hire a coach based solely on
the video interview, but the tapes will serve to provide valuable
basic information and introduce people who otherwise might not have
been considered.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue wrote in his memo to the team presidents that he
believed the current initiative would provide ``a confidential and
reliable means of expanding the hiring process.'' But he said the
ultimate decision on hiring ``will and must remain with those clubs
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   If the pilot project is considered successful, more coaches will
be asked to participate next year.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent face-to-face talks with some of the league's
owners, Tagliabue asked those who may be looking for a head coach
at the end of the year not to rush into a decision, according to
several owners.
</P>
<P>
   In his Dec. 21 memo, Tagliabue wrote: ``It is essential that the
league and all member clubs make every effort to have a process
that is credible with your coaching employees as well as fans, the
media and other interested observers. We must have a process that
is consistent with commonly accepted notions of proper business
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials, as they had done before, recently sought the
advice of black assistant coaches themselves on how to correct the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Will the latest attempts by the NFL help? There is optimism
among some black assistants that at least one of the 6 to 10 head
coaching positions that could open up after this season might be
filled by one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some things here that could finally begin to
solve this issue, which is complicated,'' said one assistant coach
in the National Football Conference. ``I finally see some hope. The
commissioner deserves a lot of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Upping the Ante &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills are rethinking how they provide security at
Ralph Wilson Stadium after a series of incidents during last week's
game against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Three fans ran onto the field during the game, and there were
some 20 arrests because of fights in the stands. The Bills already
have more security officials at games than almost any other team,
but a lawyer for the team, Vincent Tobia, told The Buffalo News
that even more may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sympathetic to fans who come to our games as a family
and have to put up with drunks, swearing and fighting in the
stands,'' Tobia said.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium security seems to pop up as an issue every few years. At
Giants Stadium on Dec. 23, 1995, fans threw rock-hard snowballs
onto the field at San Diego Chargers players, coaches and trainers.
That led to the announcement by the Giants that rowdy fans risked
losing their season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No Security &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Across the NFL, coaches _ and not just head coaches _ are
worrying about their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, if Bears Coach Dave Wannstedt is fired, his 10
assistants will in all probability be fired too. Six of them are
signed only through this season, including the offensive line
coach, Tony Wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain situations where guys, if something happens,
are willing to go from one spot to the next,'' said Wise. ``I feel
very comfortable here. That has made it strenuous personally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
