<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SHARPE-AZR &LR;      12-26 3165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SHARPE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYERS HELP HEAL WOUNDS OF EX-CARDINAL  
 EX-NFL PLAYER LUIS SHARPE TRIES TO BOUNCE BACK FROM THE DEPTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, ARIZ. - The woman took a seat, looking into the eyes
of Luis Sharpe as he began to ask questions. Only 18, she looked as
if she had seen too much. As a kid, she wanted to be a
pediatrician, but she was at the Love in Action Ministries in
Glendale earlier this month asking for only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe asked for her hands, and they disappeared into those that
held off some of the NFL's fiercest pass rushers for 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in pressed blue jeans and denim shirt, Sharpe, a former
star offensive tackle with the Cardinals, bowed his head and prayed
with her.
</P>
<P>
   As he led her to the ministry's food storage room, the scene was
a blending of heartbreak and joy.
</P>
<P>
   The last images that many have of Sharpe, now 38, are from a
June day in 1996 _ in handcuffs, on a gurney, bleeding from a
gunshot wound that entered under his chin and exited his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Addicted to crack cocaine, Sharpe had suffered his second
gunshot wound during a dispute in a crack house on Broadway Road.
</P>
<P>
   You don't notice the physical scars today unless you look
closely. The emotional wounds have been mostly healed, too, he
said. Conversations with Sharpe today are punctuated with biblical
references, praises to God and parables. With every sentence, he
bears witness.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sharpe _ emerging from the depths of drug abuse, the brink
of death and prison, and a drug relapse _ is a productive member of
society again.
</P>
<P>
   He will spend today with his five children, first at Christmas
services, later opening presents. It is a day some thought Sharpe
would never live to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe knows that many people have grown callous to news of drug
addicts finding religion, or a former professional athlete slipping
up and then trying to turn his life around. The skeptics will ask,
how long will this transformation last?
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe said he is willing to share his story not because he
wants applause, but because he wants people to know there is hope,
even when everything known to man has failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the only thing we can do is pray for people and
believe that what is impossible for man is possible for God,'' he
said. &QL; 
A sudden downfall
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's playing career ended in 1994 because of a knee injury,
prompting the infamous post-game quote from Coach Buddy Ryan, ``We
ain't got anybody hurt that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's life had seemed so perfect until then. He had a degree
in political science from UCLA. He was a member of the executive
board of the NFL players union. He was the Cardinals' marquee
player.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the facade, Sharpe's soul was crumbling. He had used
crack cocaine intermittently for years while in the NFL, mainly he
says, because he was doing nothing to nurture his spirit and
relationship with God. His marriage was failing.
</P>
<P>
   And then, the injury signaled an end to his career. He was in
despair, and he found his escape in cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, he said, most of his drug use was done in the
off-season. When he smoked crack during the season, he said he did
it mostly on Monday nights because Tuesday was the players' day
off.
</P>
<P>
   After his knee injury, the addiction became uncontrollable.
Although he had retired from the game, the next two years of
Sharpe's life were chronicled in court documents and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence, arrests, fights with police officers,
involuntary psychiatric treatment, several rehabilitation attempts,
two gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   He was placed on probation for drug and assault charges as part
of a plea deal with the Maricopa County Attorney's Office, but he
violated that probation in that summer of 1996 and ultimately spent
10{ months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He currently is under a 35-month probation period, which for now
includes house arrest. Sharpe must submit a weekly schedule to his
probation officer, Charles Medrano, whose office monitors Sharpe's
activities. In addition, Sharpe is randomly tested for drug use. He
has been clean since last spring when he entered a rehabilitation
program operated by the In Him Outreach Church in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing real well,'' Medrano said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe blames no one but himself for his descent into the abyss
of drug abuse, and for a brief relapse earlier this year. He
credits only one thing for leading him out: God's grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some heart issues, things that happened to me, people
who had let me down, and I had a hard time forgiving those
people,'' he said. ``I was carrying a lot of pain in my heart, and
I didn't know all I had to do was give my life to the Lord and walk
in forgiveness. Walk in forgiveness!''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe and his ex-wife, Kathi, communicate and are still working
through the pain of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new person; this is not the person that I knew,''
Kathi Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is a changed man, and he traces the transformation
back to the summer of 1996 when he was shot for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of several forces, some of which he cannot
explain, have brought him to where he says he is today: a man of
God who spends most of his days volunteering at Love in Action and
at the In Him Outreach Church; a loving son and a father who has
rebuilt relationships with his five children, who range in age from
14 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't claim to have conquered his addiction. He fell back
into that world earlier this year, he said, using drugs for a
three-week period. He then entered a treatment program, from which
he graduated last month.
</P>
<P>
   Beating drug addiction, along with the continuing development of
his faith, is part of a process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that he now has people he can talk to, people such as
his pastor, David Vasquez, and Patricia Eckhardt, the director of
the Love in Action Ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called them my spiritual parents,'' Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still bumps, trials and tribulations along the
road,'' he said. ``However, those bumps no longer represent
stumbling blocks. They are merely steppingstones that allow me to
grow more and more in faith.'' &QL; 
Angels of mercy &QL; 
Lying on a gurney in the emergency room of Maricopa Medical Center,
Sharpe was choking on his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in the neck during a dispute at a crack house, he had
fought with police officers, who finally subdued him and brought
him in for treatment. Sharpe, in critical condition, had a vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, I feel these literal, physical hands on my
body from my ankles to the top of my shoulders,'' he said. ``They
were like the hands of death. I felt the spirit of death come upon
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then coming around the corner into the room, I see this man
who has on all black and he has a nightstick in his hand, and he's
beating it on the other hand. He's standing at my feet, and I'm
trying to figure this out. I look up and see this man in all white.
He says, `Now we put our faith in the one we believe.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really trippin' now. I don't understand this at all. I
can't speak because I'm choking on blood. He says it again, `Now we
put our faith in the one we believe.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I nodded my head yes, and he put his hand where I got shot,
right here,'' said Sharpe, placing his finger under his chin. ``And
I remember him saying, `Everyone in this room who doesn't belong
here, leave immediately.' Those hands lifted off my body and I felt
the gurney carrying me out of the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Sharpe was on his way to a jail infirmary. He
started thinking about what had led him to this cell, how his story
was being told in the newspapers and on television, how his
children would see Daddy's latest failure on television and hear
about it from classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to seriously contemplate suicide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adele Harris, the Cardinals' community relations director, came
to visit Sharpe about then. She was stunned at what she saw and
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried,'' she said. ``He had been such a strong individual. I
don't mean in football, but he knew where he was going. He had
direction. But he just sounded so down. He was saying things like,
`I'll be all right' and `Does it really matter?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frightened for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe frightened himself. On a Sunday, he summoned a guard and
told him he was having suicidal thoughts and needed to see a
psychiatrist. The guard told him he'd try, but it was Sunday, and
it might take a while.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, the Rev. Timothy Tuggle was waiting for
Sharpe. Tuggle had seen Sharpe's story on the television the night
before and decided to visit.
</P>
<P>
   He told Sharpe that he had a purpose for living, that one day he
would bring ``thousands into the kingdom of God.'' They prayed, and
Sharpe went back to his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to sleep and woke up the next morning and the spirit of
depression and suicide had left me and I was full of joy,'' Sharpe
said. A few weeks later, Sharpe was sentenced to a year in prison
for violating his probation. He served 10{ months before being
released in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to a man who had everything the world had to
offer, materially, socially, financially, and you know what?''
Sharpe said. ``It took me having my physical freedom taken away to
be set free from myself. In prison, I had more joy, more peace. I
knew I was on a different path.'' &QL; 
Lending a hand &QL; 
Larry Lee's eyes began to mist. A friend of Sharpe's since they
were teammates at UCLA in the late 1970s and early '80s, he
couldn't help but get emotional when he heard Sharpe address a
crowd at his sister's wedding last summer in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, with the blessing of his sister and brother-in-law, just
wanted to thank everyone for their offers of help during his
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Lee watched as Sharpe's oldest daughter, 14-year-old
Leah, hugged her dad. A couple of her sisters, Sarah and Rebekah,
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Lee thought back to the time in 1995 when Sharpe was in trouble
and he visited Sharpe's ex-wife and the kids. Leah was shouting
that she hated her father for everything he had done.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception, Sharpe came over to where Lee was and saw that
his ex-teammate was crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we both started,'' said Lee, the vice president of
football administration for the Detroit Lions. ``Two big old guys
just boo-hooing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee had never lost hope that day would come.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Day 1, I saw it as plain as day,'' he said. ``I saw Luis
have a testimony, and I saw this public gathering, and he was the
highlight, and there wasn't a dry eye in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sharpe's life spun out of control with drugs and violence
in 1995, Lee conspired with former Cardinals wide receiver Roy
Green to try to help Sharpe. Lee flew to Phoenix and, with Green's
help, bound Sharpe with duct tape and drove him to the Betty Ford
Clinic in California.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Sharpe left, paying $1,800 for a cab ride to
take him back to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's brother, a minister, had some advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we want to help people out, and sometimes we block
God's blessing,'' Lee said. ``Some people have to hit rock bottom
before the Lord can perform a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee stopped helping the day before Thanksgiving 1995. He spoke
to Sharpe and could tell his teammate was ``probably still out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Both knew well the toll the drug could take. They and several
other former UCLA players had attended the funeral of former
teammate Don Rogers, who died of an overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Lee snapped and started screaming into the phone. ``Luis, the
next thing we'll be coming to Phoenix for is your funeral. All the
UCLA guys will be coming together in Phoenix. Just go ahead, Luis,
die, man! Go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Sharpe's family who live in Detroit flew to Phoenix
numerous times to help. Harris kept in touch with Kathi Sharpe and
the kids to make sure they were doing as well as possible. And
strangers were thinking of Sharpe, also.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw news broadcasts of Sharpe on a gurney, Pastor
Vasquez of the In Him Outreach Church grabbed his wife's hand and
prayed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord God, send somebody to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Love in Action Ministries, Eckhardt and some other
volunteers did the same. They saw the television reports and prayed
that Sharpe would find help.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe was released from prison in April 1997, about the same
time his divorce became final. He maintained his sobriety for a
while before his relapse.
</P>
<P>
   Through another minister, he was referred to Vasquez, who runs a
drug rehabilitation home in Glendale, and he entered the nine-month
program last spring. &QL; 
In search of forgiveness
</P>
<P>
   The In Him Outreach Home in Glendale accommodates 12 men who
share four bedrooms. It's a tight fit, especially after some of the
men recover from withdrawal and start eating well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in skinny and get big,'' Vasquez said. ``We have to
get them down from the top bunks to the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   The men rise early, and lights are out at 10 p.m. It's not a
prison; they are free to walk out any time. But if they commit to
the program, they must earn the privilege of leaving the home. They
pray, study the Bible, and they work.
</P>
<P>
   The men do volunteer work at Love in Action twice a week and are
involved in the neighborhood, sometimes helping do work for older
people.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to help a man forgive himself and view himself as
worthwhile. Drug habits are kicked through prayer, Bible study and
fellowship. The men in the program attend services regularly at the
In Him Outreach Church, located in a vacant store in the Manistee
Town Center at 57th and Northern avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into a home with several other men was not easy for
Sharpe, who made $1.8 million in his last season with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to submit yourself to living where there are 14, 15
men,'' he said. ``That's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But the home provided what he needed: the opportunity to be
around men of God for 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you hit bottom, and when people lose confidence in you,
you lose just about everything,'' Vasquez said. ``He needed
somebody to be real with him, to put a mirror in front of him, but
with love and compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Sharpe was willing to look at the image staring back.
</P>
<P>
   ``God had great things prepared for me, and as long as I held on
to bitterness and resentment, I couldn't see them,'' he said.
``Talking about Buddy Ryan, talking about the end of a marriage,
talking about the end of an NFL career. Those were the issues I was
dealing with and that I didn't know how to deal with at the time.
That's the reason I was out there doing those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who I was. For 13 years in the NFL, I was always driven
by my fleshly, carnal nature, by whatever felt good. Whether that
was in my diet, in hanging out in the streets and doing the things
professional athletes do when you're in the limelight and women
make themselves available to you. I did very little for my
spiritual man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe graduated from the program a month ago in a celebration
attended by friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   He's living in a house in Ahwatukee now so he can be close to
his kids.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, he hopes to attend a school in Tulsa in order to
become a minister. &QL; 
Feeding the spirit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Love in Action, Sharpe does a little bit of everything. He
speaks fluent Spanish, having been born in Cuba and immigrating to
the United States with his family when he was 6. The second
language is often an asset in interviewing those asking for help to
assess their need.
</P>
<P>
   He loads and unloads trucks and occasionally drives one to pick
up donations. He cleans toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to say, `I'm above that,' '' Eckhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't know who Sharpe was that first day he arrived with
the other men from the In Him home. She knew him only as Brother
Luis.
</P>
<P>
   One day, another volunteer told her who Sharpe was, and Eckhardt
remembered her prayer the night she saw pictures of a wounded
Sharpe on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so unbelievable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe has always had compassion for the less fortunate. Harris,
the Cardinals' community relations director, remembers that when
the Cardinals were still in St. Louis, Sharpe would walk by her
desk occasionally and overhear her talking to someone in need.
</P>
<P>
   One time, a woman with kids called, asking for money to pay her
heating bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would reach into his pocket and pull out a $100 bill,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On an average day, about 50 families are helped at Love in
Action. Volunteers are working now to fill the needs of 150
families for the holidays. That includes food, clothing and toys
for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their situations are heartbreaking. If interviewers
determine that a family requires special attention, or additional
assistance beyond the norm, they'll write ``blessing'' on an
information card.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers tease Sharpe because he writes that word so often.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not at 51st and Orangewood during the day, chances are
Sharpe is at the In Him Outreach Church. He operates the church's
sound system and makes recordings of sermons that are distributed
to members of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   He sees his children three or four times a week and has become a
big part of their lives again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at it, it didn't just happen to him, it happened
to my whole family,'' Kathi Sharpe said. ``It was difficult at that
time to see the end of the tunnel. We just hung in there and
figured it couldn't get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his troubles, Sharpe managed to stay financially sound.
A court order allowed him access to just $5,000 a month. Today, the
children are well taken care of, and Sharpe said he really doesn't
need to work.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe knows the pain he caused his family. ``I heard a saying
once,'' he said. ``A king's character permeates his kingdom. While
I was out there living life disobediently and recklessly my
children were suffering.'' &QL; 
Looking ahead &QL; 
Cynics will say Sharpe's conversion won't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``In God's infinite wisdom, he prepared me for this time, when
he knew people would doubt my sincerity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having played for the Cardinals . . .,'' he added, laughing,
``one of the things I found myself doing was refuting those
negative reports, to always have hope and believe in myself and our
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   He has plans for the future. He would like to minister to
athletes, many of whom he believes are struggling as he did.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Luis Sharpe friends and family know. Strong-willed
and determined. A man with a vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mystery of the gospel is that God will use imperfect
vessels to preach or spread a perfect gospel,'' he said. ``I
believe that as a Christian man, my failures are my successes. They
represent the miracle that I survived.'' &QL; 
Kent Somers can be reached at 444-8335 or at kent.somers(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
