r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-WRITERS-LADN     12-26 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-WRITERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD A TOUGH TOWN FOR AGING WRITERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- This is not your father's Hollywood, not for
writers over 40, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place where you really begin to notice that you're too old
is at the meeting level when you're pitching,'' said 50-year-old
Larry DiTillio, who began working in Hollywood in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell right away that these guys, who are in their 20s
and 30s, are not interested. From their standpoint, it's like their
father walked into the meeting. Do you really want to work with
your father for an extended period?''
</P>
<P>
   For 81-year-old Oliver Crawford, who survived blacklisting to
earn credits on ``Perry Mason'' and other top shows, there's little
interest in grandfather-aged writers, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were not interested in me when they began to call
me Mr. Crawford. Everyone had always called me Ollie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contemporaries are either retired or dead. The trouble is
that science is doing what it can to keep guys like me alive but
the business is telling me, hey, you've had it.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Writers Guild of America, the union that
represents TV scriptwriters and movie screenwriters, found that
many producers definitely don't want to work with their fathers,
especially in television. Professors William and Denise Bielby
described an increasingly bleak outlook for older writers and
disclosed that 77 series last season had no writers over 50 and
half a dozen, including ``Friends'' and ``Veronica's Closet,'' had
no writers over 40.
</P>
<P>
   Older writers find they're being excluded not just from the
plethora of shows aimed at adolescents but also from adult-oriented
shows. ``The executives have really convinced themselves if you're
50, you can't write sharp dialogue anymore for something like `NYPD
Blue,' '' said Steven Lord, who has over 200 writing credits.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's discrimination against older writers, though
illegal, is nothing new. The issue began to receive notice in the
early 1990s when a documentary, ``Power and Fear: the Hollywood
Grey List,'' compared the problem with Hollywood's blacklists of
the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, conditions have deteriorated. Some writers have even
taken the same steps as aging actors and actresses -- dyeing their
hair, lying about their age and obliterating credits more than a
decade old. And much like Woody Allen's character in the 1976 movie
``The Front,'' some enlist a younger relative or friend to act as a
partner during pitch meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Why are older writers pushed out of the way? The short answer
lies with Hollywood's legendary obsession with youth and its
pursuit of the next Steven Spielberg or Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a 32-year-old writer-actress named Kimberlee Kramer
felt the need to change her name to the now-notorious Riley Weston.
She passed herself off as a 19-year-old in order to get hired for
``Felicity'' as part of a $300,000 deal and was quoted saying
things like, ``In many ways, I am Felicity.'' When Kramer's
subterfuge became public in October, no one expressed any surprise
that a writer had pretended to be someone 13 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   What's particularly troubling for older writers is the attention
and resources lavished on young and mostly untested writers.
Earlier this month, 20th Century Fox TV announced a three-year deal
worth at least $2 million annually for 25-year-old Seth MacFarlane,
creator of Fox's yet-to-be launched animated comedy ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Older writers acknowledge that the brutal competition in their
field, where there are literally warehouses full of unproduced
scripts, makes working in Hollywood among the most ephemeral
occupations. They know that when producers say things like ``This
show skews younger'' and ``Do you think you can write about younger
people?'' it's time to find another line of work.
</P>
<P>
   Because what the producer is really saying is this -- ``If this
show flops, at least they won't be able to accuse me of hiring
someone who can't cut the mustard anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON 2ND TAKE) &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
