<HEADER>
A7038 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-WRITERS-2ndTAKE     12-26 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-WRITERS-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
LOS ANGELES: mustard anymore.'' Still, writers admit it's a jolt to go from hot to cold in
seemingly just a few weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I worked with some consistency until there was a noticeable
drop off about a dozen years ago,'' said Crawford, the 81-year-old
veteran writer whose credits date back to the so-called Golden Age
of television, including such shows as ``Kraft Theater,'' ``Perry
Mason,'' ``Wagon Train'' and ``The Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford is one of the few writers who managed to resurrect his
career after four years on the Hollywood blacklist, but that no
longer matters much, he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound whiny because my credits are really
old-hat credits and they don't carry very much weight,'' he said at
his house in the Fairfax District.
</P>
<P>
   Writers say anti-age attitudes are not as severe in the film
side of Hollywood, where a fairly small group of A-list writers
dominate no matter what their age if they continue to deliver box
office success. But the number of writing jobs for major studio
film projects has stopped growing and the Bielby report showed
several disturbing trends:
</P>
<P>
   --Median earnings for film writers over 40 have been lower than
for younger writers in every year since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   --Median earnings for film writers in their 30s have increased
more since 1991 than for any other age group and were the highest
for that group last year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more frustrating for older writers is having to
read about prodigies like Brandon Camp, 27, and Mike Thompson, 29.
Although both were neophytes, their ``Steinbeck's Point of View''
script sold for $750,000; after Tom Cruise expressed interest, the
duo's agent negotiated a three-picture deal that could pay them as
much as $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Marcus, who won an Emmy for writing on ``Mary Hartman, Mary
Hartman,'' said anti-age attitudes have grown to the point that
they permeate Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prejudice against older writers is sort of like the
weather -- everyone talks about it but no one does anything about
it,'' she said. ``The basic message is that if you're over 50, you
should get into real estate or write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, who worked into her late 60s and then spent the last two
years writing a book about her career called ``Whistling Girl,''
believes the problem is worst for baby boomers in their 40s and 50s
because they're partly to blame for the current glorification of
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the children of boomers who are in charge now,'' she
noted. ``In this business, you tend to hire your buddies and
working on a show is very much like being in a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Many writers over 40 don't want to talk about age
discrimination, saying that going public would ruin their already
shaky chances for work. About half of the 8,200 members of the
Writers Guild of America, west, work regularly; last year, 260
members lost their right to vote on contracts and in elections
because they had not been able to find work in a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who make decisions on using writers are so
scared,'' said one Emmy-winning writer who is still working.
``They're not concerned about the quality of the shows. It's all
about saving their own behind by going with what's tried and
true.''
</P>
<P>
   George Kirgo, a former guild president who led a five-month
strike in 1988, said conditions have worsened in recent years due
to the networks' obsession with younger audiences. ``You get to 45
and forget it,'' said the 72-year-old Kirgo. ``They don't think
that anyone my age can write a show that skews to a younger age.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirgo's credits include an early episode of ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show'' called ``The Forty-Five-Year-Old Man,'' in which WJM
fires Lou Grant because he's too old. The show has an upbeat ending
with Mary Richards arranging for Lou to get his job back, but Kirgo
is pessimistic about his own prospects. Several years ago, he
pitched a movie of the week idea to his agent, who took it to a
network executive. ``Kirgo's too old,'' the executive told the
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even been trying to get TV anymore so I've been
working on movies, books and charity work,'' Kirgo said. ``I think
a lot of older writers find it unbecoming to write for TV but they
still have to earn a living. And they want it to be their decision
when they stop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(CONTINUES ON 3RD TAKE) &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-WRITERS-3rdTAKE     12-26 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-WRITERS-3rdTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
LOS ANGELES: They stop. No one claims that older writers have been entirely shut out of
Hollywood. CBS's ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' for example, employed
one writer under 40 last season of the 15 it used; all 11 writers
on ``Dellaventura'' were over 40.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burbank-based literary agent Judy Coppage, who specializes in
using older writers, believes that the problems for many older
writers reflect mostly the ferociously competitive landscape and
its economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have writers in their 20s, 30s, 40s, 50s, 60s and 70s,''
said Coppage, who's 53 and married to a gerontologist. ``So there
are six decades of writers competing for not that many slots.
Producers are going to hire younger writers because they're going
to be less expensive. A writing career doesn't last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The guild's statistics show that a decade ago, nearly half of
writers registered with the guild and in their 50s worked; now,
only a third do. For writers in their 60s, the percentages have
gone from 40 percent in 1988 to 19 percent in 1998. That means
hundreds of writers are left with little to do but collect residual
checks from shows that aired in an era when writers in their 40s
and 50s dominated the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strongly held belief among executives that once
you're past 40, you're not with it anymore and your brain just
dies,'' declared Irma Kalish, whose credits include ``My Three
Sons,'' ``Family Affair'' and ``All in the Family.'' ``And I think
they feel more comfortable with their peer group, so they can do
things like play poker or play golf together.''
</P>
<P>
   So older writers usually lop years off their resumes.
``Unfortunately, I didn't, because I thought my early credits would
help but all they do is date you,'' said Kalish, who admits she
recently brought her 40-year-old son along on a pitch meeting.
``He's an excellent writer.''
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind the youth-obsessed strategy is largely
economic: What a network charges for advertisements depends more on
how many young adults it attracts. So even though ``Felicity''
reaches a mere 5.5 million viewers and ranks 99th among prime-time
shows, it is universally regarded as a success because it draws
large numbers of 18-to-34-year-old women.
</P>
<P>
   William Bielby, a professor of sociology at the University of
California, Santa Barbara, who has compiled the discrimination
reports for the guild for the past decade, began to notice a rapid
deterioration for older writers coincident with the rise of Fox in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratings began getting done very differently at that point,
with much more detailed reporting on demographics,'' Bielby said.
``Fox was able to capitalize on it because that was the group
advertisers were most interested in reaching. So networks felt they
had to rely on younger writers.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a widely held belief that the executives who make
the hiring decisions are doing so out of a peculiar logic -- it's
perfectly OK for a writer to be churning out scripts when he or she
is under 40, but once they reach that age, they ought to be
directing or producing in addition to writing.
</P>
<P>
   Bielby noted that focusing on youthful prodigies and freezing
out all others occurs elsewhere, such as in advertising or
architecture. ``People say that you have to get into management in
your mid-40s or you plateau and don't have much of a future,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry DiTillio agrees, saying, ``The age issue is an issue in
every business; it's just become more apparent in this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindi Brooks, who left TV writing eight years ago to become a
successful playwright, said being old is more of an obstacle for
her than being a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked very steadily for 14 years and a lot of the time I
was the only woman or one of the first to get in,'' recalls Brooks,
whose credits include ``Little House on the Prairie,'' ``The
Waltons,'' ``Eight Is Enough'' and ``Fame.'' ``But when the gray
hair started to show, I was out. I didn't want to go the route of
dyeing my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(CONTINUES ON 4TH TAKE) &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
