<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-WRITERS-4thTAKE     12-26 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-WRITERS-4thTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
LOS ANGELES: my hair.'' What's particularly infuriating to older writers is how completely
unembarrassed Hollywood is over freezing them out. They often point
to a 1996 interview given by producer Gary David Goldberg about
``Spin City'' in which he asserted, ``Don't send me any writers
over 29.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldberg did not respond to a request for comment and veteran
sitcom writer Norman Belkin said executives feel no need to
apologize over that attitude. ``The networks have made their choice
and they're comfortable with it,'' he added. ``Right now, the most
attractive people in Hollywood are 30-year-old Harvard and Yale
graduates with MBAs.''
</P>
<P>
   The older writers try not to sound bitter. But the most enraging
part of the Bielby report for them comes from the cold economic
fact that writers in their 30s are getting paid more than any other
group while earnings have declined for those over 40. That's an
astounding shift from a decade ago, when writers in their 40s and
50s commanded the top paychecks, usually after long years of
building up their reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that it was the young writers who couldn't get
work, so the pendulum has definitely swung the other way,'' Kalish
said. ``It's definitely happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   What's a writer to do, then?
</P>
<P>
   DiTillio recommends looking at alternative markets and is now
writing science-fiction scripts for the French entertainment
concern Gaumont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been treated as well as I was by the Europeans,''
he admits. ``You're looking at a lot less money -- one `Murder, She
Wrote' equals seven `Babylon 5's. If they won't hire you at one
place, work for another or go to Canada. It's a global business
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppage insists Hollywood hungers as never before for good
writing, no matter how old the writer is, particularly with the
major networks seeing the ongoing erosion of their audiences to
cable. With the migration of cable-bred executives like TBS's Scott
Sassa to NBC and Comedy Central's Doug Herzog to Fox, opportunities
will be opening up for writers who can keep up with the demands of
the market, she believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think writers get better as they get older,'' Coppage said.
``My attitude is you can teach an old dog new tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bielbys and ``Riley Weston'' may have dimmed the allure
of Hollywood for aspiring writers. Paulla Hershey, a 40-year-old
waitress who has been working on three screenplays, said she cried
when she read about the Bielby report.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started working on scripts, I thought it was something
I could do forever,'' she said. ``I thought that no one will have
to know what I look like or where I live and that I could just stay
here with my cat and write.''
</P>
<P>
   She still continues to write, however, explaining, ``I don't
want to be a waitress forever. Right now, there's this huge push
toward glorification of kids, but hopefully, five years from now
the trendiness of kids and coming-of-age stories will be out.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
