<P>
   FIRST PART OF MILLENNIUM PACKAGE / MAIN NEWS
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW _ Almost 2,000 years ago, a man named Jesus
was born and the world changed forever. The impact of Jesus echoes
through the millinnia. It has profoundly changed the way people
view God, the world and each other. Over the next two weeks, and
the coming year, the Journal-Constitution will take a look at
Jesus, focusing on the spread of Christianity, first in and around
its homeland in the Mid-east, later through Europe and the
Americas, and ultimatley around the world. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CHRISTIANS _ JERUSALEM _ Despite their urban settings
and the politics that engulfs them 2000 years later, the sites
where Christ was born, lived and died are still powerful ``faith
strengtheners'' for millions of Christians world wide. Visits to
the region by Christians _ and they comprise about 75 percent of
Israel's 2.3 million annual tourists _ remind them that Jesus was
human and the ideals he practiced can be practiced by others. The
physical sites still make Jesus' story real. Christian
denominations have picked their favorite spots. Catholics come to
Jerusalem's Old City, where they often rent wooden crosses and walk
the supposed path Jesus took with his cross. Traditional
Protestants gravitate toward the Church of the Nativity and
Evangelicals head for prayer nearby in the Shepherd's Fields.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. 35.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-SCENES _ Short vignettes from the places where Jesus
was born, lived and died, focusing on what they look like today,
what visitors think of them and how they fit into today's
political, social landscape. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YEAR _ MOSCOW _ There is nothing happy about the new year
for Russia. Its mercurial post-Soviet economy went comatose in 1998
and the country's problems are forecasted to worsen in the new
year. President Boris Yeltsin is sick. Record numbers of Russians
are unemployed. Already experiencing its harshest winter in 30
years, Moscow is having difficulty keeping some of its remote
regions supplied with food and heating fuel. The government already
has announced it will default on some $15 billion in foreign debt
repayment due in 1999. A look at the bleak times ahead and what it
means for U.S.-Russian relations. (Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-BOX _ Data comparing Dec. 31, 1997 to Dec. 31, 1998
_ value of ruble, per capita income, employment, inflation, etc.
(Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-NEW _ LONDON _ With the first major step in unifying the
currencies, we take a look at the impact of unification on
culture/politics as much as economics. This as much about, or
perhaps more about the changing identities of the people of the
continent than it is about finance or economics. How will this
United States of Europe influence the way Europeans think of
themselves? (Roughton/Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EURO-BERLIN _ BERLIN, Germany _ Rebirth of Berlin as the capital
of Germany and perhaps of the new Europe. We also look at the rise
of France and Germany as the power players in the new alignment.
(Roughton, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-GREECE _ ATHENS, Greece _ Once an empire, Greece is now
having a difficult time remaining part of the Euro club. Greece's
temperamental economy kept it from becoming part of the group of EU
members which will on Jan. 1 inaugurate a single monetary unit, the
euro. Greeks are eager to join the monetary union. In recent
history a poor cousin to the rest of Europe, the euro could bring
respect and investors. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-WANNABES _ WARSAW _ Poland, like much of the rest of
Eastern Europe, has a clear image of itself in the 21st century.
Call it the anti-Warsaw Pact _ satellites of the former Soviet
Union eager to shed their association with Moscow and become
clearly linked with the West. Desirable alliances like the European
Union and NATO are integral to this new order and will redefine the
continent's political map. Poland is one of 10 eastern European
countries who want to join EU. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-BIZ _ LONDON _ Looking at what actually will happen with
unified currency on Jan. 1 _ which is limited to electronic
transactions _ and what this means for business. We also take note
of the implications to the dollar's status as the world's primary
hard currency. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EURO-BOX _ LONDON _ Welcome to Euroland. Eleven of the 15
countries in the European Union have agreed to join their financial
and monetary systems within the Economic Monetary Union (EMU). This
step will bring the people and governments of the continent closer
together than ever before. Box features: timeline; how the Euro 11
stacks up against the United States; the insiders and outsiders in
the EMU; Euro policymaking glossary. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Dec. 22 in the (f) Financial and (i)
International categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGS _ The story haunted the family like a half-remembered
dream, a mist of pride and shame drifting quietly through
generations. Thomas Jefferson, someone would say. We are related to
Thomas Jefferson. Mary Anne Medley heard the story as a girl, but
gave it little thought. Black folks in Depression-era Ohio saw
scant reason to examine or brag about a kinship with one of the
nation's founding fathers. After all, who would have believed them?
But decades later, Medley's daughters began to peel away the layers
of their heritage. They not only confirmed the link to Jefferson,
but uncovered a past where ancestors vanished into the white world.
(Keilman, Dayton Daily News). 50. WITH PHOTOS and a FAMILY TREE
GRAPHIC
</P>
