<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGS27-COX     12-26 2030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jefferson descendants peel back their past
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The story haunted Mary Anne Medley's family like
a half-remembered dream, a mist of pride and shame drifting quietly
through generations.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson, someone would say. We are related to Thomas
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Medley heard the story as a girl, but gave it little thought.
Black folks in Depression-era Ohio saw scant reason to examine or
brag about a kinship with one of the nation's founding fathers.
After all, who would have believed them?
</P>
<P>
   But decades later, Medley's daughters, including Trotwood
resident Rosemary Ghoston, began to peel away the layers of their
heritage. Their year-long search took them to libraries,
courthouses and graveyards around the Chillicothe area. It ended
with a few words on a death certificate that filled the women with
diamond-hard certainty.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was real. The story was true. They were related to
Jefferson's slave Sally Hemings, and in all likelihood, to
Jefferson himself.
</P>
<P>
   That was 12 years ago. Since then, scholarship and science have
torn away the veil that shrouded the sexual link between the
nation's third President and a slave. November's revelation that
genetic evidence linked Jefferson and Hemings made magazine covers
and front page headlines. Few doubt Medley's family now.
</P>
<P>
   Their investigation, however, uncovered much more than a famous
ancestor. It exposed a past where black melted into white, where
roots tangled and disappeared within a soil of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   While public questions may be settled, private mysteries remain.
For some, the tale is still unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1836, a 31-year-old freed slave named Madison Hemings and his
wife left Virginia for the relatively safe ground of Pike County,
Ohio. He lived quietly, rearing nine children on a farm and
supplementing his modest livelihood with the carpentry skills he
learned as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, 37 years after he arrived in Ohio, nondescript Madison
Hemings leaped onto history's stage.
</P>
<P>
   He gave an interview to the local paper, the Pike County
Republican , in which he made an extraordinary claim: His mother,
Sally Hemings, had been Thomas Jefferson's ``concubine.'' He and
three siblings were the president's children.
</P>
<P>
   The account, which remains the primary source of information on
Jefferson and Sally Hemings, was instantly attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds much better for the (slave) mother to tell her
offspring that 'master' is their father than to acknowledge to them
that some field hand, without a name, had raised her to the dignity
of mother,'' wrote a rival newspaperman five days after the
Republican article appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Madison's life, however, suggests he was no fabricator. He said
that among his siblings, he alone clung to his black heritage.
</P>
<P>
   No portraits exist of Sally Hemings or her children, but they
evidently had extremely fair skin. According to Madison's
interview, Sally was only one-quarter black (one of her
grandparents was African, the rest Caucasian). When her children
left Jefferson's estate of Monticello, all but Madison decided to
pass for white.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Beverly and sister Harriet went to Washington, D.C.,
and married white spouses. His brother Eston, who settled in
Chillicothe for a time, also assumed the role of a white man upon
moving to Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure why Madison, Sally's second-youngest child,
decided to maintain his black identity. One theory, advanced by
author Fawn Brodie in her 1974 book, Thomas Jefferson: An Intimate
History, is that Madison bitterly recalled being raised apart from
Jefferson's white grandchildren. Though his skin may have been
light, his segregated youth spurred him to cast his lot with the
black community, Brodie suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Cinder Stanton, a historian at Monticello, notes that under
Virginia law at the time, Sally Hemings' children were officially
white, since they were three generations removed from a fully black
relation (a distinction that did not spare them from a youth of
slavery).
</P>
<P>
   She speculates, though, that Madison's wife, whom he married in
Virginia, may have had darker skin, making it impossible for them
to live as a white couple.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie's research in the 1970s uncovered Eston Hemings' true
identity, and it was one of his descendents who provided the DNA
linking Sally Hemings with Jefferson. Researchers compared his Y
chromosome with that of a man related to one of Jefferson's uncles.
The chromosomes matched, meaning Thomas Jefferson and the son of
his slave shared the same genes.
</P>
<P>
   Many historians are satisfied that Jefferson fathered Madison as
well, but as of yet, his branch of the family has not provided
clinching evidence. The DNA must come from a male descendent, and
while Madison had three sons, one died before having children and
the other two vanished into the white world, erasing their links to
the family's slave history.
</P>
<P>
   They would not be the last to do so.
</P>
<P>
   When Mary Ann Medley was a girl in Greenfield, a small town 20
miles west of Chillicothe, her extended family frequently came to
visit at her grandmother's house.
</P>
<P>
   But as Medley grew up in the 1920s and 1930s, the gatherings
thinned. Aunts, uncles and cousins simply disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them married white,'' says the 80-year-old Medley, who
now lives in Chillicothe. ``I imagine if they saw us on the streets
someplace, they would turn their heads. They probably wouldn't want
their spouses to know who they were. (Their spouses) might not have
known that they were black.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the family possessed skin so light the average person
probably would mistake them for Caucasian. Some chose not to
correct that perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, for someone black to get a decent job
beyond cleaning or housework . . . a lot of people had to do
that,'' says Rosemary Ghoston, 56, one of Medley's daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Medley's children learned the subtleties of their
racial heritage. Patti Jo Harding, 46, a daughter who lives in
Chillicothe, recalls her parents' warning when the family visited a
cousin in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we got (there), they said you can't mention anything
about being black,'' she says. ``We had to act like we were just
friends. We (couldn't) let them know that we're related to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The cousin had taken a white wife who was unaware of his true
racial background.
</P>
<P>
   Ghoston, like her mother, has a fair complexion but never
wavered in her racial identity. After attending a segregated
elementary school, she swore to marry a dark-skinned man so no one
would mistake the race of her children. When she began work as a
hairdresser, she always told her customers up front that she was a
black woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that from the beginning, you know who I am, so if
you don't want to come to me, you don't have to come to me,'' she
says. ``And a few, when they found out, did stop coming to me,
especially here in Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, a family reunion prompted Ghoston and her
sisters to unravel their father's genealogy, which in turn inspired
them to tackle their mother's side. It was a task, they knew, that
could finally shed light upon the Jefferson legend.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not everyone was eager for an unmasking. The women's aunt
repeatedly asked them why they wanted to dredge up the past. There
was no honor, she said, in being related to a slaveholder, no
matter how illustrious.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her misgivings, she eventually decided to help. She gave
the women a photograph of her mother as a girl, surrounded by her
parents and nine siblings. Most of the children would later pass
for white, Medley says.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing their mother, Medley's daughters visited
government offices around Chillicothe to retrieve birth and death
certificates. They prowled cemeteries to find their ancestors'
gravestones. And with some help from a cousin, they got a big
break.
</P>
<P>
   The cousin, who happened to be tracking her own ancestry, had
sketched out a chart that connected the family with Sally Hemings.
But it was one link short of completion.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Ghoston was at a library when, for reasons
she can't remember, she picked up a book that contained Madison's
newspaper interview. In it, he lists the names of his children.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing one of those children could be the missing generation,
Medley and her daughter Patti Jo Harding went to the courthouse in
Circleville, where they found the death certificate of Emma Bird.
She was Medley's grandmother, and the last relative they knew much
about.
</P>
<P>
   The paper listed Bird's parents. Her mother, it said, was Sarah
Hemings _ daughter of Madison, granddaughter of Jefferson's slave
Sally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' thought Harding. ``That's them.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery came in 1986, yet for years the sisters told few
people about their discovery. They still weren't sure anyone would
believe them, or that anyone would care.
</P>
<P>
   Through a local historian, they made the acquaintance of
Monticello researchers who were compiling histories of the estate's
slaves. That led in 1997 to a reunion of slave descendents. Around
80 families _ most of them linked to Sally Hemings _ joined Medley
and her daughters as they toured the house and grounds where their
ancestors labored.
</P>
<P>
   While the weekend unearthed long-hidden family ties, there were
more surprises to come.
</P>
<P>
   In July of this year, one of the women's cousins, Columbus-area
resident Diane Redman, received a mysterious phone call from a
white woman who said, ``This is going to sound crazy, but I think
we're related.''
</P>
<P>
   The caller, who had begun work on her own family tree, had run
into obstacles. No one was willing to give her much information
about her estranged father's lineage.
</P>
<P>
   She had a single clue to pursue: her mother's recollection of a
long-ago visit to someone by the name of Ida Mae Redman, who
perhaps was a relative. The caller began phoning every Redman in
the Columbus phone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you've got the right person,'' Redman said.
``We're black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I kind of figured that,'' the caller replied.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled a fight her parents had when she was a child, an
argument in which one of them mentioned black relatives. That, the
caller believed, was the reason some of her family didn't want to
aid her search.
</P>
<P>
   Redman invited the caller to meet at a restaurant. Astonishing
physical resemblances convinced both sides that they were indeed
related, and Redman invited the caller and her siblings to meet the
rest of her family.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering occurred on a warm mid-summer afternoon. While it
was pleasant, Redman says it was obvious the caller and her sisters
were in shock. They learned that their father _ a man whom they
thought was white and a racist _ had two black parents. Their
mother, whose own family cut her off for marrying a black man, had
never told them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grew up white,'' Redman says. `` . . . While they felt
they didn't have any racist tendencies, they had never thought
about their skin color, never thought about what it was like to be
a black person.''
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . To suddenly find out that part of yourself is not what
you thought it was, that's very difficult. How do you explain to
your spouse, 'Oh, by the way, I'm black.' That might not go over
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The two families remain in touch, and the caller and her sisters
plan to gradually tell more of their siblings. Their father still
isn't aware that they know their heritage. Ghoston, the Trotwood
resident, says she would like to write him someday and invite him
to rejoin the scattered family of Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   His children maintain that isn't a good idea. But Ghoston thinks
this moment in history _ when Jefferson and Hemings have been
irrefutably linked, when strict definitions of race seem to be in
flux _ might be the time for a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people live a lie, they constantly worry that it's going
to catch up to them,'' she says. ``It can be such a relief when it
is all out in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
