<HEADER>
A7075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-CHRISTIANS     12-26 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CHRISTIANS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A pilgrimage of faith
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Jesus Christ walked on the stone streets of this
ancient city nearly 2000 years ago, and his followers still come
here to praise his name.
</P>
<P>
   They come, undaunted by today's reality.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the place where Protestants believe Christ was
crucified is now a grimy outdoor bus terminal. Or, that the
fortress-like Church of the Nativity sits in the heart of a crowded
Bethlehem, where the rattle of jackhammers and bus engines echoes
around ``Manger Square.''
</P>
<P>
   To the pilgrims, it is still the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The holy sites today are surrounded by the wonders and problems
of the 20th century _ office buildings and shopping malls, traffic
jams and smog.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still a few shepherds on the rocky hills of
Bethlehem. The rolling green landscape of the Galilee is still
relatively serene, a logical place for Christ to take refuge and
preach. And Jerusalem remains a spiritual center, the place legend
suggests all prayers return to before soaring to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   As this Christmas season edges us closer to the second
millennium since Jesus' birth, his believers today still find that
the ``Holy Land'' attests to his humanity. A visit to these stone
streets and rocky hillsides adds a gritty realism to The Bible
story, strengthening the faith the pilgrims bring with them.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked out of the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem
recently, through the dust of construction in preparation for the
anticipated tourist influx in the year 2000, aluminum siding
salesman David Gage reflected on his trip to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the presence of the Lord with me two or three times,
it's almost like being lifted up,'' said Gage, 39, from Venice,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, pediatric nurse Rebecca Wiley of Houston wept as
she emerged from the austere rock crypt at Garden Tomb. The bare
rock floor is believed by Protestants to be the burial place of
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the place where they laid Jesus and he's no longer
there,'' Wiley, 39, said. ``That's the whole reason for our
Christian belief. Everything you read and studied and learned _ you
look at it in a whole new light.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the fourth century, Christians have flocked to this land.
They came from Europe on foot or jammed in the holds of ships,
diseased and unwashed. Royalty and members of the aristocracy made
the journey in caravans and during state visits.
</P>
<P>
   Denominations the world over, from the Greek Orthodox in the
fourth century to Mormons in the 20th, built their churches and
schools here, laying claim to at least a portion of this holy land.
</P>
<P>
   Their pilgrims followed and, through most of history visited a
land that was ruled not by Christians but by Muslims and, now,
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they come in airliners and tour buses, from Oregon and
Great Britain and Guatemala. This is the Jewish state, but about 60
percent of the 2million tourists to Israel each year are
Christians. The total might double in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents and tour guides agree that when terrorism and the
political turmoil of the modern Middle East scare off visitors to
Israel, Christian tourists are the last to cancel.
</P>
<P>
   Most Christians are guided through their heritage by
Jewish-Israeli tour guides, licensed by the Israeli government.
They point out remnants of the pre-Christian past _ either in the
architecture or the landscape _ that bring Jesus' story alive and
let believers identify with his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Catholic priest and historian Jerome
Murphy-O'Connor notes that Bible readers might not understand why
at Gethsemane Christ anguished about his impending death. After
all, he had anticipated his demise long before. Visitors here,
though, will see that Christ had likely just walked through the
Kidron Valley, where he might have been frightened by stern tombs
that still stand today.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if one wonders about the story of the foot washing, which
Jesus did for his disciples in the manner of a servant, a few walks
around the dusty area will demonstrate why that was a custom.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Gallbreath, a civil engineer from San Antonio, Texas, said
he got a new insight looking at the woods of Galilee _ a modest
patch of trees on a rolling landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never thought of Jesus before as what he was, a
carpenter,'' Gallbreath, 54, said. ``(In the Galilee) I imagined
him having to cut down one of those trees and making it into
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, drawing inspiration from the holy sites may require
imagination or selective tourism. The exact location of many
biblical events is disputed and many shrines are labeled
``traditional sites,'' meaning people have decided through the
years to accept their authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The various Christian denominations have chosen their separate
destinations. Protestants favor the airy, landscaped Garden Tomb
near the bus terminal in east Jerusalem. Catholics and Orthodox
Christians say Christ was crucified and buried at the hulking
Church of the Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants often sing Christmas carols in the Shepherds Fields
outside of Bethlehem. Catholics kiss the stones of the big
churches, more ready to accept that the floors and walls touched by
Christ still radiate his holy essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the Catholics will be moved standing in the chapel,
the Protestants in the hillsides,'' Israeli tour guide Josef Gilboa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many evangelical Protestants carry a literal belief in the
Bible's Book of Revelation. They see the apocalypse as close and
believe steps are under way to clear the way for Christ's return.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical tourism surged after Israel captured the West Bank
in the war of 1967. Many Christians see the uniting of the Holy
Land under the Jews as a necessary condition for Christ's return.
</P>
<P>
   Such belief has led to a stream of evangelical tourists who are
also hard-line believers that Israel should keep controversial
occupied Arab territory. Frequent visitors include the Revs. Jerry
Falwell and Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the birthplace of Christianity can include a sail on
the Sea of Galilee, where Christ is said to have walked on water.
Some pilgrims rent smocks and towels and stand knee-deep for a
rebaptism in a branch of the Jordan River, the same river _ though
in a different spot _ where Jesus was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the religious sites are getting a make-over for the
millions expected at the turn of the millennium. That can be
sensitive work in a land where tradition often trumps pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   After four years of pressure, the Israeli government recently
talked the three main orders in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre _
Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian Orthodox _ into adding a
second door to the church for a much-needed emergency exit. After
that, Israeli officials want them to upgrade the dilapidated public
toilets.
</P>
<P>
   The three groups have feuded for centuries and jealously guard
their portions of the church. They fear that even the slightest
change will disrupt ownership rights.
</P>
<P>
   The church, first dedicated in 335 A.D., is often held up as a
metaphor for the region, where followers of many religions live
under the same roof but cannot agree on simple solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But even the religious rivalry and harsh politics can be
incorporated into the story of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rossing, a Jewish Israeli who used to be the government's
liaison with the Christian churches, said Christian visitors should
not be distracted by the discord.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was the story of Jesus all about?'' Rossing asked. ``It
was about him coming to the nitty-gritty. You want a paradise?
That's not what this is about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
