<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW27     12-26 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One man, 2 millennia, 2 billion followers worldwide
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Christians believe that through the birth of Jesus of
Nazareth, God became human.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he was God incarnate, Jesus changed the world.
History is full of the best and the worst of human actions in his
name: horrible wars and wonderful acts of kindness; persecution and
sacrifice; bigotry and unselfish love. Some of the world's greatest
art, music and literature have been produced and some of its most
prominent institutions of medicine and learning have been
established to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   Even the calendar changed to mark his birth. The celebrations
that will mark the beginning of the year 2000 will actually
acknowledge an anniversary of that event. Groups ranging from small
survivalist sects to the Roman Catholic Church are gearing up for
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in a small Middle Eastern town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early Christians did not believe that the time and place
of the birth of Jesus had been left to chance,'' writes church
historian Justo L. Gonzalez of Decatur, author of ``The Story of
Christianity.'' ``On the contrary, they saw the hand of God
preparing the advent of Jesus in all events prior to the birth, and
in all the historical circumstances around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus was born at a crossroads, historically and geographically.
Palestine back then was at the intersection of trade routes joining
Egypt with Mesopotamia and Asia Minor with Arabia. As a result, it
was often invaded.
</P>
<P>
   In the late first century B.C., Palestine was a ``rustic,
despised corner'' of the Roman Empire, Gonzalez said. A few hundred
years before, people had lived in city-states that determined their
identity, including their religion. But with the Roman Empire came
interaction of cultures and a new mobility.
</P>
<P>
   The time of Jesus' birth ``was a time of confused identities,
similar to now,'' Gonzalez said. ``Christianity came into that
fray.''
</P>
<P>
   It arose as a renewal movement within Palestinian Judaism.
Jesus' earliest followers saw their role as fulfilling the promises
of God, Yahweh, to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The gospels of the Christian Bible say God performed miracles
through Jesus, beginning with his birth to a virgin and ending with
his resurrection after death. Perhaps one of the most amazing is
the growth of the faith that worships him. From 12 disciples,
according to Biblical accounts, it has increased to nearly 2
billion followers. One out of three people identifies with some
branch of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exact date of Jesus's birth is unknown and
generally estimated to have occurred between 3 and 6 B.C., the
coming of the year 2000 still has great symbolism for Christians,
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good time for reflection, for recollection, for
thanksgiving and for repentance,`` he said. ``Every once in a while
you need to go back to your origins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
