<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIAN-REFUGEE27-CO     12-26 1676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIAN-REFUGEE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugee not content to just look back
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Back in his homeland of Nigeria, there was a price on
Abelage Sunday Ereba's head.
</P>
<P>
   He was wanted, dead or alive, simply because he had organized
protests against the government and Shell Oil Co., which, for 40
years, had drilled oil from Ereba's region of Nigeria. The
drilling, protesters argued, caused air pollution and left much of
the rich farmland unusable.
</P>
<P>
   Ereba never attacked anyone. Never killed anyone. All the
protests about the environmental effects of the drilling were
peaceful, he said. ``We carried palm fronds. No one was armed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the military government considered him an enemy of the
state because his protests made it look bad and eventually forced
Shell to stop drilling. He and the other protesters also cost the
government money because it lost its cut of Shell's profits when
the oil giant left.
</P>
<P>
   So when Ereba's name went on the ``most wanted'' list in 1994,
he had to go into hiding. For the next two years, each day could
have been his last. Whoever turned him in would get about $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Often he hid in rivers or creeks, dodging snakes and crocodiles.
He moved under the cover of darkness and could hear soldiers
terrorizing nearby villages. He heard gunshots and screams as
people ran away. He smelled fires when the soldiers burned down
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Some days he didn't eat. He relied on the kindness of
sympathetic strangers who gave him food and warned him if the
soldiers were getting close.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't know who to trust. You had to move a lot, so as not
to be discovered. You take whatever comes your way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ereba's story is similar to those of 65,000 refugees from hot
spots all over the world who now call Atlanta home. Many of them
also fled torture, detention, the murder of loved ones and other
unspeakable horrors of war. After escaping places like Bosnia,
Rwanda, Vietnam, northern Iraq, Sudan and Somalia, they hardly ever
look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Refugees who come to Atlanta have lost everything. They have
to start over with nothing when they arrive here,'' said Stephanie
Baric of the International Rescue Committee, a nonprofit agency
that has resettled thousands of refugees, including Ereba, in
DeKalb County. ``When they come here, they want to leave what
happened to them behind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ereba, 34, is different. He is eager to talk about his past.
And he is still fighting the demons who forced him into exile. His
willingness to talk about his old life opens the door for his new
neighbors here to understand how far refugees have come, not just
in distance. It also helps Atlantans understand the contrast
between an open, democratic America and the oppression of the
countries refugees fled.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted by his government
</P>
<P>
   Ereba worked in security and personnel for Shell from 1985 until
1989. In 1990, he joined the Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni
People (MOSOP) in protesting Shell's presence in the Ogoni region
of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shell took the oil out of our land, but they gave nothing
back. We had been cheated and we decided we should have a share in
the resources,'' he said. ``We had nothing. No electricity, no
running water, no schools.... We didn't have good roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell's pipelines were not buried deep and they often exploded,
leading to gas fires that would burn for days, polluting the air
and making breathing difficult. The resulting oil spill also ruined
the land, but the farmers were never compensated for their losses,
Ereba said.
</P>
<P>
   Shell acknowledges environmental problems with its operations in
Nigeria, but says it has not devastated the land.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known in his village, Ereba was targeted by the government
because he worked closely with MOSOP officials to organize
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Ereba was one of about 2,000 refugees who fled Nigeria because
they were wanted by the government. ``Many people were in Ereba's
shoes,'' said Ledum Mitee, MOSOP president at the organization's
London office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people hid in the bush, or fled to neighboring
communities. Many others were killed when the soldiers came into
their villages looking for them.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 men, women and children were killed in a military
crackdown that followed Ogoni protests against Shell, Mitee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were an activist, they went after you. If they couldn't
find you, they would go after your family,'' Mitee said. ``Ereba's
house was destroyed by security agents. His stepfather was detained
and tortured. He is no longer in detention, but his health is very
bad, I'm told.''
</P>
<P>
   While in hiding, Ereba missed the birth of his first child, who
was born about a month after he disappeared. His wife, Nelly, had
to hide with the infant because of her husband's sins against the
state. ``They wanted me to get to him,'' she said. ``I could hear
the soldiers shooting as we ran away from the hospital. It's only
God who saved my life and the life of my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Also while he hid, the government executed nine of his comrades,
including Ken Saro-Wiwa, a prominent writer who had been nominated
for a Nobel prize in literature. They were accused of treason and
murder, but human rights organizations condemned their hangings,
saying they were killed simply because they opposed the government.
</P>
<P>
   Ereba could have easily been in the gallows with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by the grace of God that I am alive,'' he said. ``They
would have killed me if they had found me.''
</P>
<P>
   Working in Buckhead
</P>
<P>
   While he worries about the family he left behind in Nigeria _
including his mother, three sisters and a brother _ Ereba is
adjusting well to his new life here. Since September, he has lived
in a three-bedroom apartment in Clarkston with his wife, two
daughters, a brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   He works as a security guard at the Grand Hyatt in Buckhead,
where he makes $8.25 and hour and says he feels like part of a
family. The ambience couldn't be more different from the world he
knew in Nigeria. At the hotel, the rich come to do business and
attend parties. Valets park their cars. Guests dine on gourmet food
served on fine china.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it fascinating. It gives me a clear sense of seeing and
knowing the other side of life,'' he said. ``Right now, it poses a
challenge. I have decided to do my best.'' The job ``is like a son
to me,'' he said. ``My whole family is involved in seeing to it
that I get to work on time.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes him 90 minutes to get to work. A bus, two trains, a
short walk up Peachtree Street from the MARTA station. He gets free
meals at work, and his family was given a turkey, stuffing and
cranberry sauce at Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   A local church and the International Rescue Committee have
donated food, clothing and furniture to his family and several
other Nigerian families who have moved to Atlanta in the past few
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been an immigrant myself, it's easy for me to identify
where they are coming from,'' said Bankole Akinmola, a native of
Nigeria and pastor of the World Outreach Church for All Nations in
Tucker. ``God has brought these people to us and because they are
immigrants, there are many things they need. We want to meet their
needs physically and spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   One church member had heard of Ereba, who is known as Sunday to
his friends. His middle name came from the day of the week he was
born. Such naming is common among Nigerians from his region. It is
a remnant of British colonial rule, which ended when Nigeria gained
independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday is a very courageous, intelligent man. God is really
guiding him,'' said the church member, Dorn Manadom, a native of
Ogoni who left Nigeria in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard that some refugees were going to be sent from
Ogoni to Atlanta, I quickly called all the agencies responsible for
bringing in refugees. They were able to tell me where they put
them. I was the first person to see them from Ogoni.''
</P>
<P>
   Ereba said he is grateful and amazed that strangers have offered
him so much help. It's an example he hopes to emulate when he is
more settled. ``I hope to be able to help some other people who
might need help tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staying in touch
</P>
<P>
   Although he doesn't have much here, it's more than what he had
had for two years in a Benin refugee camp. Food was rationed in the
crowded, desolate camp, and there was never enough. The fact that
he found his wife after two years apart was miraculous. He
clandestinely crossed into Nigeria from Benin in February 1996 and
entered a refugee camp. Two weeks later, U.N. officials located his
wife and brought her to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw my daughter, I broke down in tears,'' he
said. ``My wife and I were both in tears. It was a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   A second daughter was born in the camp. He prayed every day that
they would be approved to come to America. ``I never planned for a
refugee life,'' he said. ``Escaping into Benin to seek asylum was
my last resort. I am very grateful that it was approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is thousands of miles away from home, Ereba stays
in touch with MOSOP officials in London and the United States. His
briefcase is filled with articles about the struggle of the Ogoni
against Shell. In November, he went to Washington for a human
rights conference sponsored by the MOSOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue the struggle even as I am here,'' he said.
``Something must be done to stop Shell from coming back into
Ogoniland and to make them compensate us for the damage they caused
while they were there.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ereba reflects on his life, he savors the freedom he now
enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself in a completely different environment, an
environment where people can air their different views and not be
afraid. For now, I feel safe. I had no feeling like that for four
years. I had been living in perpetual fear,'' he said. ``It was
like I was living in a dungeon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
