<SLUG> BC-OBI-BRINKMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD GERHARD BRINKMANN, 53, ARCHITECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donald Gerhard Brinkmann, a partner in the New York
office of Gensler, an international architecture and interior
planning firm, died on Dec. 19 at New York University Hospital. He
was 53 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure after a stroke, the firm reported.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkmann, a native of Riverside, Calif., attended California
State Polytechnic University and graduated with a degree in
architecture in 1969 from the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   He then spent 13 years as a designer and associate in the San
Francisco office of Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, architects.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to New York in 1982 to join Gensler Architecture Design
and Planning Worldwide and was named a partner in 1985. As the lead
designer in the office, he worked on projects in San Francisco,
Minneapolis, Buffalo, Miami, Washington, New York, London and South
America.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkmann designed office space for law firms, financial
institutions, corporations and consulting firms. He recently
completed projects for Baron Capital in New York, QVC Network
headquarters in West Chester, Pa., and Swiss Re American Corp.
offices in New York. He was also working on designs for Christie's
auction house in New York and Bank Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to the Interior Design Hall of Fame in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a brother, John, of Riverside, and his
companion, Dr. Mark Weinrod.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
