<HEADER>
A7110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTING-HIGHWAY27-COX     12-26 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTING-HIGHWAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Burbs swarm in deer
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's one of the few really cold mornings of the
hunting season so far, and Mike Ivie, face flushed from an icy
wind, shivers in his tree stand as the sky begins to brighten.
</P>
<P>
   He listens to the noises of the forest: The rush of a nearby
river, the cawing of an obnoxious crow, the scurrying and barking
of squirrels, the constant roar of the morning rush-hour traffic
and the ``thump-thump-thump'' of heavy bass coming from a music
lover's car.
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Ivie is hunting within earshot of I-20 and a major road leading
to it. On the way to this section of DeKalb County, he drove by
large, luxury homes with manicured lawns and custom landscaping.
Not exactly the pastoral scene that comes to mind when the word
``hunt'' comes up.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to hunting in the 'burbs. When asked where he would go
to get a trophy deer, Ivie replied: ``DeKalb County with a bow and
arrow. South Fulton also has some excellent deer. All these places
that have woods where the deer have been pocketed up, hunted only
with a bow, not shot at and not spooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think deer are using people _ subdivisions and other
neighborhoods _ as safety valves,'' he said. ``A lot of Pope &AMP;
Young (scoring system for bow hunters) deer in DeKalb have been
taken around subdivisions.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that only bow hunting is legal in DeKalb, says
Ivie, 46, major-league baseball's No. 1 draft pick in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first love was hitting a baseball,'' he said. ``Next is
deer hunting with a bow. I take hunting as seriously as I did
playing ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He hunts nearly every day of the season and many a morning his
mind must drift to today's sports salaries, especially some of
those fringe players with million-dollar contracts.
</P>
<P>
   His career .269 average and home-run-hitting bat, would be worth
big bucks today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quiver at the thought,'' Ivie said. ``I could own my own
hunting preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been away from the game for more than 10 years but still
dreams of getting a job as a minor-league hitting instructor,
possibly with the Braves; Atlanta coach Glenn Hubbard is a hunting
buddy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he had asked Hubbard to hunt with him that morning but
it didn't work out. That was the day Hubbard's home burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. I used to live within walking distance
from him,'' Ivie said. ``I hate it. I hate it. And right at
Christmas time. But I'm extremely glad none of them were harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivie's trophy wall at home is tangible proof of his hunting
skills, with 20 trophy deer head eight points or better with
18-inch spreads or better.
</P>
<P>
   A large portion were taken with the bow. He started bowhunting
at 13 with a recurve and now uses a compound. For the last five
years, he has used a bow only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather bow hunt because I don't have to worry about
someone shooting me with a rifle by mistake,'' he said. ``You
really know you've become a real, true deer hunter when you sit and
watch a deer 40 yards away, watch it feeding on acorns or something
else and don't take a shot at it (because it's out of range).''
</P>
<P>
   At such times, Ivie says, he studies the deer's habits and adds
the information to the mental file that will contribute the his
next success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn so much about deer hunting by bow hunting,'' he
said. ``You really learn about deer. If you watch them enough, the
deer will actually tell you where to put your stand.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing Ivie learned: ``A deer is nose, No. 1,
ears No. 2 and eyes No. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Covering scent is the most important aspect, then being silent
or at least not making noises foreign to the habit, and then
camouflage. Ivie's DeKalb enclave isn't the only 'burb suddenly
becoming a deer-hunting hotspot.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Ivie's hunts in a patch of woods close to one of the
Harry's Farmer's Markets and has taken several deer. He's shot at
some while hearing people talking and putting groceries in their
car trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Other unlikely spots include one near a Shoneys and another
within earshot of a Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got 10-15 acres in DeKalb,'' Ivie said, ``you've got
deer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
