</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOOR-ALMANAC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No minor accomplishment
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell and Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   TOP GUN
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Norman F. LeClair got the Christmas card of a lifetime
earlier in the week. It was signed, Norman ``Top Gun'' LeClair and
signified a momentous event, the day a son topped his dad. The
senior LeClair, 62, seemed unbeatable in the Thanksgiving Grand
National Waterfowl Hunt at Cambridge, Md., having taken five ducks
with his five allotted shells. But a hunter on another team was
even more perfect, after figuring that two ducks with one shot can
improve a score. Norman A. LeClair, 35, got two doubles along with
his singles, to win the event's Top Gun award. The senior LeClair,
acknowledged as the ``fastest gun in the South'' by those who have
participated with him nationwide in various celebrity hunts, said,
``I taught him everything I know, he turns around and whips me. It
may be years before I live this down.'' He was smiling, though.
</P>
<P>
   BRAGGIN' RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   What 20-year-old Brian McBride has done since taking up fishing
seriously more than a year ago will be unsettling and maybe even
infuriating to many veteran bassers. In that short span, the
Barnesville college student has caught three largemouth bass
weighing more than 11 pounds _ a feat most anglers never
accomplish. And get this: The latest lunker he has landed weighed
15 pounds, 13 ounces, one of the largest largemouths caught in
Georgia in recent years. McBride caught the bass at the same place
he landed the other two fish three weeks apart last summer _
weighing 11-7 and 11-15 _ at a 20-acre private pond near Griffin.
``It was a monster,'' McBride said. ``It took me about 20 minutes
to land it. I was taking my time because I knew it was big. I
wanted to be careful.'' The Middle Georgia College sophomore caught
the fish on a large shiner he caught with a cast net at a nearby
creek. He caught it Dec. 10, the first day of his Christmas break.
McBride took up fishing seriously after he graduated from Lamar
County High School and no longer had football as a hobby. A former
tight end, he began taking frequent trips with grandfather Donald
Duke and friend Jeremy Worthy. The only problem McBride has now is
trying to outdo his unreal beginnings as a serious angler. ``I
really can't explain it. Maybe it's just pure luck. It's hard for
me to believe (what) I've done,'' he said last week. ``I almost
wished I hadn't caught them yet, because it makes me think, `What
else more can I do?' I can't expect to catch anything (bigger) than
15 pounds again. ... But I'm still going fishing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S TIP
</P>
<P>
   The challenge in landing a big striper this month has been
finding the roaming fish. Lake Lanier guide Don Roberson has been
finding stripers in 35 to 50 feet of water feeding on school shad.
Flex-It jigging spoons are still successful. ``They're on the
move,'' Roberson said. ``All of a sudden they'll be gone.''
Stripers have been coming up the surface in coves and shallows late
in the day, feeding on the summer's last shad hatch. Those baitfish
are small _ generally less than an inch long _ and the stripers are
pushing them to the surface and gulping up several at a time.
Matching the bait _ fly fisherman Craig Carter was throwing flies
of similar size _ can attract some good action. The problem? The
stripers might be splashing the surface all over a cove, but they
might not stay around long.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE NEWSSTAND
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought it? Old-timers are probably looking
askance at the cover of Sports Afield magazine's Winter 1998-99
issue. Instead of a hunter and a deer or bear, or an angler, there
is a skier. And inside, it's celebrity buzz with a report on the
rich and famous buying the state of Montana. Names dropped include
Ted and Jane, David Letterman, Steven Seagal, Dennis Quaid and Meg
Ryan, and Whoopi Goldberg. In an old-line hunting and fishing
magazine!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
