<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National big bass contest
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell and Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Catching a big bass can offer a bigger reward than an
impressive trophy mount. If it's caught as part of Bassin'
magazine's Big Bass World Championship program, it can mean $50,000
in cash and a fully rigged bass boat.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 10th year, the program is America's only nationwide
fishing event in which weekend anglers can fish any time, anywhere
to win big money.
</P>
<P>
   Qualification for the BBWC begins Jan. 1 and continues through
Aug. 15. Contestants can fish in any participating state except
Alaska. Anglers must be at least 18, have a valid fishing license,
and send an $18 fee with an entry form. Contestants also must be a
Bassin' subscriber at the time of their catch.
</P>
<P>
   Until Aug. 15, anglers fish for the heaviest largemouth bass in
their state in order to qualify for the finals, scheduled Oct.
15-16 in Branson, Mo. To get an entry form or inquire about rules,
call 1-800-883-2292 or visit the Web site
(http://www.bigbasschampion
</P>
<P>
   ship.com).
</P>
<P>
   Shad season
</P>
<P>
   The commercial shad season on several Georgia river systems
begins at 6 a.m. on Jan. 1, with no regulation changes from 1998.
The season runs through midnight March 1. The Altamaha River,
including the Oconee and Ocmulgee rivers; the Satilla; and the St.
Mary's downstream from the Seaboard Coastline Railroad bridge will
be open for commercial fishing Monday through Friday each week.
Waters upstream from the bridge will be open Tuesday through
Saturday. The Ogeechee will be open on Fridays and Saturdays. The
Savannah River will be open downstream from the I-95 bridge Tuesday
through Friday, and Wednesday through Saturday upstream. Only drift
nets may be used downstream of a line between the mouth of Knoxboro
Creek and McCoy's Cut at Deadman's Point. Persons fishing
commercially for shad must have a valid Georgia commercial license,
and boats used also must be licenced. Sturgeon, catfish and all
game fish other than American shad or hickory shad taken in drift
or set nets must be released immediately. For more information,
call the state Wildlife Resources Division law enforcement at :
912-264-7237 (Brunswick); 706-595-4211 (Thomson); 704-846-8448
(Manchester); 912-430-4252 (Albany); or 912-685-2145 (Metter).
</P>
<P>
   Shooter's guide
</P>
<P>
   The National Shooting Sports Foundation has a new guide, ``So
You Want to Build a Shooting Range,''to help recreational shooters
develop their own ranges. The guide is free for members, $5 for
nonmembers. To get a copy, write to The National Shooting Sports
Foundation, 11 Mile Hill Road, Newton, CT 06470.
</P>
<P>
   Tree recycling
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Hartwell Project, accepts
Christmas trees for recycling as submerged fish attractors in Lake
Hartwell Dec. 26-Jan. 5. Trees can be dropped off at Big Oaks
Recreation Area, one mile past the Hartwell Dam on U.S. Hwy. 29.
Trees are tied together in bundles, weighted with concrete blocks
and sunk in locations marked with buoys. Along with providing cover
for fish, the trees also provide habitat for aquatic insects,
essential food sources during the early stage of most fish species.
For information, call toll-free at 888-893-0678.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
