<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoke is Asheville hit
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ It's not unusual to see crowds in this part of
the Smoky Mountains in the fall. But the lure usually is autumn
leaves and bookstores, not a Class A-level hockey team and $1 beer
nights _ ``Frosty Fridays.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget that Asheville didn't have hockey before the UHL's Smoke
left Brantford, Ontario. The city didn't have an ice rink.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ohio State hockey player and owner Dan Williams, who
purchased the Smoke with his brother last year, spent $500,000 to
build a rink in the 23-year-old Asheville Civic Center. Problem is,
the arena wasn't built for hockey. Consequently, the rink is only
185 feet long, 15 fewer than standard. Team officials were painting
lines on the ice until 3 a.m. the eve of the first home game, and
the ice still isn't quite up to standards.
</P>
<P>
   But without a reference point, fans hardly notice. Crowds were
near capacity for the first three games in the 5,434-seat facility.
The team averaged 1,464 in Brantford but stands at 3,620 in
Asheville. Residents are thrilled to have a new diversion, even if,
as forward Kris Schultz says, ``Somebody asked me how we can stand
on the ice, because it's so slippery.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz spoke by phone with friends in Regina, Saskatchewan, the
other day. ``They asked me what the temperature was, and I told
them, `On the 17th hole, it was about 76 degrees.' They told me it
just snowed two feet. I love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Merchandising: Almost anything with the smoking dragon logo is
a hot item; the glow-in-the-dark goalie mask is unique.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nourishment: Low marks for grub, but the buck beers on Fridays
are a hit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Between periods: Fans shoot the puck through a microscopic
hole to win a truck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best promotions: Players skate out through inflatable dragon;
the team raffles off an autographed Wayne Gretzky stick _ the coach
is his brother Keith; fans skate with the Smoke after selected
games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never thought you'd see: Dasherboard ads for ``3 Little Pigs
BBQ'' and ``Alan's Jewelry and Pawn Shop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
