<SLUG> BC-HKN-BIRMIN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls slog through bad ice, worse Elvis
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ On a football Saturday, an oversized,
inflatable bull walks _ on two feet _ through the corridors of the
Birmingham-Jefferson Civic Center. If the mascot bears a strong
resemblance to ``Sir Slapshot'' from the days of the Atlanta
Knights, there's a reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham Bulls of the East Coast Hockey League are owned
by David Berkman, run by Charles Felix and marketed by Bruce Burge,
all of whom held similar positions with the Knights. What the Bulls
don't quite have is the Knights' loyal following. They average
fewer than 3,500 fans per game, near the bottom of the league. The
crowd looks particularly small in a 16,850-seat arena.
</P>
<P>
   But Felix says, ``We believe this is a good market, and we're
trying to do some things to get out in the community more. We're
bringing more entertainment into the arena.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a moonwalk in the lobby for kids. The public-address
announcer describes every Bulls score with the cry of,
``Goooooal.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost enough to make you forget that the season opener had
to be canceled because of unsafe ice. Potholes developed where ads
had been placed, and the ice never froze properly.
</P>
<P>
   Although not quite holding the rich tradition of football,
hockey tradition here runs deeper than in most Southern cities. The
city had teams in the since-disbanded World Hockey Association
(1976-79) and the Central Hockey League (1979-81).
</P>
<P>
   _ Merchandising: ``My other car is a Zamboni'' bumper sticker;
12 kinds of hats; hockey masks in three colors; stuffed bulls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nourishment: Burgers, dogs, ``Gus BBQ Pork'' and three of the
team's major sponsors _ Budweiser, Finlandia, Jack Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Between periods: Bicycle races on ice; the absolute worst
Elvis impersonator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best promotions: Family Fun Zone with interactive games in the
arena lobby; kids' summer hockey program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never thought you'd see: One man, David Berkman, being allowed
to have ownership in three teams _ Birmingham, Pensacola,
Jacksonville _ in the same league. ECHL bylaws prohibit his making
trades or waiver transactions between his teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
