</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FAYETT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Force unafraid to be zany
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. _ It's one hour before faceoff and George
Butterfly, a.k.a. Mr. Puck, is getting his game face on. He is
dressed in black shorts, a psychedelic T-shirt, clown shoes, a bow
tie and a puck hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 48, but I'm only one in puck years,'' says the mascot of
the CHL's Fayetteville Force. ``I'm on medication now. I don't
drool anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterfly/Puck is not a converted hockey fan but a Northern
transplant. ``I'm from New York, and this is as close as I get to
my Rangers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Force is owned by the promotion-oriented Bill Coffey, a
long-time minor-league hockey executive, and plays in Crown
Coliseum (9,715), a facility impressive enough that the NHL's
Carolina Hurricanes almost made it a temporary home until their
arena in Raleigh was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The team nickname plays off nearby Fort Bragg. ``The military
has a $3 billion payroll,'' Coffey explains. ``That's a lot of
money floating around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Force sold out its final home game last year, its inaugural
season. Average attendance is down about 700 to 3,300 this year,
but Coffey is always looking for new gimmicks to bring in fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fayetteville also has something no other Southern hockey team
does: a member of the Guiness Book of World Records. General
manager Kevin McNaught scored 25 points (seven goals, 18 assists)
in a British Super League game. ``To tell you the truth, I didn't
want anybody in my family or friends to find out, because I didn't
want them to know how bad the league was,'' McNaught says.
</P>
<P>
   McNaught, a Canadian, said hockey in Fayetteville and London
have one thing in common: ``People here don't know a lot about
hockey, just like there. But they want to have fun. And I guess
they like the fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Merchandising: Original logo with ``demonic-looking'' _
Coffey's words _ dragon was canned after complaints from scared
kids. New army-looking, bandaged hockey player is a hit on jerseys,
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nourishment: First choice is ``The Boss Hawg'' BBQ.
</P>
<P>
   _ Between periods: Fans shoot pucks at empty beer cases. You win
a full case for every one you knock over.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best promotions: Win a drawing to ride on the Zamboni between
periods. It got out of hand one night when a woman, emboldened by
beer, flashed the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never thought you'd see: Dasherboard with a ``Bill Claydon's
Tattoo World'' ad. The original board spelled it tatoo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
