</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devils waken offense
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Something has happened to Team Sleepeze.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Devils, believed to be the only team in NHL
history to win the Stanley Cup and concurrently gain a national
endorsement from the Association for Chronic Insomniacs, seemingly
have undergone a transformation this season. The former masters of
the wait-wait-wait-for-a-break-and-win-games 2-1 have opened up the
offense and continue to win with a roster that only slightly
resembles the Cup winners of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Lou Lamoriello insists, ``It wasn't our intent
to change our style,'' this season under first-year coach Robbie
Ftorek, who replaced Jacques Lemaire. But that's the appearance.
New Jersey recently had a five-game stretch during which it scored
five goals or more in each game for the first time in franchise
history. Through 30 games, the Devils were one of only four teams
averaging at least 3.0 goals per game (Toronto, Detroit and Phoenix
were the others).
</P>
<P>
   There was little sign this was coming. New Jersey scored only 12
goals in six exhibition games, then lost their first two of the
regular season (2-1 and 3-1) for the first time in five years
before taking off. The Devils had runs of four straight wins and
one loss in a stretch of 13 games (9-1-3). They've also continued
to operate as a sports executive's dream, winning with a payroll
($27.7 million) that ranks 21st of 27 teams and is dwarfed by that
of their border rivals, the New York Rangers ($39.8 million), who
struggle nonetheless. This team does not include what are arguably
the five best forwards from the '95 team: Stephane Richer, John
MacLean, Neal Broten, Bill Guerin and Claude Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made some difficult decisions, but they've usually
worked out for us,'' said Lamoriello, who declined to match
Chicago's $6 million-a-year offer to free-agent center Doug
Gilmour. ``We've always tried to stay consistent and not let the
fans or the media make decisions for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were consistent under Lemaire, perfecting the
neutral-zone trap defense that smothered opposing offenses and
eventually led to rule changes to open the game back up. But
Lemaire's Devils won only one playoff series in the three seasons
that came after the Cup and he resigned in May, six days after the
team was bounced by Ottawa in the first round. Lamoriello said the
decision was entirely Lemaire's (who remains in the organization as
a Tampa-based ``consultant,'' but he may eventually leave to coach
elsewhere).
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek, an assistant coach for two years but in the organization
for seven, was promoted to replace Lemaire. There were skeptics. In
his only previous head coaching stint, with Los Angeles, Ftorek
went 65-56-11 and won one playoff game in a year and a half. He
also reportedly clashed with then-King Wayne Gretzky, which isn't
conducive to job security.
</P>
<P>
   But under Ftorek, the Devils have trapped less and attacked
more. Lamoriello said the change has less to do with philosophy
than it does the team's youth. Of New Jersey's top eight scorers,
five are 25 or younger, including 22-year-old points leader Petr
Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when a team is playing a certain way, perception
becomes reality,'' Lamoriello said. ``With the type of players we
have, young, highly skilled forwards that we've been bringing
along, we felt it was time to let them go. Robbie has been in the
organization for a number of years, so we have a similar philosophy
about things. We're still a team where defense is very important.
People are looking at what we're doing offensively and think we've
changed. But I think by the end of the year, we'll be as good a
defensive team as we were before. . . . The trap is an overused ...
word. We've been tagged (unfairly). We're just a quicker team now
than we were last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
