<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY27-COX     12-26 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Asheville's Team Gretzky
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ During a recent road trip through various
Northern hamlets in the United Hockey League, the coach of the
Asheville Smoke directed the team bus driver to go to Brantford,
Ontario, for a stopover.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to Keith Gretzky that his players might want to see
the city where Alexander Graham Bell invented the telephone and
Gretzky's brother reinvented the game of hockey. And don't ask
which feat is held in higher regard in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to my parents' house and showed them all the
trophies,'' Gretzky said. ``Their basement is, like, the Hockey
Hall of Fame. They all took turns putting on some of Wayne's old
jerseys and having their pictures taken.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have connections. Keith Gretzky, coach and general
manager of the Asheville Smoke, is a younger brother of Wayne
Gretzky, widely considered the sport's greatest player. So is
forward Brent Gretzky, who has played much of this season in
Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an instant marketing dream come true for Smoke owner
Dan Williams. He moved the team last year _ out of Brantford, where
it flopped at the gate _ and brought it to a mountain resort known
more for bookstores, New Age shops and changing leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gretzky) is the one name everybody knows,'' Williams said.
``It has created an identity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent, 26, may be familiar to Atlanta hockey fans, having played
for the since-departed Knights and getting called up for cameo
apperances by the NHL's Tampa Bay Lightning 1993-95. He bounced
around the minors, playing on four teams in three U.S. leagues
before signing with a club in Austria. He was set to return to
Austria this year for a second season but came home because the
team, having financial difficulties, reneged on housing promises.
</P>
<P>
   Brent, who had resisted offers to play with Keith, 31, in
California for three years, decided to contact his brother in
Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Keith at 11 o'clock at night, and we had a deal in an
hour and a half,'' Brent said. ``A lot of people say, `How can you
play in this league?' But sometimes that's what you have to do, and
it's worked out great. Plus I had the security of playing for
Keith. I get a lot of ice time.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing an estimated $50,000 salary, compared to Wayne's $6
million with the New York Rangers, Brent scored 45 points in his
first 20 games with the Smoke before being called up by Hershey in
the AHL. He played well in six games, then returned to Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   On the hockey ladder, the AHL is two steps higher than the UHL,
but Brent is having such a good time that he might decline an offer
to play with Hershey for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Keith also enjoys Asheville. Had the Smoke remained in
Brantford, ``I never would have coached there,'' the former
European and minor-league player said. ``I like the States.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gretzkys often are taunted about their famed sibling. ``In
Utica, some guy held up a sign saying, `You'll never be like
Wayne,''' Brent said. ``They were throwing garbage in the penalty
box at me. I expect to get hit on the ice. But the garbage? I guess
it comes with the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The tradeoff: Wayne, 37, gave Keith an autographed stick to be
raffled off at a recent game to raise money for the team, which
also uses equipment Wayne's company supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Did the renowned brother supply it for free?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but we got a family discount,'' Keith said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
