<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HOCKEYBOOM27-COX     12-26 2011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEYBOOM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South afire over hockey
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the chuck-a-puck contest, before spotlights and
FM tunes and the apparent rule that every minor-league hockey
player had to pass through an inflatable smoking animal before
skating onto the ice, there was just the game and the owner and the
traveling team bus with the hole in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, my first bus was used in `Slapshot,''' said Bill
Coffey, owner of the Central Hockey League's Fayetteville (N.C.)
Force, referring to a satirical movie that is as embraced in the
hockey world as ``Caddyshack'' is in golf. ``That's when I owned
Winston-Salem in the Atlantic Coast League. Bus had a hole in the
floor. A man could fall right through and fall right to the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how teams would issue helmets and gloves and shoulder
pads in training camp? I used to issue sleeping bags. Players were,
like, `What's this? We already have bunks.' Then they'd get on the
bus and find out there was no heat. Drove that thing in the winter
and snow would blow up through the hole, so you had to bundle up.''
</P>
<P>
   That first bus _ not to be confused with the bus he acquired in
exchange for his rights to another franchise _ now sits in a North
Carolina junkyard, Coffey said. In the interim, the sport of hockey
has been repackaged and distributed as at no time before,
particularly in the South.
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta Thrashers make their NHL debut in the fall,
they will represent at least the fourth hockey team in Georgia,
joining minor-league franchises in Macon, Columbus and Augusta,
with another possibly relocating to Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is not even ahead of the curve. There are eight
franchises in Florida and seven in Louisiana, including the
Lafayette-based IceGators, a member of the mushrooming East Coast
Hockey League and the gold standard for minor-league teams. Even
with a drop in attendance this season, the IceGators have a
season-ticket base in excess of 7,000 and average crowds of 9,800
in an 11,000-seat building.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Road doesn't quite resemble the Canadian provinces, but
it's getting there. North Carolina has four hockey teams, with a
possible relocation on the way. The Asheville Smoke couldn't make
it in Brantford, Ontario, the birthplace of Wayne Gretzky, but is
thriving in the hometown of Thomas Wolfe. Tennessee owns three
franchises, including the NHL's hip Nashville Predators. South
Carolina has three teams, with a commitment for a fourth, including
the Greenville Grrrowl, sports' only nickname that comes equipped
with woofers. The ECHL team is owned by former longtime NBA
executive Carl Scheer, who has sold all 30 suites at $45,000 a pop
in the new 14,000-seat Bi-Lo Center.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 40 franchises are spread out over seven leagues
operating in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia
and West Virginia. You can visit the Everblades in Florida, feast
on Kingfish in Baton Rouge, hit the Lynx in Augusta, run with the
Throroughblades in Kentucky or, if in the mood, make Whoopee in
Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Desrosiers, coach of the ECHL's Birmingham Bulls,
recalled when the team moved from Cincinnati. ``There was some
controversy at the time whether the team should come here, because
some of the other owners thought it was too far south,'' he said.
``Now we're the northern-most team in our division.''
</P>
<P>
   To Thrashers vice president of marketing Derek Schiller, the
boom ``without a doubt'' will have a positive impact on the NHL
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the ability to make anybody a hockey fan, and thus an
Atlanta Thrashers fan, is to have some understanding what the sport
is,'' Schiller said. ``Part of that understanding is going to a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller expects the Thrashers to evolve into a regional
attraction. ``I would compare it to the Braves drawing from a lot
of the minor-league communities in the South,'' he said. ``We have
the same expectations. We'll market fully in those towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the expansion
</P>
<P>
   There is no single overriding theory why hockey and the South
now seem as perfectly partnered as grits and Canadian bacon.
Actually, there are six:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Gretzky. Doesn't it always start with him? When Gretzky
was traded from Edmonton to Los Angeles in 1988, it spurred
sellouts in a previously half-empty building and stimulated NHL
expansion or franchise relocation in areas not terribly familiar
with Toe Blake, dump-and-chase or the Original Six. Soon, pucks
were flying in San Jose, Anaheim, Miami, Tampa Bay, Dallas,
Phoenix, Nashville and Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern migration. The economic boom has created a haven for
transplanted Northern fans. Hockey generally has defied the belief
of the late Jack Kent Cooke, first owner of the L.A. Kings, who
said, ``The reason all the Canadians moved to California was to get
away from hockey.'' But Coffey believes a number of the Southern
teams are not dependent on transplants. ``These are just
Southerners catching on to hockey,'' he said. ``When we started (in
Fayetteville) last year, I bet you nine out of 10 people didn't
know what offsides was.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Marketing and promotion. Hockey was the last sport to catch on
to the idea, and it started mimicking minor-league baseball. ``We
recognized that a game was an entertainment event and that the
hockey was just a part of that,'' ECHL president Richard Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, every between-periods intermission is filled with
wackiness. In chuck-a-puck, the most common game, fans can buy a
foam-rubber puck for $1, write their names on it, then throw it to
a designated spot at center ice. Closest to the spot wins cash or a
souvenir of his or her choice. At worst, a team will collect $1,500
in exchange for a $75 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only two things I won't use are politicians and animals,''
Fayetteville's Coffey said. Fortunately, he wasn't part of the
ill-fated guess-the-weight-of-the-cow night in Muskegon, Mich.,
several years ago. The cow slipped on the ice, broke all four legs
and had to be destroyed on the site.
</P>
<P>
   But Coffey did once hold a ``Fight Night'' in which he ordered
four ambulances to circle the arena. ``The city attorney wasn't
very happy,'' he said. ``It turned out there weren't any fights,
but we had a great crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Secondary markets. Teams are thriving predominantly in areas
where there is no other pro sports franchise, except perhaps
minor-league baseball. Particularly in the South, hockey is being
exposed for the first time in smaller cities, and potental fans
don't have _ or care about _ a reference point. Whether it's the
NHL or the Class A equivalent United Hockey League, it's just
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that Miami, a major sports town, is last in
the ECHL in attendance. The NHL's Carolina Hurricanes are a
major-league team dying in a minor-league town (Greensboro) until
its arena in Raleigh is complete. Greensboro residents have
supported minor-league teams in the past but won't pay NHL prices,
let alone to a temporary tenant. It's expected that when the
Hurricanes move to Raleigh next season, the American Hockey League
will shift its franchise in New Haven, Conn., back to Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   _ Affordability and backlash against major leagues. Scheer says
rising ticket prices and a ``bad trend'' in television revenues led
him away from the NBA and into part-ownership of an ECHL team in
Charlotte four years ago. ``I didn't like the way consumers were
being treated,'' he said. ``I didn't see a future in the CBA
because college basketball was so big, but hockey was different. It
had enormous appeal to a midsize city in a blue-collar environment.
It had the physicalness of it, the fighting. It had the finesse.
And most important, it was affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Growth of in-line skating. It led to the roller-hockey fad and
an understanding of the game and partly has fueled the increase of
construction in ice rinks in the South. The Asheville Civic Center
didn't have ice until the UHL's Smoke announced plans to move there
this year. ``I never saw a rink made until I came here,'' said
Smoke forward Kris Schultz, a Saskatchewan native. ``Where I'm
from, there's towns with 2,500 people that have two rinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose structure to leagues
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's minor leagues are not as structured as baseball's. All
NHL franchises have one major affiliate in the American or
International leagues, which is comparable to baseball's AAA level.
Some also will supply players to the ECHL (AA). The Central, United
and Western Pro and West Coast leagues are roughly Class A, also
called ``Plumbers League,'' with few players whose rights are owned
by NHL teams.
</P>
<P>
   All leagues have salary caps, enabling them to control costs and
limit ticket prices. Players in the ECHL, CHL and UHL generally
earn $400 to $500 per week, plus housing. ``It's not quite the
business it is at the next level,'' said Dave Schultz, a former
Philadelphia Flyers bad boy who is coach and general manager of the
UHL's Mohawk Valley (N.Y.) Prowlers. ``These guys are just making a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Canadian players, however, have taken to Southern
towns and now find themselves rejecting promotions to the AHL or
IHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I didn't know what I was getting into when
I came here,'' said Birmingham forward Jamey Hicks, an Ontario
native who played two years in Europe. ``But I don't know if I ever
want to leave. I think one reason hockey players love the South is
we love to golf. It's a lot different going from practice to the
golf course instead of going home to shovel snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said he has turned down IHL teams, adding, ``To go some
place for a few weeks for an extra $100 a week, it's not worth it.
It used to be guys would keep their bags packed, just praying for
the day to go to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has seen more changes than Coffey. His entry into hockey
came 15 years ago when he asked the Winston-Salem Thunderbirds if
they needed an accountant. The team and its league have since
folded, as have two other ventures. He helped launch the five-team
ECHL in 1988. Franchises could be had for $25,000. Now, expansion
fees are $2 million, and the league is 27 teams deep, with an
intended cap of 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we (expanded) to Tallahassee in 1994, they were an island
down there,'' Adams said. ``Then we went to Lafayette and drew
10,000 (per game). Then they put ice in in Baton Rouge and we went
there, then the same in Pensacola. Now we have nine or 10 teams
along I-10.''
</P>
<P>
   It has grown too large for Coffey, who used to drive not only
the bus to the games but the Zamboni during them to smooth the ice.
``At some point, there is going to be some serious consolidation,''
he said. ``All of these leagues and teams can't survive.''
</P>
<P>
   He also subscribes to the ``three-and-done'' rule, claiming that
after three years the newness will wear off with a number of teams
and crowds will start to drop. It already has occurred in
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey's Fayetteville team is averaging 3,300 fans, not great
but enough for now. He says he has done ``very well'' from selling
ECHL teams in Knoxville and Greensboro. He didn't exactly sell
Winston-Salem, instead agreeing to give up his share of the team to
partners in exchange for the team bus, which he wanted to bring
with him to Knoxville in 1988, the ECHL's birth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I announced I was putting a team in Knoxville, one
reporter said to me, `You'll be bankrupt by the end of the year,'''
Coffey said. ``But we did great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, we didn't even get there until late September and the
season was starting in October. We didn't even have dasherboards. I
hired three people to build them in 26 hours, around the clock. A
lot of these billionaire (owners) won't go into a place now unless
everything is done. They never would have survived back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Least of all, without a sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
