<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MACON27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Macon Whoopee no easy sell
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ It's another Central Hockey League season, another
reason for Macon Whoopee.
</P>
<P>
   The world's best sports-franchise nickname is back for a third
season, tripling the lifespan of the Southern Hockey League's Macon
Whoopees, who unfortunately didn't check opponents as well as their
owner bounced checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Whoopee's five-headed ownership group is down to two,
including CEO Jeffery Fried, a Macon physician, who concedes,
``I've realized this takes a lot of work to make it profitable. I
thought crowds would just automatically show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, Fried hired a new president, Keith Burdette,
who has imported several promotions from his previous team in
Memphis and plans a grand expansion of the Whoopee Web site, which
should be a gold mine for merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   Burdette also plans to unveil a new ``spicier'' logo for a third
jersey, although it will include the current fig leaf _ ``everybody
thinks it's a maple leaf.'' A mascot also might be created,
although it could be dangerous given the team's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is happier about the franchise's resurrection than
Spencer Barnes, who professes to be the first season-ticket holder
of Whoopees '73. ``It's like I'm reborn again,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes says about the players, ``They were a lot meaner back
then.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach and general manager is John Paris, who led the former
Atlanta Knights to an IHL championship. Asked if he ever thought he
would coach a team called the Whoopee, Paris says, ``No. But I knew
the song.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Merchandising: Two things you won't find in any other arena
are the book, ``Once Upon A Whoopee,'' about the ill-fated
Whoopsters of 1973-74, and the ``10 reasons for Macon Whoopee''
T-shirt. Among the few printable ones for family readership is,
``Your parents cheer when you score.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nourishment: Food is standard burgers and dogs, but there are
two bars serving mixed drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Between periods: There's nothing like Human Ice Bowling _
helmeted fans on sleds sliding into inflatable pins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best promotion: The Macon Whoopee ``One Night Stand'' includes
15 seats and a keg of beer for $450.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never thought you'd see: A kiosk to apply for a Macon Whoopee
MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
