<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLEAST27-COX     12-26 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gardens party
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Much has been made of the fact the Toronto Maple Leafs
will move out of antiquated Maple Leaf Gardens in February and into
the new Air Canada Centre. But as coach Pat Quinn said, ``Maybe
we'll run down to the new place and destroy it.'' The Leafs went
12-4-2 in their first 18 home games, on pace for their best home
record in 30 years. Toronto has had losing home records the last
two years. The Leafs' league-high of 105 goals in 32 games _
including 19 in consecutive wins over Phoenix, the New York Rangers
and Pittsburgh _ also left them at a full-season pace of 269 goals,
75 more than last season. In crediting Quinn for the turnaround,
left winger Derek King unwittingly took a shot at former coach Mike
Murphy, saying, ``Pat is letting us be creative instead of just
dumping (the puck) in. In the past, we were too concerned with
keeping the puck out of our net and not concerned enough about
putting it in the other net.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuffled off
</P>
<P>
   Despite having one of the best records in the Eastern
Conference, Buffalo general manager Darcy Regier is feeling some
heat for getting only a second-round draft pick from Los Angeles
for forward Donald Audette. Audette, who was unsigned, led the
Sabres in goals last season and scored on his first shift with the
Kings, who have been desperate for offensive help. ``We were not
offered players who we thought would come in and contribute to the
hockey club right now,'' Regier said. ``If we had been performing
poorly, there would have been more pressure to sign Donald or get a
player who could help us right now.'' Sabres forward Brian
Holzinger appeared to second-guess Regier, saying, ``My personal
feeling is he's a guy we need on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho ho ho
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Penguins are losing their shirts but they haven't
lost their sense of humor. In a videotaped holiday greeting that
was played on the Civic Arena scoreboard, coach Kevin Constantine
said, ``We hope that your holiday spending hasn't left you, shall
we say, bankrupt?'' The Penguins, in the midst of bankruptcy
proceedings, sold out only one of the first 12 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera
</P>
<P>
   After Anaheim's Travis Green hit New York's Kenny Jonsson from
behind, Islanders coach Mike Milbury called Green a ``gutless
puke'' and added, ``I don't know what day they come into Long
Island, but it will be interesting.'' . . . As Montreal continues
to struggle, trade rumors concerning Mark Recchi heat up. The
winger is an unrestricted free agent after the season and probably
won't be re-signed by the Canadiens. ... Lost in Montreal's 10-game
winless streak at midweek was that Jeff Hackett, acquired from
Chicago, appears to have solved the goaltending problems. Hackett
stopped 35 of 37 shots against Dallas, but the Canadiens only tied
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
