</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odds against Paris for Thrashers coaching spot
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thrashers general manager Don Waddell says he has
``probably 200'' resumes from qualified coaches and scouts seeking
positions with the team, and John Paris makes it no secret that he
represents one of them. Paris coached the IHL's Atlanta Knights
when the since-departed team won that league's Turner Cup title.
Now, he is coach and general manager of the Macon Whoopee of the
Central Hockey League. Paris said he has had offers to work for
other teams in the CHL or ECHL but he has stayed in Macon. ``I like
living in Georgia,'' he said. ``(And) I knew the Thrashers were
coming into the league. Everybody knows why I stayed here. We'll
see if it works out.'' The odds are against Paris. Waddell has
completed the scouting staff, and Paris probably won't be a
candidate for the head coaching position. Whoever is chosen as the
head coach will pick his own assistants. Other positions to be
filled include a lawyer or financial person in the front office to
deal with contracts, trainers, equipment people and a publicist. .
. . Waddell flew to Winnipeg on Christmas day for the World Junior
Championships. He estimated that ``20 of the 28'' first-round picks
will be in the tournament, and the Thrashers will staff it
accordingly, with five scouts. . . . The Thrashers will conduct a
street hockey clinic for physically disabled youth Monday (10
a.m.-noon) at the Robert D. Fowler YMCA in Norcross. The clinic is
being held in conjunction with the American Association of Adapted
Sports Programs. . . . Club hockey teams from Georgia, Georgia
Tech, Florida and Tennessee will take part in an inaugural hockey
tournament in Savannah Jan. 8-9. The games, at the Savannah Civic
Center, will decide the winner of the ``Thrasher Cup'' _ yes, named
for the team. Savannah also is interested in bringing a Thrashers
exhibition game to the city.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING SPREE
