<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is the Red Wing's Panic premature?
 &HT;    By Jeff Schutlz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Detroit is coming off consecutive Stanley Cups and
appears in control in the Central Division. But when the Red Wings
lost to Dallas last week for the third time in a row, speculation
grew that management might try to alter the team's chemistry with a
trade or two. But former Wings assistant general manager Don
Waddell, now with the Thrashers, says he thinks there has been too
much focus on the Dallas games because ``those games are lot more
important to Dallas than they are to Detroit.'' One statistic is
worth noting, however. Through 31 games, Detroit was 0-7 against
division leaders and only 4-10 against teams with .500 or winning
records. ``We're not fooled by our record by any means,''
defenseman Larry Murphy said. ``We haven't had much success against
the stronger teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Expansion nightmare
</P>
<P>
   Nashville goalie Mike Dunham (10-9-1, .912 saves percentage),
the primary reason the Predators have been competitive this season,
also might be the center of the team's possible forthcoming slide.
Dunham will be out at least three weeks with a strained groin. If
it sounds familiar, it's because he also suffered a groin injury in
training camp, then aggravated it Nov. 29, then was reinjured when
he came back two weeks later. ``It's not chronic,'' Dunham insists.
``It's just that we didn't let it heal 100 percent from the last
time, and the muscle wasn't strong enough. I'm not worried about
letting this affect the rest of my career. I just need to let it
heal completely this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bure to Belarus?
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver holdout Pavel Bure, who isn't talking to the U.S.
media but apparently has no problem discussing his future on
European television, says he has an offer to play in Belarus next
season. Bure has been skating with the Russian national team in
Moscow. Calgary's Valeri Bure, who speaks to his brother by
telephone often, said, ``I don't know what Vancouver is going to
do, but he might not even come back here. He might play in Belarus
and make the same type of money that he would here. . . . He
sounded (on the telephone) like he wanted to get back to playing,
but he can't let that get into his head. It's tough, though, for
him to sit at home and watch the other guys play.''
</P>
<P>
   Et cetera
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton general manager Glen Sather denies a Canadian TV report
that he is close to firing coach Ron Low: ``Do these guys make this
stuff up? There's absolutely no truth to this at all. Ronnie's done
an exceptional job. Every time a team goes for a slide, is it
supposed to be time to get rid of the coach? We're in first place
in our division, and we haven't had Doug Weight. I'd say that's
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
