<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran to players: Invest
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Wednesday night's secret David Stern-Billy Hunter
meeting at the Los Angeles office of agent Leonard Armato in mind,
here's a little NBA story for some perspective on today's impasse
over mega-bucks.
</P>
<P>
   This is about a 6-foot-6 guard with the musical name of Shaler
Halimon, who in 1969 was dealt from Philadelphia to the Bulls with
Chet Walker for Jim Washington, now an Atlantan.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Super Shay'' for his entertaining and individualistic
style, Halimon never fit with coach Dick Motta's conservative game,
but before the advent of the three-point basket he once registered
four points in one second to help the Bulls beat Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Halimon today is a bus driver in Portland, where he played after
being traded by the Bulls in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   He's been working for the transportation company for 17 years
and figures he has 10 years until retirement. With his $1,400 a
month NBA pension and good investments, he says, ``I'll be in good
shape. Gosh, if I would have made (today's minimum salary of)
$250,000 a year, I would have never had to work again.''
</P>
<P>
   Halimon told Oregonian columnist Dwight Jaynes, ``You know, the
greatest thing man ever invented was compound interest. So many of
these young basketball players never learned that. Most of them go
to college, but I don't think very many of them take finance
classes. They never learn how to take care of their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with all that money?'' wondered Halimon, whose
top salary was $60,000. ``There's only three things you need in the
world _ a home, food and a job. Most of those guys have four
houses, seven cars, two or three girlfriends, a lot of clothes and
about 16 people trailing along behind them. Have they ever heard of
mutual funds or zero-coupon bonds?''
</P>
<P>
   Solutions
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone denies that he and John Stockton are working behind
the scenes to bring the lockout deal to a vote, perhaps even
working on having David Falk clients Pat Ewing, Dikembe Mutombo,
Alonzo Mourning and Juwan Howard removed from leadership.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Malone says, ``I'm with the union.'' His agent,
Dwight Manley, says, ``I don't know that Karl has even talked to
John lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Manley also said, ``Karl would be glad to serve, if asked, but
he is not trying to usurp any power.''
</P>
<P>
   Some background on the frenzied efforts to save the season:
</P>
<P>
   As some might have expected, Stern's skiing vacation was a
calculated ploy, as was his announcement of a Jan. 7 ``drop-dead''
date. On two occasions, union leaders reneged publicly on verbal
agreements, infuriating Stern, who broke off negotiations each
time.
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials claim it happened a third time a week ago, after
which Stern suddenly announced he was off to his vacation home in
Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter has needed a deadline to get serious, believing that
Stern wouldn't get serious until the end. Meanwhile, his sport is
eroding as Charles Barkley, Malone, Tim Hardaway and now Kevin
Willis openly break with the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Learning game
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens can't coach the Hawks on the court during the
lockout, but he can coach in your den. Wilkens and long-time friend
and assistant Dick Helm have produced an instructive videotape and
booklet set, entitled ``The Basics,'' available at the Turner Store
and by telephone order at 800-261-3773. The teaching is done in
clear, concise language, with diagrams and player demonstrations,
particularly effective for young players. The bad news: The set is
a very pricey $39.99.
</P>
<P>
   Under repairs
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Pervis Ellison isn't the malingerer some Celtics believed.
The Savannah native quietly had surgery last month to repair a
tendon in his right ankle. That solves the physical issue and helps
quiet the negative rumblings among Ellison's bosses after he failed
to respond properly to rehab on the injury that originally occurred
Jan. 7 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what it was, but I knew it was more than just a
sprained ankle,'' Ellison said. ``Nothing I did for it seemed to
help, so I finally went to see a doctor at Johns Hopkins, and he
found the torn tendon. I had the surgery about four weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden silence
</P>
<P>
   Here's a holiday gift for the ears: Jim Chones, one of the worst
game analysts of all time has left the booth in Cleveland to become
a coach at Orange High School, where the star players happen to be
his 14-year-old triplet sons _ Kyle (6-4), Kendall (6-5) and
Kameron (6-1). The left-handed freshmen have a lot of their
father's mannerisms on the court and, it is hoped, none of his
penchant for verbosity.
</P>
<P>
   A fortune
</P>
<P>
   Australian Chris Antsy can't understand the grumbling over an
extra million here and there in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference if you make $10 million a year or $9
million a year? How much difference does it make to your lifestyle?
It's going to be more than most people see in a lifetime, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish someone would explain it to me. I played my first three
years of professional basketball in Australia, and my total salary
was $150,000, and I was happy with that. Right now, I'm making
($713,900 last year), less than half the average salary, and I
couldn't be happier with what I'm making. I never thought I'd make
this much in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness
</P>
<P>
   Think players don't mellow with age? Look to Rick Mahorn. In
Mahorn's early years in the league, he never smiled. Now, he grins
even when he knocks you down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to the point where you realize that all you want to do
is be healthy enough to go out there and play the game,'' Mahorn
says.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Royal can relate to that. The Hornets free agent is on
the mend from surgery for colon cancer. On Monday, he takes a blood
test to see if his white cells have returned to normal so he can
resume full-scale workouts, with a comeback in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
