</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making a list . . . checking it twice
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New York Jets assistant head coach Bill Belichick, the
eventual heir to Bill Parcells, may not hang around and wait for
''The Tuna'' to retire. Belichick last week contacted Baltimore
vice president Ozzie Newsome seeking permission to speak with
current Ravens assistants about the possibility of joining him if
he lands a head coaching job. Ravens assistant head coach Kirk
Ferentz, receivers coach Richard Mann, special teams coach Scott
O'Brien and strength coach Jerry Simmons all worked for Belichick
when he was head coach of the old Cleveland Browns franchise.
Belichick interviewed for the Oakland vacancy last year and is
certain to draw interest for some of the jobs coming open.
</P>
<P>
   . . . Checking it twice
</P>
<P>
   Seattle president Bob Whitsitt, who won't waste much time in
dismissing coach Dennis Erickson, may seek permission to talk with
Steelers defensive coordinator Jim Haslett as early as this week.
Whitsitt and vice president Randy Mueller also will speak with
former 49ers coach George Seifert. Owner Paul Allen, who failed to
land Mike Holmgren a year ago, won't make a second run at the
Packers coach. Mueller has distinguished himself enough to preclude
having a coach-general manager position anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Paup-ularity contest
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville linebacker Bryce Paup continues to be distressed at
the way he was used this season by coordinator Dick Jauron and is
having a hard time biting his tongue. The Jags promised Paup he'd
be a pass-rush force again, but the nine-year veteran more often is
used in coverage. When he earned defensive MVP honors with Buffalo
in '95, Paup rushed on nearly 80 percent of the snaps. This year he
has rushed 38 percent of the time. Jacksonville is paying Paup
$6.95 million in '98 and he has just 5 1/2 sacks. Meanwhile, Jags
owner Wayne Weaver is becoming increasingly frustrated with agent
Bob Fraley as he attempts to negotiate a contract extension for
coach Tom Coughlin. Ever since the fiasco two years ago with Bill
Parcells' contract in New England, Fraley has sought more clout for
his clients and is meticulous in nailing down every clause. Witness
how long it took the Falcons to finalize a deal with Dan Reeves,
another Fraley client, after they had an agreement with him.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall law
</P>
<P>
   Colts tailback Marshall Faulk needs 122 receiving yards today to
join Roger Craig as the only players in NFL history to reach 1,000
yards each rushing and receiving in the same season. But Faulk may
get just scant playing time from coach Jim Mora against the
Panthers. The multi-talented back has been late for several
meetings the past two weeks, and some disciplining may be the
result. Also, there continues to be a disagreement over a clause in
Faulk's contract. Agent Rocky Arceneaux claims Faulk is a free
agent if he finishes among the top five rushers, while GM Bill
Polian contends that isn't the case. Faulk enters the weekend No. 6
in the league, 18 yards behind Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has yet to be announced, 16-year guard Bruce
Matthews has agreed to a contract extension with the Oilers. ...
Jerry Jones Al Davis Jimmy Johnson Look for Steelers president Dan
Rooney Bill CowherRay Sherman Neil O'DonnellRonald MooreBrock
Marion Doug Flutie leg injury and Rob JohnsonWade Phillips
</P>
