<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cardinals reviving
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Including victories in both matchups this season, the
Dallas Cowboys have defeated the Arizona Cardinals in 16 of 18
meetings during the '90s. That dominance aside, the last team
Cowboys players want to see at Texas Stadium for the first round of
the playoffs next weekend is the upstart Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up 28-0 the last time we played and barely hung on to
beat them (35-28 on Nov. 15),'' Dallas strong safety Darren Woodson
said. ``They started playing `street ball' with no huddles, the
quarterback was running around making a lot of big plays, and we
about died. They're a dangerous team that I could do without (in
the playoffs).''
</P>
<P>
   The decimated Cowboys are the division champion most observers
see headed for an early playoff exit, and the Cardinals are the
wild-card entry everybody wants to avoid. Provided, of course,
Arizona evens qualifies for its first postseason since the
truncated '82 season.
</P>
<P>
   A victory today over San Diego _ no gimme, because the Chargers
quietly own the NFL's top-rated defense _ will secure Arizona the
lone vacancy left on the Super Bowl tournament dance card. More
important to personnel director Bob Ferguson and coach Vince Tobin,
it will provide positive reinforcement necessary for a young roster
that probably doesn't realize yet how good it can become.
</P>
<P>
   Like most playoff-bound teams in a league diluted by free-agency
and the accompanying lack of depth, the Cardinals have holes. The
safeties are pedestrian, the offensive line makeshift, the
defensive front ravaged by injuries and the kicking inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   But give credit to Tobin, and more notably Ferguson, for
dragging owner Bill Bidwill into football's modern age. One of the
game's most unloved losers, Bidwill has loosened his purse strings
to acquire key free agents, turned most of the football decisions
over to football people and actually demonstrated the kind of
vision that has been foreign to the franchise's limp legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the turnaround is quarterback Jake Plummer, who last week
agreed to a contract extension that made him the
second-highest-paid player in the league. A skinny passer from
Idaho who brought his derring-do playing style to Arizona State,
the second-year veteran probably will return the Cardinals'
investment with increased ticket sales. Fans in the Valley of the
Sun, who watched Plummer take ASU to the Rose Bowl his senior
season, are betting that he eventually will get the Cardinals to a
title game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are betting on it as well, to the tune of a $15
million signing bonus, and $7.425 million average compensation in
the next four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing thing is that I had to sell everybody, including
Vince, on him,'' Ferguson said, remembering the passionate debate
that transpired in the second round of the '97 draft. ``Vince was
afraid Jake would come in and be a flop, and then we'd have to
release the golden boy of Arizona State football.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the emerging star has rallied the Cardinals to comeback
victories in eight of his 24 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is the foundation in the rebuilding of the team, but the
Cards have other bricks as well. Ferguson is a savvy football guy
who tended bar, sold shells in Hawaii, drove a beer truck, did
public relations for a hydroplane-racing team and booked the
appearances of the Seattle Seahawks cheerleaders while trying to
break into the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   He has drafted wisely and spent judiciously on key free agents.
As demonstrated in 1997, when he browbeat Bidwill into signing
standout wide receiver Frank Sanders to a huge contract extension
that kept the former Auburn star off the free-agent market, he has
worked hard to retain nucleus players. The last thing Ferguson
wants is for his carefully constructed house of Cards to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the playoffs today would be the next, but not the
final, step.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in training camp, fullback Larry Centers tricked
then-rookie Plummer into carting a dead skunk into his dorm room by
convincing the quarterback that the plastic bag he handed him
contained a takeout order of chicken wings. The Cowboys' Darren
Woodson agrees that Plummer isn't about to fall for such hijinks
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team,'' Woodson said, ``doesn't stink anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
