<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Niners still in flux?
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's still plenty of smoke to the speculation that
Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren could end up back in San Francisco,
and recent events have fanned the flames. About 10 days ago,
current 49ers coach Steve Mariucci told his agent, Don Yee, he was
prepared to sign a contract extension he'd been considering for
months. Mariucci's rationale was that the uncertainty over
ownership, and the possible return of Ed DeBartolo Jr., still was
superceded by security through the 2005 season. But then the team
suddenly began ''negotiating in reverse,'' in the words of one
party involved, and slowed the talks with Mariucci. If Bill Walsh
returns as team president, there's little doubt he'll push for the
hiring of Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Vikes strikes
</P>
<P>
   Credit the Vikings for a preemptive strike Christmas Eve,
signing quarterback Randall Cunningham and right tackle Korey
Stringer to five-year extensions. Both would have been among the
most coveted players in the '99 free agent market. The move allows
the Vikings to keep intact a line that may be the league's best. In
addition to Stringer, three other starters _ left tackle Todd
Steussie and guards Randall McDaniel and David Dixon _ are signed
for 2-4 more seasons. The team still has several key free agents,
though, including middle 'backer Ed McDaniel, defensive linemen
Jerry Ball and Derrick Alexander, safeties Orlando Thomas and
Robert Griffith and corner Corey Fuller. Keeping Cunningham sets up
some intriguing possibilities with former starting quarterback Brad
Johnson, who is due a roster bonus of $1.15 million on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren redux
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty over where Holmgren will coach next season is
starting to wear thin on Packers GM Ron Wolf, who feels the
speculation has distracted the club. Holmgren does not have a
21-day window to seek other positions, Wolf said last week, much to
the chagrin of agent Bob LaMonte. The Packers, who could be eyeing
Jets assistant coach Bill Belichick, among others, want a swift
resolution of Holmgren's status. Carolina owner Jerry Richardson
stopped only inches short of conceding he intends to pursue
Holmgren after dismissing incumbent Dom Capers in the next day or
two. Unless current Redskins president John Kent Cooke retains the
team, or the group including Joe Gibbs gets it, Holmgren will be a
candidate in Washington. Both Cooke and Gibbs' partner Sam Grossman
would keep Norv Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Giants steps
</P>
<P>
   Despite the three-game winning streak he has sparked since
replacing Danny Kanell, there's no way New York Giants quarterback
Kent Graham goes to camp as the clear-cut starter in '99. And even
though Gary Brown will probably go over 1,000 rushing yards today,
GM Ernie Accorsi plans to pursue a big-time tailback. That might
run counter to coach Jim Fassel, who has told some confidants he
feels LeShon Johnson, out all this season while recovering from
non-Hodgkins lymphoma, could come back and win the No. 1 tailback
spot. Look for Accorsi to woo quarterback Kerry Collins unless he
signs back with New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke turned down at least two offers to partner with other
groups attempting to buy the Redskins and his reluctance could cost
him the team. ... The fate of Bears coach Dave Wannstedt remains
uncertain, with team president Mike McCaskey cryptic about his
plans. McCaskey plans a weeklong vacation starting Monday to mull
things over. ... Jim ''Mouse'' McNallyRams coach Dick Vermeil Jerry
Rhome ... Panthers linebacker Kevin Greene
</P>
</TEXT>
