<SLUG> BC-FBN-ODDS-ENDS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-minute drill with Buffalo's Sam Gash
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Buffalo fullback Sam Gash.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: His selfless approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Background: An eighth-round pick of New England in 1992, the
former Penn State star signed with the Bills as an unrestricted
free agent this year. In 103 games, he has only 237 ``touches,''
including just 115 rushing attempts. Despite only 10 carries this
season, Gash was elected to the Pro Bowl squad for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The last four seasons, you've carried the ball a total of 32
times. Wouldn't you like to get 20-25 carries in a game just once?
</P>
<P>
   A: That kind of stuff only happens in my dreams. Man, I'm a
1,000-yard rusher when my eyes are closed. Seriously, I get excited
from putting a linebacker on his rear end, then watching somebody
else get the yards.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the key to being a good lead blocker?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a grunt job, so a lot of it is mental. Physical stuff,
like hitting square-up, gets to be second nature. You have to like
pain, because there's a train wreck every play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After making the Pro Bowl, what areas can you improve?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a lot of room for improvement in my blitz-pickup
technique. In the run game, it's seek and destroy, and I like
finding people to hit. Pass protection is different and more about
recognition and reading keys.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on . . .
</P>
<P>
   Veteran: In the past two weeks, Green Bay tailback Dorsey Levens
has rushed for 175 yards and seems to be rounding into shape after
a nine-week absence. Against a porous Chicago defense, Levens
figures to get 25 more rehabilitative carries this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie: Miami first-round tailback John Avery is allegedly
quicker on artificial surfaces, but his AstroTurf average (3.6
yards per carry) is no better than on grass (3.7). With Karim
Abdul-Jabbar injured, Avery gets a chance to test the Georgia Dome
rug today.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent: The Giants have won three in a row with reserve
quarterback Kent Graham and a fourth today could force Arizona to
defeat San Diego for the final wild-card berth. Graham once played
for the Cards, and he wouldn't mind turning up the heat on Vince
Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Despite winning the division, Jets coach Bill Parcells
had his team in pads last week because he wants the ground game
ready for the playoffs. That means offensive line coach John Matsko
better have the troops hyped for ``Tuna Bowl IV'' this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   This will be a tough week on coaches. Dom Capers (Carolina),
Dennis Erickson (Seattle), Ted Marchibroda (Baltimore) and Ray
Rhodes (Philadelphia) all figure to be fired by the middle of the
week. ... Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick, certain to
be a candidate for a number of vacancies, would like to take
Vikings offensive line coach Mike Tice with him. That could be a
problem in San Diego, where GM Bobby Beathard wants to retain
incumbent Joe Bugel. ... Any doubts about the future of Cincinnati
coach Bruce Coslet were quashed last week when owner Mike Brown
quietly extended the contracts of all the assistant coaches. ...
The latest rumor _ and that's all it is for now _ is that Kentucky
quarterback Tim Couch, having conferred with Peyton Manning, is
leaning toward staying in school. ... The Rams might consider Scott
Mitchell, who will be jettisoned by Detroit next spring, as
competition for Tony Banks. ... Amid speculation he will be fired
if Bill Walsh rejoins the team, San Francisco personnel director
Vinny Cerrato met with owner Eddie DeBartolo Jr. to attempt to
gauge his future.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up
</P>
<P>
   Just one year after a spinal cord injury ended his career,
former Lions linebacker Reggie Brown is getting on with his life.
Brown, 24, spends two days a week visiting patients with spinal
injuries. He will graduate from Texas A&AMP;M in May with a degree in
economics, and on Christmas he became engaged to longtime
girlfriend Kerrie Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart was replaced for the
second week in a row by Mike Tomczak because of ineffectiveness,
but Stewart refused to accept blame for the Steelers' continuing
offensive malaise. Word is that Stewart and coordinator Ray Sherman
have been at odds much of the season, and teammates are turned off
by the quarterback's huge ego.
</P>
<P>
   The list
</P>
<P>
   How strong a year is Atlanta Falcons tailback Jamal Anderson
having in '98? His 1,743 yards represent the 14th-best performance
in NFL history. He needs 75 yards today to earn a spot among this
elite top 10:
</P>
<P>
   Yards Player Team Year
</P>
<P>
   2,105 Eric Dickerson Rams 1984
</P>
<P>
   2,053 Barry Sanders Lions 1997
</P>
<P>
   2,003 O.J. Simpson Bills 1973
</P>
<P>
   1,934 Earl Campbell Oilers 1980
</P>
<P>
   1,883 Barry Sanders Lions 1994
</P>
<P>
   1,863 Jim Brown Browns 1963
</P>
<P>
   1,852 Walter Payton Bears 1977
</P>
<P>
   1,830 Terrell Davis Broncos 1998
</P>
<P>
   1,821 Eric Dickerson Rams 1986
</P>
<P>
   1,817 O.J. Simpson Bills 1975
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week
</P>
<P>
   Until Oakland tailback Napoleon Kaufman won the dubious
distinction last year, Barry Sanders led the NFL in rushes for
negative yardage five seasons in a row. Sanders is tied with
Tennessee's Eddie George with a league-high 56 losses this season.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Arizona offensive tackle James Dexter on quarterback Jake
Plummer: ``He's at his best when he's playing schoolyard ball.
It'll be like, `Take the route to the Ford Escort and do a deep
curl at the fire hydrant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
