<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Run missing in Miami
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Their air attack working superbly against the Super
Bowl champions on Monday night, the Miami Dolphins' ambition this
afternoon at the Georgia Dome is to establish a running game
against one of the NFL's best run-stopping teams, the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes for an interesting clash, particularly since
starting back Karim Abdul-Jabbar has suffered from concussions for
the last two games. And so, rookie John Avery likely will be thrust
into a starting role. And even he missed a workout on Wednesday
because of an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Teams have stacked the line of scrimmage against Miami, their
obvious intent being to stop the run and force the Dolphins'
offense to survive solely on the arm of Dan Marino. That tactic
didn't work Monday night, for Marino was stellar in throwing for
four touchdowns in Miami's victory over Denver.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, however, the Dolphins' ground game has been mostly
anemic. In the past five games, Miami backs have failed to get 100
yards. And now the Dolphins have to rely on a rookie with a
questionable ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver tried to put somebody in every running lane we have and
they did it,'' Avery said. ``(New Orleans) had three or four guys
waiting for us on the backside for our cutbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons likely will not change anything in trying to contain
Miami's ground game, which was held to just 33 yards by New England
and 36 by Denver. Atlanta is seventh in the league against the run,
thanks largely to a front seven that has been sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that (Miami coach) Jimmy Johnson likes to run the
ball, no matter who is in there,'' Falcons defensive lineman Lester
Archambeau said. ``So, it's up to us to shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9, 190-pound Avery, who has just 45 carries and 112
yards in the previous five games, is excited about his opportunity,
so much so that he said his ankle hardly would keep him out. ``Not
much going to keep me out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To take out the Miami running game would be to force Marino to
pass more. That, however, is a short-term solution. Teams that go
deep into the playoffs usually have a running attack that is
effective and consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has so little confidence in its running game that on most
third-and-short situations it passes. ``I think we get in that
situation and we have doubt that we can do it,'' Avery said. ``We
have to get an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
