<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ECAC-FESTIVAL-NYT     12-26 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ECAC-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFSTRA HAS EASY TIME HANDLING GEORGIA TECH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A holiday date at Madison Square Garden. A convincing
victory over an opponent from the prestigious Atlantic Coast
Conference. Hofstra acted as if it accomplished the ordinary
Saturday in demolishing Georgia Tech, 61-42, in the ECAC Holiday
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Craig Claxton of Hofstra simply held the ball as
time ran out, and the Flying Dutchmen shook hands with each other
and then shook hands with the Yellow Jackets as both teams filed
into the locker room. No hugs, no jumps for joy. Business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on the road so much, we said we would treat this as
a home game,'' Hofstra Coach Jay Wright said. ``Since it was a home
game, we expected to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright even put up a sign that read ``attitude'' in the Flying
Dutchmen's locker room at the Garden, just like home. Every Hofstra
player slapped it on the way out, and the team showed plenty of
attitude in harassing Tech into 25 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra (6-4), from the glamour-challenged America East
Conference, received a game-high 23 points from smooth-shooting
swingman Norman Richardson. Alvin Jones led Georgia Tech (8-3) with
12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra managed only 6 points in the first 6 minutes 45 seconds
of the second half, and its 12-point halftime lead dwindled to
35-29 after Tech's Jason Collier hit a layup. Roberto Gittens
twisted in a layup and Marc Petit swished a baseline jumper to
stretch Hofstra's cushion to 39-29 with 11:36 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra had refused to give Tech any momentum by taking care of
the ball and sprinkling in a few offensive rebounds to milk the
clock. Richardson hit a 3-pointer at the shot-clock buzzer and
followed with another to give Hofstra a 47-33 lead with 7:30 left.
</P>
<P>
   Then guard Jason Hernandez was fouled hard by T.J. Vines on a
breakaway. Hernandez made one of two free throws on the
intentional-foul call. Hofstra did not score when it retained
possession, and it lost Claxton, who vomited at the baseline under
the basket. Claxton got sick again at the bench, but even without
its floor leader, Hofstra stepped up its upset bid. Richardson
floated in a 3-pointer from the baseline to make the score 51-33
with 5:53 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Claxton returned to the game a few minutes minutes later,
missing a layup, but Duane Posey scored on the follow to give the
Flying Dutchmen a 55-40 lead at the 3:23 mark. Posey hit a soft
jumper and Richardson dunked off a break to widen the gap to 19
points.
</P>
<P>
   Tech Coach Bobby Cremins called a timeout, but all the
gamesmanship in the world was not going to bail the Yellow Jackets
out of this surprising defeat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the beginning of the second half, Tony Aikins hit a 3-pointer
and Jones followed with a dunk to pull Georgia Tech to within
29-22. Claxton responded for Hofstra with a driving layup to
restore the lead to 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra had taken a 12-point lead at halftime by collecting
eight steals and controlling Tech's mammoth front line.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra refused to be intimidated by Georgia Tech's 66-64
victory over No.7-ranked North Carolina last Tuesday. The Flying
Dutchmen took an 11-9 lead on Hernandez's 3-pointer with 14:52 left
in the half. Posey built the margin to 4 with a put-back after
three offensive rebounds by the Dutchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the Yellow Jackets' 6-foot-11-inch center, followed with
a dunk. It was one of the few moments either Jones, or Collier,
Tech's 7-foot power forward, was able to use his height advantage.
Hofstra, without a player taller than 6-8 on the floor, used simple
man-to-man defense and darting hands to limit Jones to 6 points and
Collier to none (on 0-for-4 shooting) in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jones and Collier showed fatigue whenever the pace
quickened. The smaller Dutchmen appeared energized. Richardson
scored 5 straight points to build Hofstra's lead to 18-13.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech has had a wild couple of weeks. On Dec. 13 the
Yellow Jackets rallied to beat Georgia, a game that Cremins said
was one of the most exciting in his 18 seasons at Georgia Tech.
Three days later, they had trouble defeating Wofford.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 19, Tech suffered a 41-point loss to then-No. 3
Kentucky, and then came the stunning victory over North Carolina.
Against the Tar Heels, the secret was that Tech committed a
season-low eight turnovers and fouled just nine times. Tech also
has shown resilience with three overtime victories over New
Orleans, Appalachian State and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yellow Jackets' mercurial season should come as no
surprise. They have two sophomores, two juniors and a freshman in
their starting lineup. Guard Dion Glover, their leading scorer last
year at 18.3 points a game, is out for the season with a torn
ligament in his left knee. Their leading scorer now, Collier (18.8
points a game), has played only four games since becoming eligible
after transferring from Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech defeated Hofstra, 58-47, in the 1996 Holiday
Festival before losing to St. John's in the final, 67-55. The
Yellow Jackets won the 1993 tournament. Cremins, a native New
Yorker, brought his first New York-free roster to the Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
