<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 12/26/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- THEME-RESTAURANT-DECLINE-2,
12-26 -- Planet Hollywood, once a Wall Street favorite, is working
on a plan to reorganize as a leaner company by jettisoning its All
Star Cafe chain. For theme restaurants, the magic is gone - and so
are the profits. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- THEME-RESTAURANT-DECLINE-1,
12-26 -- The Official All Star Cafe in Times Square has quietly
been offered for sale, along with the nine other cafes in the
chain. Theme restaurants, which exploded across the urban skyline
three or four years ago with promises of untold profits from a
slickly packaged blend of eating, shopping and entertainment, are
collapsing. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WOONSOCKET, R.I. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- ALPHA-CHRISTIANS,
12-26 -- A movement that began as a Bible study course in London
has drawn American churches like St. James Episcopal in Woonsocket.
``Alpha'' course objectives are to introduce newcomers to the
Christian faith and to re-establish ties with wayward parishioners
through a 10-week videotaped crash course in the basics of
Christianity. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SENATE, 12-26 --
Arizona's John McCain (shown) and Susan Collins of Maine are two
Republicans whom Democrats may call on to help cut the impeachment
trial short. Democrats say they also need a conservative Republican
with a following among Senate colleagues to negotiate a censure.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- IMPEACH-BYRD, 12-26 --
From left, Democratic Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York,
Carl Levin of Michigan and Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia in
April. Many in the White House are concerned that Byrd will be more
a guardian of the Senate as an institution than of his own
Democratic Party in the upcoming impeachment trial. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOULDER, Colo. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- Y2K-CODE-WARRIORS-3,
12-26 -- Worried about the havoc computer failures might cause,
Kathy Garcia of Boulder has stockpiled rice and other staples. the
Y2K problem, as it is known in computer jargon, is already draining
hundreds of billions of dollars from companies and governments
struggling to tame what some call the millennium bug. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEWARK, N.J. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- Y2K-CODE-WARRIORS-2,
12-26 -- Lyudmila Zavlyanova uses a program to find year 2000
computer problems at a New Jersey utility. Mrs. Zavlyanova, a
27-year-old from New York, is one of tens of thousands of
programmers throughout the world racing to head off the havoc that
could ensue because many of the computers in today's wired society
do not understand that a year can begin with a number other than
19. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- Y2K-CODE-WARRIORS-1, 12-26
-- Hospitals are checking medical equipment to make sure it will
function in the year 2000. At New York Hospital, Louis Wetstein
adjusts the dates on an electrocardiograph for a test. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BEDFORD, Mass. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- MILITARY-SALARIES,
12-26 -- From left, Air Force Maj. Rick Coveno, Capt. Chris Ruefer,
Capt. Joe Allegretti and Capt. David L. Peeler Jr. Defense
Secretary William Cohen announced last week that he was requesting
the biggest raise in basic military pay in a generation, with
particular salary carrots for midlevel officers like Coveno. (Rick
Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PASADENA, Calif. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- CALIF-ROSE-PARADE-2,
12-26 -- When completed, The Cat in the Hat float will assume a
place of honor near the front of the Tournament of Roses Parade.
The event has become a premiere advertising vehicle. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PASADENA, Calif. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- CALIF-ROSE-PARADE-1,
12-26 -- A worker constructs the frame for a float based on Dr.
Seuss' The Cat in the Hat for the Tournament of Roses Parade, set
to take place on New Year's Day. It will be one of 56 floats on
display. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- GEN-ZINNI-PROFILE, 12-26
-- At a recent Pentagon briefing, Gen. Anthony C. Zinni describes
the damage done to Iraq by American and British bombs and missiles.
With the strikes over and American policy toward Iraq lurching into
a new period of uncertainty, Zinni, who as commander of the U.S.
Central Command oversees all American forces from Sudan to
Pakistan, will play a major role. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NAPA, Calif. -- Dec. 26, 1998 -- CALIF-ART-SCHOOL, 12-26
-- Stephen Thomas, a printmaker, is the director of the Oxbow
School, a boarding school in a Victorian-style house in Napa, where
classes will be led by a teacher and an artist. The school's first
class, made up of 48 high school juniors drawn from private and
public high schools around the country, will arrive next September.
(Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
