</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DOLPHINS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons are still reaching for goals
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons fans long ago grew tired of games like today's
season finale against the Miami Dolphins, a meaningless contest
where the home team is playing for nothing, with no chance to
advance in the standings and no reason to fight to the finish in
hopes of securing a playoff bid.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the Georgia Dome sold out today?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (13-2), have become fun to watch while rendering
this game unimportant for all the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta already has won the NFC West and locked up a bye in the
first round of the playoffs and a home date with either Dallas,
Green Bay or San Francisco in the second week of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   So why lay it on the line today against a 10-5 Miami team that
will play all-out in an attempt to win a home playoff game of its
own?
</P>
<P>
   There are goals, like the team's first undefeated record at home
and a record-tying nine-game winning streak. And there's a mind-set
at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our incentive is to maintain what got us here,'' said
defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, who is interim head coach while
Dan Reeves recuperates from quadruple heart bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to fall off before the playoffs,'' Brooks said.
``We have to keep on trucking, and playing hard. Playing another
team that is going to be in the playoffs ... really, it's kind of
an extension of the playoffs for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players, such as left defensive end Lester Archambeau,
could use some time off. He still has two pins sticking out of the
skin near his broken left thumb, which is in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about this game not meaning something. It means a
ton,'' Archambeau said. ``Anytime you can go into the postseason
with some momentum, it's going to carry you. We'll have a week off
after this.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was released from the hospital Thursday. Team officials
say he's not supposed to be at the Dome today. In a season where
surprising developments have become the norm, it wouldn't be a
shock if he makes an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, today figures to be difficult. Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson is very good at getting his squad ready for big games.
He'll bring the NFL's No. 2 defense to town, a young and quick unit
that limited Denver, the AFC's No. 1 offense, to 219 yards in the
Dolphins' 31-21 win Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it may end up looking like a normal game because, like
quarterback Chris Chandler said, ``It's a Sunday in the football
season, and that means you go out to play to win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
