<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE27-COX     12-26 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even '74 Marino great
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Arduous research has shown that there have been only
nine coaches over the last 25 years who defeated a Dan
Marino-quarterbacked team more than once in a season. And, believe
me, I am honored to share the company of an illustrious roll call
that includes Bill Parcells, Marv Levy, Raymond Berry, Marty
Schottenheimer, Joe Walton, Ron Meyer, Pete Carroll and Bruce
Coslet.
</P>
<P>
   For the better portion of 16 NFL seasons those coaches have
watched Marino _ who makes his first and likely final appearance in
the Georgia Dome this afternoon _ from a sideline vantage point.
For those 16 years, and the four before them when he played at
Pitt, I scrutinized him through binoculars, usually with my elbows
resting on a laptop computer. This bond, however, we share: It was
just as difficult designing a game plan to counter Marino more than
two decades ago, when he was starring for St. Regis Elementary
School in Pittsburgh, as it was for Falcons coordinator Rich Brooks
and his staff over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow we pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1974 and two buddies and I coached the junior high
team at St. Joseph Elementary School. The endeavor helped me score
points with the team nurse, now my wife of 24 years, and kept a
neighborhood school we all had attended from disbanding its
floundering football program and spending the bingo money on
textbooks. Two years out of college, it was a good excuse not to
look for a real job.
</P>
<P>
   Our expertise was about as short as the AstroTurf-carpeted
80-yard surface of Dean's Field, where we played our home games,
but at least we were long on good intentions. And every season we
managed to develop a couple of solid prospects for Central Catholic
High School, the beloved alma mater that Marino and I share.
</P>
<P>
   The scores from those '74 titanic struggles between rival junior
highs representing the adjacent East Side neighborhoods of
Bloomfield (mine) and Oakland (Marino's) are irrelevant. And
because the Pittsburgh Catholic League collapsed years ago, ending
the superb feeder system that fueled Pittsburgh's private high
schools, the records have been forever lost.
</P>
<P>
   This much, though, the ravages of 24 years of brain-cell
deterioration and 20 seasons of trying to make deadline have not
purged from my memory banks: In '74, we somehow defeated Dan
Marino's team twice, that despite the fact he was an incredible
player.
</P>
<P>
   How good was Marino at age 13? Good enough that, as an
eighth-grader, he certainly could have beaten out any quarterback
Central Catholic coach Joe Scully had playing on the varsity squad
at the time. Good enough that, everywhere St. Regis played that
year, large crowds showed up to watch Marino and the home team
always banked a few bucks more when it passed the hat at halftime.
Good enough to be a hometown legend before he ever picked up a
razor for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Good enough that, on the two occasions we played St. Regis, the
coaching staff sent a letter home to the parents of our players,
apprising them that practices would run at least an hour longer
that week. Because of Marino, and an incredibly convoluted offense
designed for him by St. Regis coaches Shorty Mafeo and Chick
Sciulli, the floodlights at Dean's Field burned late into the night
as we tried to devise a defense that might hold him under 30
points.
</P>
<P>
   Once we even dispatched a spy to Frazier Field, where St. Regis
played its home games, hoping to infiltrate a practice session. The
gambit failed, likely because our would-be saboteur suffered from
asthma and the field, since renamed Dan Marino Field, overlooked
the blast furnaces of the Jones &AMP; Laughlin steel mill.
</P>
<P>
   So we plotted against a St. Regis passing game that featured
flea-flickers and double reverses, all of which ended with the ball
in Marino's hands. We schemed against a run game whose staple was
the old Statue of Liberty play. And somehow _ maybe Marino had a
debilitating attack of acne those two weeks _ we defeated St. Regis
twice.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, when I visited my two sideline compadres in
Pittsburgh, we tried to convince ourselves the outcomes of those
games were the result of seamless coaching. But we all knew better.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the '74 season ended, our staff was chosen,
largely by default, to head the East squad in the annual Catholic
League all-star game. Our quarterback, of course, was Marino and
our instructions to him were something along the lines of: ``Here's
the ball, Danny, throw it as much as you want.''
</P>
<P>
   That minimalist approach backfired and we lost the game. Given
that Don Shula had the benefit of Marino's brilliance for 13 years,
though, and never won a Super Bowl game, I don't feel so bad. Give
me Marino now, and the experience of watching 20 years of some
dubious NFL coaching decisions, and I'd probably win that all-star
game.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the all-star game, Marino went on to Central
Catholic and I moved on to writing about the game he has played so
well. For four years _ one of which included a season when my
younger brother, Joe, served as his right tackle _ I watched Marino
hone his skills. And when he was at Pitt, I documented some of his
deeds. Now that it appears he'll play a few more seasons, there
will be even more opportunities to watch him turn back the clock,
as he did last Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Dan Marino hasn't forgotten the people he met on
the way up. He is _ and this is the highest honor I bestow on
anyone _ the consummate Pittsburgh Guy.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man whose private graciousness outshines even his public
performances. When his son, Michael, was discovered to be autistic,
he helped raise funds for a program at the Miami Children's
Hospital to offer comprehensive care for similarly challenged kids.
Earlier this year, he and wife Claire added to their own brood of
four by adopting daughter Niki Lin, a 2-year-old Chinese orphan.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins played in Pittsburgh a few years ago, Danny
ducked out of the locker room for a few minutes to visit with my
brother, whom he hadn't seen in years. Since I'm begging off
today's contest at the Dome to spend some time with my family and
gear up for weeks on the road at the playoffs, I won't get a chance
to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   But if I did, the message would be this simple one: Thanks,
Danny, for the memories.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
