<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAZERHOMES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beazer shapes a financial plan
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beazer Homes has no intention of getting caught in a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case one happens next year, the Atlanta-based builder is
fine tuning a strategy that includes gaining market share through
acquisition, taking short-term options on land rather than risking
ownership, exploring niche markets, avoiding duplications of
competitors' products and rewarding employees for saving money
internally.
</P>
<P>
   That sits well with analysts such as David Dwyer of Salomon
Smith Barney. He believes that consolidations will overcome the
effects of a 1999 slowdown, assuming market fundamentals like
interest rates and inventories stay low and buyer commitments stay
high.
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes' share price has jumped nearly 50 percent during
the past six weeks. When stockholders receive their 1998 annual
reports in the next week or so, they'll understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Shares closed down Thursday at $25.37 1/2, down 31 1/4 cents,
near the 52-week high of $27.12 1/2 reached April 7. The climb has
been steady since Nov. 4, when the nation's eighth-largest builder
reported dramatically improved fourth-quarter earnings and year-end
results. It also announced a significant acquisition in northern
Virginia, Trafalgar House Property, which is expected to take
revenue past $1 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Through a joint venture with a Mexican builder, and based on
projections of large increases in the Hispanic population, the
company is targeting the Hispanic market in Texas and potentially
Arizona, Florida and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the 1997 fourth quarter, 1998 net income was up 59
percent, to $12 million from $7.5 million. Income per share came in
at $1.37 in the period ended Sept. 30, against 87 cents in the
prior-year quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Dec. 2, Beazer Homes revealed its entry into an
experimental niche for a home builder _ the never-land of apartment
renters _ by announcing an Atlanta venture with Chicago-based
Equity Residential Properties Trust, a large real estate investment
trust with several apartment complexes in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, an exclusive arrangement called ``rent with
equity,'' is intended to allay the renter's chronic anxiety that
rent is money down the drain. An Equity Residential Properties
tenant paying, say $1,000 a month for an apartment, would have 25
percent of that payment credited toward the purchase of a
Beazer-built house, to a maximum of 3 percent of the total value of
the home.
</P>
<P>
   1999 earnings estimate
</P>
<P>
   By the time January ends, results for the first fiscal 1999
quarter, which ends Dec. 31, will be ready for release. Wall Street
looks for Beazer Homes to report 44 cents a share, against 14 cents
per share in the first 1998 quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Ivy Zelman expects 45 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Zelman, who has a ``hold'' rating on the stock, has raised her
fiscal 1999 earnings estimate twice since Beazer Homes' year-end
report: from $3.25 to $3.70 and, in early December, to $3.75. First
Call's consensus estimate for 1999 is $3.62. The company earned
$2.66 in 1998, so meeting either estimate would represent at least
a 36 percent year-over-year increase.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it would cap a brisk ride for a company that went
public in England in 1971, branched into the United States in 1985,
separated from the parent and became publicly held here in 1994. It
would also underscore what Ian McCarthy, chief executive officer
and president, says: ``We have posted a 30 percent annual growth
rate in closings during the past three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes now builds entry-level and move-up houses in 12
Southern and Western states and, by virtue of the Trafalgar House
acquisition, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview, McCarthy indicated that the Trafalgar
House deal could also be enhanced by Beazer Homes' year-old
in-house mortgage operation that he said added $2 million to fourth
quarter 1998 profits .
</P>
<P>
   He further said its design center _ which allows buyers to
select upgrades for their houses _ added another $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure against overhead eating into profits, expenses are
controlled partly through a thin corporate staff. Only 35 people
work in the company's north Atlanta headquarters. The rest of the
1,200 or so employees work in sales, management and construction at
construction sites in the metro area and around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are in great financial shape. We continue to be
among the most conservatively financed builders,'' said David
Weiss, chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   For the Trafalgar House acquisition, the company increased its
debt-to-capital ratio to 55 percent from 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After analyst Steve Percoco of Lark Research expressed minor
concerns about that, the company said its $200 million line of
credit is set for four years, which would enable it to withstand a
liquidity crunch that might make it hard for privately held
builders to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Beazer Homes controls enough land to last for three
years. Half is owned, half is under option because, McCarthy said,
``we want to work our assets and turn them fast to limit
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Increase in backlogs
</P>
<P>
   Backlogs, or homes under contract but not actually closed and
occupied, soared 73 percent to 2,057, year over year, at the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Builders tend to regard such increases in backlog as birds in
the hand because buyers have made a commitment to buy the new home.
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts, including Percoco, point out that those
buyers do not necessarily have their mortgages approved and, he
says, ``if there is a dislocation in the market or the economy, you
could have increased cancellations. Your view of backlog should
depend on where that buyer is in the (home-buying) process.''
</P>
<P>
   Industrywide, home building has enjoyed strong order growth, but
closings have been slower to grow. This, in Percoco's mind, has
contributed to the increases in backlog.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Weiss and McCarthy maintain that Beazer Homes is
conservatively managed. Since the initial public offering, there
has been only one setback, one McCarthy says the business press
overinflated. It was reported during fiscal year 1997 involving a
$6.3 million inventory write-off of Nevada properties and a
decrease in closings and average sales prices in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The company has regained whatever ground was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, home-building stocks have outperformed the Russell
2,000, an index of smaller-capitalized companies. But they have
underperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which represents the
broader market. In October, there was a general decline, then a
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the top 10 home-building stocks have not followed. With
its notable share-price increase, Beazer Homes is _ at least for
now _ one exception to the rule. Pulte Corp. and Kaufman &AMP; Broad
Homes are the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of its goals to increase sales and profits may be
tough to accomplish during this stage of the cycle, says analyst
Percoco, ``from a strategic perspective, this company is very well
positioned.''
</P>
<P>
   BEAZER HOMES
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Based: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   History: Hanson PLC, a conglomerate in the United Kingdom, owned
Hanson Properties North America Inc., which owned Beazer Homes'
operations. They formed, in November 1993, Beazer Homes USA Inc.
and went public in March 1994. The company raised $99 million.
</P>
<P>
   Leadership:
</P>
<P>
   Chairman, non-executive: Brian C. Beazer
</P>
<P>
   President, CEO: Ian J. McCarthy
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president, CFO: David S. Weiss
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president, COO: Michael H. Furlow.
</P>
<P>
   Rank: No. 8 in Builder Magazine's top 10 U.S. home builders in
terms of homes closed annually, about 6,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 24 markets in 12 states
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions: Houston, Dallas, Orlando, Washington D.C./northern
Virginia. Most recent, Trafalgar House Property of Washington,
which added 4,000 lots in northern Virginia, Maryland and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
