<SLUG> BC-LAPD-LAWSUITS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITIGATION AGAINST LOS ANGELES POLICE COSTLY FOR TAXPAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The city has identified 300 pending lawsuits
against the Los Angeles Police Department as the tip of a
litigation iceberg that is costing taxpayers tens of millions of
dollars a year, according to computer-generated records obtained by
the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The first-ever compilation of LAPD litigation by City Attorney
James Hahn's office for the Police Department and its oversight
commission is the initial step in a far-reaching plan to identify
every department's exposure in an effort to reduce payouts that
since 1992 have cost the city more than $322 million.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the city had little idea what its exposure might be
at any given time, even as police payouts rose to $26 million in
fiscal year 1994 before settling back to about $12 million in
fiscal 1998 _ still about six times the annual payments in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The new window into the LAPD shows just how extensive a problem
litigation has become since the 1991 Rodney King beating by police
officers and its subsequent $3.8 million payout.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an aggressive risk management program, the LAPD
continues to account for about one-third of all city settlement and
judgment payouts, which have totaled $109 million since fiscal
1993, according to city attorney records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not satisfied,'' said police Cmdr. David Kalish. ``We
have to identify the areas that create the greatest risk and to
reduce our future liability. We live in a litigious society, and
the department must be proactive in addressing risk management.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a six-year average, the Police Department has paid out
about $17.4 million annually, followed by street maintenance at
$8.4 million, engineering at $5.7 million, transportation at $4.1
million, sanitation at $3.2 million, the city clerk at $3.1
million, and recreation and parks at $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the payouts will amount to about $42 million
citywide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still too high,'' Hahn said. ``We have to get all the
departments involved from the claim stage. Right now there is too
much of a focus on single cases. The City Council looks at the big
cases and the big dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The city still does not have a state-of-the-art system to track
litigation in most departments. General managers also have not
acted aggressively enough on available information to improve
practices to avoid lawsuits, Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   The City Attorney's and Mayor's offices are proposing a claims
board, which has the support of both the elected and appointed
Charter Reform Commissions, to involve more of the city in making
decisions on litigation and payouts. The mayor in particular would
have more influence.
</P>
<P>
   A new risk management executive committee made up of department
representatives also has met for a year under the chief
administrative officer's oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Barring rapid improvements in all departments, though, Hahn said
he is prepared to recommend far harsher remedies, including
charging departments directly for settlement and judgment payments.
</P>
<P>
   Police litigation has taken center stage as a new city
attorney's police division with 29 lawyers is scheduled to start
work on the pending 300 cases and all new police litigation Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cutting settlement and judgment payouts, the
department hopes to reduce its use of outside law firms, which have
been paid more than $5 million on police litigation alone since
fiscal 1995, according to city records.
</P>
<P>
   The division will work with LAPD risk managers, who will
concentrate on identifying and minimizing risk through officer
training, identifying trends of behavior, tracking risky personnel,
holding supervisors accountable for failing to curb high-risk
actions and the application of appropriate discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The tabulation of 300 cases provides much better detail than the
LAPD previously had on litigation trends.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits include 25 police shootings, which carry some of
the highest exposure ratings. Exposure does not indicate liability
or wrongdoing, but rather what a jury might award, usually based on
experience with similar cases.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 182 lawsuits allege civil rights violations, including
use of force and unlawful searches. Assault and battery or false
imprisonment account for 54 cases, while 83 other plaintiffs have
sued for damages as the result of traffic crashes. The remaining
cases are unclassified.
</P>
<P>
   There are 20 cases rated as having a high exposure, which means
an exposure to a jury award of more than $500,000 per case, or
above $10 million total, according to the city attorney's rating
scale. That number includes one case that is headed to trial after
the City Council recently refused to settle it for $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some 53 cases are rated at medium exposure, while the remainder
carry a low rating or are unrated, according to the records.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff attorneys contend that high numbers of lawsuits and
large payouts remain a measure of the LAPD's failure to
sufficiently reform itself in accordance with Christopher
Commission recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   (second take to follow)
</P>
</TEXT>
