<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7182 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAPD-LAWSUITS-2nd-tak     12-26 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-LAWSUITS-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: Commission recommendations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney Beatrice Royster, whose client Damien Deshay Burris was
released after 5 1/2 months in jail on a murder charge, questions
the significance of the LAPD's attempt to get a handle on
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see much of a change in the department,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Royster said charges against Burris were dropped after new
detectives were assigned to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The City Attorney's Office, without admitting any wrongdoing,
has said the case carries a high exposure. The first civil trial
resulted in a hung jury, with a second scheduled early next year,
Royster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They locked this guy up for months, then other detectives
investigate and he's out,'' she said. ``Their approach is to ruin
his reputation rather than look at their investigative
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's attorney in the case, Marsha Berkowitz, said she
could not comment on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Stephen Yagman's Venice law firm is suing LAPD
officers, as well as the council and other city officials in
connection with shootings involving the LAPD's Special
Investigation Section. He said the department has not reformed
because it refuses to recognize that anything is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no improvement,'' said Yagman, who contends the
SIS has acted like ``death squads'' in waiting for criminals to
commit crimes before swooping in on them, sometimes resulting in
shootouts and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the SIS cases are rated with high and medium
exposure, but Deputy City Attorney Cory Brente said the tactics
used are defensible and the shootings unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shootings are up to the criminal,'' Brente said. ``Who (on
the Police Department) wants to shoot anyone, to be called death
squads, killers, murderers? Who wants that?''
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the department determines an officer acted beyond
the scope of his duties, it can recommend against legal
representation, and the officer is left to pay for his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. David Louis Navarro, a former Foothill Division officer,
was denied city representation after pleading no contest July 2,
1997, to four counts of assault under color of authority in
connection with the sexual assaults of several minor girls,
attorneys involved in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The city recently paid more than $1.2 million to settle the case
and is in the process of filing a cross-complaint against Navarro,
said Assistant City Attorney Philip Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Encino attorney Karyn Shatzkin said the case was outrageous on
its face, but that the city failed to monitor Navarro's fitness for
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar said research indicated there are no reliable tests to
predict sexual assaults. Navarro, who was fired, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said isolated cases, and even litigation in general,
should not be the sole barometer of LAPD reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are anomalies,'' he said. ``There are much more
scientific ways to evaluate the improvement in the organization,
including citizen surveys.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Attorney's Office continues to grapple with its
litigation strategy, particularly what cases to take to court and
which ones to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't uncomfortable with giving out $1 million,'' said
Thomas Hokinson, chief assistant city attorney. ``Twenty years ago,
$100,000 was a large amount for a case.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend has been for the City Attorney's Office to try fewer
cases, in part because there is a smaller backlog of cases under
the present fast-track system of handling cases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the office tried 78 cases, losing 20 of them at a cost
of $5.8 million. Last year, the number of trials dipped to 17, with
two losses amounting to $2.9 million in payouts.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in 1990 the office settled 87 cases for $5.9
million, compared with 100 settled for $7.5 million in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
