<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Dec. 27. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANTIAGE _ What would it mean to the world, to our lives, to
politics, economics, culture, if growing old as we know it becomes
a thing of the past? What would happen if an elixir were discovered
that, when injected into the heart, the brain, the liver, the
kidneys, would rebuild old tissue with new cells? Scientists say
that era is at hand. Over the next 20 years, new elixirs are likely
to revolutionize medicine and aging. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TESTS _ As a kid I hated report cards. Now, several decades later,
I still felt nervous as Dr. Charlene DeHaven held my test results
and got a funny look on her face. I knew I was in for it. While my
birth certificate and driver's license say I'm 46, my anti-aging
report card said I should really be putting 52 candles on my cake.
Thank you, Doc. Thank you very much. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VEGAS-AGE (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ America's bio-medical community is
closing in at a feverish pace on the secrets of aging and disease.
If its methodical and well-funded approach looks like a NASA moon
shot, be advised that there are also others _ a Wild West fringe
group of anti-aging treatment promoters _ whose Las Vegas gathering
earlier this month at moments looked more like a Star Trek
convention than serious science. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
