<HEADLINE>
A LONG SHOT TO CAPTURE BEST MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ufdrop &LR; I &UR; xr &LR; t was a request from a golf publication to vote for
the best of 1998, and much of it took some thought. But not the
lead question, which asked for the sport's top moment. No room for
debate here, as the vote went to a young woman who made an
improbable putt that did more than force a playoff _ it provided
proof that the foundation of this game remains unspoiled.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Chuasiriporn, on the 72d hole of the US Women's Open,
reminded us all that golf, though an impossible game, never fails
to somehow reward us. She was shocked when her putt went in, and
whether it covered 40 feet or 50 or somewhere in between is
incidental; the lasting image is what matters, because it embodied
so much of what is missing in sports today: sincerity and
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn seemed embarrassed to make the putt, not because
she was a 20-year-old amateur playing against professionals and not
because the birdie bomb had tied her for the lead; no, she was
embarrassed because she knows what every golfer knows, that you
don't try to make putts like that, you just want to get them close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick a spot,'' she told her brother/caddie Joey, who gave her
the line. He told her to give it a good run, a stern reminder that
she had left a par putt short on the 71st hole. Chuasiriporn
watched the putt roll and roll and roll and ... drop. She put her
left hand to her mouth and looked aghast, almost apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no need to apologize, for she had painted the
sport with a fresh coat of humility. And she did it all while
having no chance to earn any money, outplaying the likes of Annika
Sorenstam, Laura Davies, and Dottie Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18-hole playoff the next day, Chuasiriporn started well,
struggled in the middle, then seemed poised to win on the 18th
hole. But what golf gives, it also takes, and on the 18th hole the
psychology major at Duke missed a putt to win. Two holes later, in
sudden death, Chuasiriporn lost to Korean sensation Se Ri Pak. Six
months later, however, Chuasiriporn is still golf's biggest winner
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The views out across Pleasure Bay will still be spectacular and
the greens velvet-smooth, but for those privileged to play Eastward
Ho! next spring, there will be something missing: the gracious
presence of  &UR; John Scheffler &LR; . The 62-year-old former baseball star
is retiring after 19 years as head professional at the venerable
Chatham course, drawing the curtain on 38 years in the golf
business. Scheffler is one of the great gentlemen in the New
England PGA, a man who had the distinction of breaking into the
business working for  &UR; Jack Grout  &LR; in the early 1960s at LaGorce CC
in Miami Beach. Grout was a giant, universally acknowledged as the
teaching force behind  &UR; Jack Nicklaus &LR; . Scheffler continued his good
fortune with several years under the tutelage of  &UR; Bill Ezinicki &LR; 
before taking his first head job at Wianno. He stayed there for
seven years before heading to Chatham, where the ride has been more
joyful than he could have imagined. Scheffler was recently honored
as Professional of the Year by the Cape Cod Chapter of the NEPGA
... Also honored at the Cape Cod festivities was  &UR; Mike
Ghelfi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the assistant at Ballymeade who earned Player of the Year
status by winning the coveted Wessner Award.  &UR; Mike Pry  &LR; of New
Seabury was cited as Junior Golf Promoter of the Year, while  &UR; Jane
Frost  &LR; of Holly Ridge and  &UR; Sue Kaffenburgh  &LR; of Hyannis GC shared
Teacher of the Year honors ... The Massachusetts Golf Association
will hold its 1999 spring conference March 9, when the theme will
be ``A Salute to the Ryder Cup,'' in recognition of that little
gathering just nine months away. The MGA is hoping to stage a
re-creation of ``Golf Talk Live'' with The Golf Channel's  &UR; Peter
Kessler &LR;  and former Ryder Cup players helping out ... He is a
superb golfer from Australia, and 1998 will go into the books as
his first season without a victory since 1989.  &UR; Greg Norman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; you
say? Wrong.  &UR; Peter Senior &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the man whose swing is nothing to
imitate but whose success is to be admired. He made a strong run in
the Australian Open earlier this month but finished second. For the
record, Norman, before his shoulder woes, won the Holden Classic
Down Under last February; he last was winless in 1991 ... One
Aussie who will never forget 1998 is  &UR; Stuart Appleby &LR; . By now the
27-year-old's story of tragedy is well-known to golf fans: His wife
 &UR; Renay  &LR; was killed in London, crushed by a car as she unloaded
luggage from a cab at the airport. Appleby was a witness to the
July accident, and it has been a tough road for him. He returned to
competition at the PGA Championship in August and was cheered by an
enthusiastic gallery, and after a few other emotional events,
Appleby recorded a bittersweet win at last week's Coolum Classic.
It was an event he would not have played, he said, save for the
fact that his wife used to love the stop ... Appleby will be in the
select field when the Mercedes Championship tees off Jan. 7 at
Kapalua on the island of Maui. That's right, the kickoff to the
1999 PGA Tour is just 11 days away. If you are looking to pick a
winner in that event, you might consider  &UR; Davis Love  &LR; or  &UR; Fred
Couples &LR; . Love won the Kapalua International in 1992, Couples took
the title the next two years, and Love returned to the top spot in
1997, the year it ended its 15-year-run as one of the premier
non-Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   During the Presidents Cup two weeks ago, it was reported that
Norman's doctor had expressed fears of the golfer getting into too
hectic of a schedule so soon after returning from a long layoff.
Dr.  &UR; Richard Hawkins  &LR; reportedly suggested that Norman take six
weeks off after the Cup to let the shoulder heal. Norman must be
listening, because he is not due back until the Holden lassic in
early February, followed by a date in the Australian Masters. The
latter is a surprise, because Norman has not played the event since
1994 when he split with IMG, which organizes the tourney. Of
course, for a reported $300,000 appearance fee, Norman can let
bygones be bygones ...  &UR; Ernie Els  &LR; joined select company when he
was granted lifetime membership on the European PGA Tour.  &UR; Arnold
Palmer &LR; , &UR; Gary Player &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Bob Charles  &LR; are also lifetime members
... The pet peeve for 1998 was the same as the pet peeve for 1997
and the pet peeve for 1996 (and, sadly, probably the pet peeve for
2000). Namely, all those low handicappers who neglect to hand in
their cards following competitive rounds ... If you are able to
play to that low handicap, however, it figures to be an attractive
summer in '99 for you. The MGA State Amateur will be held at
Kittansett, the US Amateur at Pebble Beach. Expect record entries.
</P>
</TEXT>
