<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS A CREDIT TO PARCELLS'S SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Former Patriots on the New York Jets said last week
that they felt the Patriots' resilience the past two seasons was
born of their experience with Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The nonsense on this subject persists almost two full seasons
since Parcells left New England.
</P>
<P>
   Even Parcells said, ``I had nothing to do with what's happened
there the past couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edwards didn't learn how to recover from a midseason dip
under Parcells. Chris Floyd didn't learn to block well from
Parcells. Tony Simmons was milking cows in Wisconsin when Parcells
was here. Chad Eaton became a major player under Pete Carroll, not
Parcells. Chris Slade became a Pro Bowler under Carroll the year
after Parcells benched him on first and second downs. Ty Law
finally got his wish to cover the top receiver under Carroll, not
Parcells, and now he's a Pro Bowler who leads the league in
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Thomas, the heart and soul of the defense, never played
for Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Armstrong had a chance to join Parcells in New York but
stayed in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Todd Rucci.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells makes players play? Shawn Jefferson said he was fine
the week after sustaining a concussion on Opening Day in Miami in
1996, but Parcells wouldn't let him play. It's the only game
Jefferson has missed in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Brown, when healthy, has flourished under Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells led Todd Collins to quit football by treating him like
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Milloy has come on like gangbusters the last two years
under Carroll and is now a Pro Bowler.
</P>
<P>
   Zefross Moss, who has had the most consistent year of any
Patriot offensive lineman, never played for Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   It is Carroll's team that has made the playoffs two years in a
row. Parcells did not do that in his four years with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   If these Patriots are resilient, they have become so the past
two years under Carroll, not Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday that resilience will be tested again. Having gone 4-1
after hitting a low point at 5-5, the Patriots at 9-6 have
qualified for the playoffs, and need Sunday's game for a shot at
home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like to win it for two other reasons as well. (1) They're
sick of the Parcells topic _ and that goes from owner Robert Kraft
right down to the coaching staff and the players. (2) Momentum for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum is what it's all about,'' said Willie McGinest, who
will see some action at his defensive end spot Sunday. ``If you
have it heading in, it means everything for you. You build a head
of steam, a confidence, and you feel like nobody can beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   The healthy Jets likely will throw everything including the
kitchen sink at Scott Zolak, who is expecting it. The Patriots kept
their practices under wraps this past week, but the playbook again
will include the long ball as they believe they can beat the Jets
and Otis Smith downfield because New York stops the underneath
passes so well.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will be missing not only Drew Bledsoe, Terry Glenn,
and Ted Johnson, but also linebacker Collins, who has a tear in a
chest muscle. That leaves the Patriots with Marty Moore in the
middle and probably Vernon Crawford, a second-year linebacker out
of Florida State, to play a lot in the regular defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will have to contend with their former specialty
player Dave Meggett, who will get more playing time this week on
third down and on punt and kickoff returns. The Patriots know
firsthand how Meggett can destroy opponents with big plays.
</P>
<P>
   This could be one of the more physical games the Patriots play
all season. The first meeting, a 24-14 win by the Jets at
Foxborough Oct. 19, was costly since it began the incredible run of
injuries the Patriots have endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose this game,'' said Eaton. ``This is a game that
can play on our nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gave us a chance last week against San Francisco,''
added Willie Clay. ``Nobody seems to be giving us a chance this
week. But this team has a lot of pride in the way it's fought back
from all the adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   And that has nothing to do with Parcells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
