<HEADLINE>
POTI LOOKING SLICK AS AN OILER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Poti's adjustment to the pro game has been virtually
seamless. The former Boston University defenseman, who had two
years of eligibility left with the Terriers, is playing about 20
minutes a game with the Oilers, paired with another
offensive-minded blue liner, Roman Hamrlik.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough at first, I'd say it took me 8-10 games to feel
comfortable,'' said the 21-year-old Poti, who figures to be a
shoo-in for the NHL's All-Rookie team if he keeps up his
impressive, steady play. ``(Hamrlik) is a very gifted offensive
defenseman, so it was pretty weird they put us together, but they
did, right from the start of training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3-inch Poti is playing at 205 pounds, about 10 more
than he carried in his college days. Head coach Ron Low also rolls
him out for the second unit on the power play, pairing him with
Janne Niinimaa. Not even halfway through his rookie season, Poti
looks and plays most nights like a seasoned veteran.
</P>
<P>
   General managers from around the league call the Oiler front
office, mention Poti's name, and assistant GM Doug Risebrough
apprises them, ``He's for real.'' Message: Don't even think about
asking for a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised,'' said Poti. ``But I've worked at this
all my life, waiting for this opportunity to come. It's a different
game, though, pretty much in every way, mostly because of the pace.
You've got to be thinking about what you'll do with the puck even
before you get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Poti keeps up on his Terriers, who have
struggled this year. His sister, Colleen, tapes some of the BU
games and sends them to Edmonton. He wishes his old team was doing
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never looked back on my decision,'' he said. ``I met
with (BU coach) Jack Parker five or six times before I made up my
mind, and he was great about it. He just said, `You've got to do
what's right for you.' He wanted to make sure I was doing it for
the right reason _ not doing it for the money, but doing it because
it was the right time and it made me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Glen Murray &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Boston's first choice in the '91 draft, finally
is blossoming into a scorer at age 26 _ once again a reminder that
these things sometimes take time. Murray banged home his 14th goal
of the year Tuesday night vs. the Penguins and should break his
career-high mark of 29 last season. The Kings picked up Murray from
Pittsburgh at the March '97 trade deadline, giving up  &UR; Ed Olczyk &LR; .
Kings coach  &UR; Larry Robinson  &LR; on Murray: ``When he came to us, we
really didn't know what we had. What we've gotten from him is a
kind of diamond in the rough who has really blossomed.'' ... The
Sabres have seen their average attendance jump by nearly 3,500 this
season, a carryover from last year's promising finish and playoff
success. They're also reaching over the border, offering Canadian
fans a decent exchange rate on their deflated dollar (75 cents
instead of 64 cents) when buying tickets ... At the rate he's
firing, Hingham's  &UR; Tony Amonte  &LR; could walk away this year with the
first Maurice Richard Award as the league's No. 1 goal scorer. Not
bad for a guy whose career seemed to come to a close with the
Rangers when then coach  &UR; Mike Keenan  &LR; questioned his courage. ``I
know one thing,'' said another ex-Ranger,  &UR; Doug Weight &LR; . &UR;  &LR; ``Tony's
not chicken. He gets his goals from the same place ( &UR; John &LR; ) &UR; LeClair
 &LR; and ( &UR; Keith &LR; ) &UR; Tkachuk  &LR; get 'em _ and they call those guys power
forwards.'' Amonte on Keenan: ``He definitely didn't like me, and I
didn't like him. I still don't think I like him.'' ... How badly do
the Avalanche miss  &UR; Uwe Krupp  &LR; and  &UR; Sandis Ozolinsh  &LR; at the points?
They were recently mired in a 4-for-62 slump on the power play.
Krupp left as a free agent for the Wings and Ozolinsh still can't
come to contract terms. The sides are close on the money (two
years/$6.75 million), but the sticking point is that Ozolinsh wants
it backloaded _ much more money in year No. 2 _ in order to
diminish the sting of not being paid for this season's ``lost''
games. Meanwhile,  &UR; Claude Lemieux  &LR; is teeing it up at the point.
Ouch ... The Capitals will go the rest of the way without tough guy
 &UR; Chris Simon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but don't worry,  &UR; Craig Berube  &LR; can still pound the
heavy bag with the best of 'em. Simon came back too soon from
shoulder surgery last season, reinjuring himself in the Cup finals
vs. Detroit, and a second operation will keep him down until next
September. The good news for the Capitals:  &UR; Adam Oates  &LR; returned
last night after missing some three weeks with a groin pull ...
 &UR; Donald Audette &LR; : &UR;  &LR; Two games with the Kings, two goals. And, folks,
there were actually teams out there that said giving up a
second-round pick for him was too much. Sure, there are some real
finds in the second round, but not enough to pass up a 29-year-old
winger who can score _ not might score ... Weight, who skated
Tuesday for the first time since Nov. 2 knee surgery, has collected
no fewer than 40,000 votes for the All-Star Game. ``I must have had
a hell of a three games,'' mused Weight, whose season started late
because of a contract holdout. Truth is, Weight was hurt in his
fifth game, but it's good to know the fans aren't counting.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, Bruins fans, Christmas doesn't get much better than a
0-5-5 Montreal winless streak. But, hey, they just had to get rid
of  &UR; Patrick Roy  &LR; ... While on the subject of St. Patrick, keep in
mind that he is an unrestricted free agent as of July 1, 1999. Do I
hear the bidding begin at $6.5 million per year? And what do you
suppose  &UR; Guy Hebert &LR; , &UR;  &LR; another UFA goalie, is going to bring on the
open market? Hebert, who recently came within five minutes of a
third straight shutout in the Anaheim net, will turn 32 Jan. 7 and
is in only his sixth season as an NHL starter (read: lots of miles
left) ... Word around Tampa is that the Lightning, projected to
lose $20 million this year, would love to unload both  &UR; Craig Janney
 &LR; and  &UR; Stephane Richer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who have failed to spark the offense.
Janney, with only the balance due on his $1.7 million this season,
could be a cheap, interesting fit as a second-line center for the
Bruins. OK, he's soft, but don't discount the effectiveness of his
velvety hands; he entered this season with better than a
point-per-game average (724 points/704 games) over his 10-year
career. For about $850,000, with no obligation beyond that, he
could be that dash of creativity the Bruins need in the pivot ...
Hall of Famer  &UR; Glenn Hall  &LR; sounded miffed recently, following
comments from Calgary coach  &UR; Brian Sutter &LR;  about the way Hall's
stomach often turned over come game time. ``Everybody says that's
what I'm known for,'' said Hall. ``Nobody knows that I also stopped
the odd puck.'' Sutter wouldn't let his own netminder,
 &UR; Jean-Sebastien Giguere &LR; , &UR;  &LR; leave the Calgary net in a recent game,
even though the rookie was heaving because of dehydration. Hall,
said Sutter, was sick before games and between periods, but never
gave in to his gut. ``That's a fantasy,'' said Hall. ``I did get
sick before games, but I don't think I ever got sick during a
game.'' ... The fur was flying in Anaheim when Islanders GM/coach
 &UR; Mike Milbury  &LR; berated  &UR; Travis Green  &LR; as a ``gutless puke'' for the
stinging hit Green put on New York defenseman  &UR; Kenny Jonsson &LR; .
``It's why he doesn't wear an Islander uniform anymore,'' added
Milbury, who dealt Green to the Ducks last February. The immediate
diagnosis was that Jonsson suffered a concussion _ and there was
talk it could be career-threatening, because Jonsson has suffered
five concussions in his career. But Jonsson, later told by doctors
his head was fine, was back and playing two nights later in Phoenix
... As expected, San Jose defenseman  &UR; Gary Suter  &LR; will be out for
the year, following a third surgical attempt to repair his torn
right triceps. In the latest operation, an Achilles' tendon from a
cadaver was inserted into Suter's arm _ reminiscent of when doctors
patched up ex-Bruin  &UR; Randy Burridge's  &LR; knee with parts taken from a
deceased donor ...  &UR; Ziggy Palffy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; fresh from signing his
five-year, $25 million contract, connected for a pair of assists in
his first game back with the Islanders Tuesday night. Meanwhile,
rumors persist that the Islanders will deal Woonsocket's  &UR; Bryan
Berard  &LR; _ a Group 2 free agent as of July 1 _ before the March 23
trade deadline. Another possibility to go is former BU blue liner
 &UR; Scott Lachance &LR; . Berard, NHL rookie of the year in '96-97, could
be a victim of mixed signals, getting conflicting reads from the
lengthy list of Islander coaches. Berard has the skills to be a
great talent, but not if he's asked to be two or three different
kinds of player ... Among the many benefits of New Jersey's revived
offense under new coach  &UR; Robbie Ftorek &LR; : &UR; Jason Arnott  &LR; had nine
goals as of last week. Suddenly, the swap that brought the Oilers
 &UR; Bill Guerin  &LR; doesn't look so lopsided. Unlike their days under
 &UR; Jacques Lemaire &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Devils aren't reluctant to go on the
attack. Lemaire's game plan grew increasingly more conservative
(read: stifling).
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh defensive whiz  &UR; Rob Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; once dubbed a ``goal
suck'' by goalie  &UR; John Vanbiesbrouck &LR; , &UR;  &LR; will be out 6-8 weeks
following surgery Wednesday to repair a broken bone in his left
foot. Brown was felled by a  &UR; Garry Galley  &LR; slapper Tuesday night,
and he knew the diagnosis even before going for an X-ray. Brown:
``There's a pretty big dent where the bone used to be.' ... Quick
lesson in hockey's runaway economics: The Ducks, who had a $16.5
million player payroll in '96-97, this year are paying $31.5
million _ nearly a 100 percent increase in two years. According to
team president/GM  &UR; Pierre Gauthier &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Ducks, with ticket sales
down some 6 percent, will lose upwards of $9 million by the end of
the season ...  &UR; Steve Smith &LR; , &UR;  &LR; back in uniform after surrendering
to a bad back two years ago, is playing 20 minutes a night on the
Calgary blue line. The Flames some nights look to be taking shape,
but they really won't know their direction until they figure out
whether they can afford to re-sign  &UR; Theo Fleury &LR; , &UR;  &LR; their downsized
sharpshooter. If not, then now is the time to deal him, get some
value back, and move ahead with a full commitment to kids ... The
Canadiens likely won't pony up the bucks for  &UR; Mark Recchi  &LR; when
he's an unrestricted free agent next summer. When the bidding
begins, look for Dallas owner  &UR; Tom Hicks  &LR; to open wide his wallet
one more time. Recchi is close pals with Stars coach  &UR; Ken
Hitchcock &LR; , &UR;  &LR; once his junior coach in Kamloops ... When his wife
had to go to the Mayo Clinic recently for back surgery, Sabres
netminder  &UR; Dominik Hasek  &LR; brought along his pads, figuring he'd
stay sharp by practicing with a local junior B squad in Rochester,
Minn. But the diagnosis and surgery went so quickly that the
Dom-inator never got on the ice with the locals ... Ex-NHLer  &UR; Craig
Simpson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whose bad back forced him to pack it in at age 27,
recently had to miss a CTV commentary assignment because of vertigo
... As of last week, old friend  &UR; Jeff Odgers  &LR; led the league with
no fewer than 15 fighting majors. He recently got a two-year deal
with the Avalanche, worth a total of $1.2 million ... The Kings
next season will play in their new $350 million arena, but their
first home game isn't scheduled until Oct. 23. They'll play a
couple of early-season games in England, one in London and another
in Manchester. LA owner  &UR; Phil Anschutz  &LR; also owns a hockey team in
London (the Knights) ...  &UR; Stu Barnes &LR; , &UR;  &LR; relegated to fourth-line
duty for the Penguins in recent weeks, moved up a considerable
notch on the depth chart last week when  &UR; Alexei Morozov  &LR; went out
of the lineup with his second concussion in less than six weeks.
Head coach  &UR; Kevin Constantine  &LR; slotted Barnes between  &UR; Alexei
Kovalev  &LR; and  &UR; German Titov  &LR; the next night. Barnes, who makes $1.5
million a year, has been the subject of much trade speculation, but
GM  &UR; Craig Patrick  &LR; says he's not interested in dealing the
28-year-old center ... The Kings have seen next to nothing from
 &UR; Steve Duchesne  &LR; after laying out $11 million over four years to
woo him away from St. Louis ... Can anyone really believe that
 &UR; Pavel Bure &LR; , &UR;  &LR; yet to report to the Canucks, actually would give up
the idea of playing in North America for a $4 million deal in
Belarus next season? If so, you'd have to believe there is $4
million in all of Belarus. And if there is, what would it be worth
by the time the Russian Rocket pulls on skates? Truth is, there are
only a handful of teams that can pay Bure _ the Rangers, Wings,
Stars, Flyers, and maybe the Kings. When Canucks GM  &UR; Brian Burke
 &LR; hears the right offer from one of those clubs, that's where Bure
will play, and nowhere else. Oh, unless Hartford comes in with a
late bid, of course.
</P>
