<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLHOOP-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR UCONN, FLEET NOT NECESSARILY IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Connecticut the best men's team in the country? Perhaps,
perhaps not, but in December, it really is a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   What is more important for the Huskies is that they stay aware
of a couple of Atlantic Coast Conference teams in the polls and
computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's much too early to worry about NCAA Tournament
seedings, No. 1-ranked UConn should remember this as the season
unfolds: Even if the Huskies take care of business and finish with
a sparkling record _ we're not going to project them to run the
table quite yet _ they are no mortal lock for a No. 1 seed in the
East, which would mean first- and second-round games at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons. Duke, which did a pretty good job of
spanking Kentucky Tuesday night in the Meadowlands, and Maryland.
Both teams appear to be good enough to merit No. 1 seeds. With
first- and second-round regional games also slated for Charlotte,
the ACC teams, if they were ranked higher than UConn by the
tournament selection committee, would get preference and stay in
the East.
</P>
<P>
   Since a region obviously can't have two No. 1's, someone would
have to be shipped out, and that could be UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Huskies coach Jim Calhoun doesn't mind his team
traveling (as long as it's not to an opponent's home court, such as
North Carolina had at Greensboro in last year's East Regional
final). This season is different, however.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has never lost in the FleetCenter, and the Meadowlands,
site of this season's East Regional final, is a familiar and
comfortable venue for the Huskies as well as one easily accessible
to UConn fans.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, UConn has had to deal with some strange
geographical imbalances. The Huskies lost the West Regional a
couple of years ago to UCLA in Oakland. Greensboro last season was
one of the most one-sided home-court situations imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies must take care of their own business, not only in
March, during the single-elimination part of their season, but now
as well. They need to stay ahead of Maryland and Duke in the RPI
rankings, which seem to mean so much.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the Holiday Festival at Madison Square Garden
was the crown jewel of holiday tournaments, drawing large fields of
quality teams, who played before sellout crowds. Not anymore. This
year's field: Georgia Tech, Penn, Hofstra, and Iona. Ticket sales
are so bad that the Garden is making this offer: Any adult buying a
ticket can bring in any number of kids for free ... The FleetCenter
has been awarded first- and second-round games for the 2003 NCAA
Tournament. Count on it getting an East Regional site after that as
long as there are no serious glitches at this season's games ... Is
Rutgers women's coach  &UR; Vivian Stringer  &LR; a fan of the men's team or
not? Depends on whom the Scarlet Knights are playing. At last
week's Rutgers-Temple game, Stringer sat one row behind the bench _
the Temple bench. Coach  &UR; John Chaney &LR;  is an old friend. Stringer
made it known that she received the tickets from Chaney, although
she could have easily gotten great seats from the Rutgers athletic
department ... George Washington's  &UR; Tom Penders  &LR; has coached in 805
games, which puts him 14th on the active list. But he is the
runaway leader in number of teams coached among that elite group,
with stops at Tufts, Columbia, Fordham, Rhode Island, and Texas
before he came to George Washington last spring ... Atlantic 10
fans looking for an excuse for the slow start of the conference
teams can use this to warm their spirits. In the first RPI report
of the season, the Atlantic 10 had the second-toughest of
conference schedules, trailing only the Big 10 ... Pay attention to
Notre Dame freshman  &UR; Troy Murphy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is averaging 19.5 points
per game and already has been named Big East Rookie of the Week
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Maryland is off to such a quick start is the
play of guard  &UR; Steve Francis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a junior college transfer. While
some schools have made a living taking JC transfers (Cincinnati
comes to mind), Maryland is not one of them. Until Francis,
Maryland coach  &UR; Gary Williams  &LR; had recruited only two JC players in
nine years ... American-Puerto Rico's 2-0 forfeit loss to Oklahoma
_ after a brawl in Monday's first round of the Puerto Rico Holiday
Classic _ was rare but not unprecedented. According to NCAA
records, Chicago State forfeited a game to Illinois State in 1991
after a brawl in which 10 Chicago State players were ejected. In
1990, a game between North Carolina Central and North Carolina A&AMP;T
was declared no contest after a brawl resulted in injuries to seven
people ... Nothing like a good old-fashioned family feud in the
Southeastern Conference to start off the season. That's what's
happening between South Carolina's  &UR; Eddie Fogler  &LR; and Florida's
 &UR; Billy Donovan &LR; . Seems that Fogler questioned the propriety of a
basketball trip organized for Florida recruits by a financial
adviser. Fogler and Donovan got into a verbal sparring match during
SEC media day, and last week the SEC office reprimanded both. Said
Fogler, ``I said, `Is it ethical?' Does the release say anything
about whether it was illegal or not? It did not. As far as I'm
concerned, I stand by my statement.'' The Florida-South Carolina
games on Jan. 13 and Feb. 24 should be something else ... Look for
North Carolina to get even better now that freshman guard  &UR; Ronald
Curry  &LR; has finished his quarterbacking duties with the football
team ... Anyone check out what Ohio State has done in  &UR; Jim
O'Brien's  &LR; second year? Last year the Buckeyes were a woeful 8-22.
They have already surpassed that win total this season _ 11-2 ...
The rest of the America East teams may be playing for runner-up
status if Delaware continues its roll. The Blue Hens have yet to
lose in the nonconference part of their schedule. Even worse for
America East teams, the conference tournament will again be played
at Delaware, something that needs to be changed next season.
Delaware has gotten too good to have a home-court edge in the
postseason ... Here's Duke coach  &UR; Mike Krzyzewski &LR;  on sophomore
center  &UR; Elton Brand &LR; : &UR;  &LR; ``He can become an outstanding player. He's
not an outstanding player right now. If you feel that you've
already finished the journey, you don't continue to travel. He
needs to continue to travel and that's what we're trying to impress
upon him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
