<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COATES-TOUGHYEAR-     12-26 2466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COATES-TOUGHYEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT END'S YEAR COATED WITH ANGUISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The end is coming, but it can't come soon enough
for Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   In five more days, Coates will tear the final page from his wall
calendar with a sad flourish. A year littered with trials and a
trial will finally be over and he will move on, knowing there is
little chance that 1999 could be worse than this year just past, a
year in which he earned his fifth trip to the Pro Bowl and his
first trip to hell on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my personal problems, I wish the year was over right
now,'' the Patriots tight end said last week, as he prepared for
Sunday's regular-season finale against the New York Parcellses. ``I
look in the mirror some mornings and I can't wait until Dec. 31.
There has to be some good things for me in 1999 because it can't
get no worse than '98.''
</P>
<P>
   On the football field, 1998 was not unlike 1994 and 1995 and
1996 and 1997 for Coates. He was an unstoppable force at tight end
except on those Sundays when his own team stopped him by looking
elsewhere or on the one day two sprained ankles stopped him after
113 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   When such things did not conspire against him, Coates caught
enough passes to rank second among tight ends to Tennessee's
versatile Frank Wycheck, who led him by two (67 to 65) going into
the weekend but does not play the true tight end position.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Wycheck doesn't play like Coates does, and neither
does anyone else. Since he made his first Pro Bowl appearance in
1994, Coates has caught more passes for more yards than any other
tight end in the game, and that includes Denver's fast-talking
All-Pro Shannon Sharpe, but as Coates's position coach points out,
not even Sharpe comes close to doing all Coates is asked to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost nobody can fight a war against Reggie White and Mo
Lewis and Levon Kirkland and Henry Jones and win all those
battles,'' Carl Smith said. ``Some of the other guys are good at
certain things and try the rest. Ben does all those things and gets
them done.''
</P>
<P>
   What he gets done most often, though, is catching footballs in
clutch situations. Since his first Pro Bowl season, Coates has
hauled in 373 passes for 4,578 yards to Sharpe's 360 for 4,208, and
after them, no one else is even close. Yet even though he has put
up numbers this year similar to the ones that preceded them,
everything has been different because everything about 1998 has
been wrapped in the dark bunting of death or the white light of bad
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as the season went along the coaches wanted to get me
more involved in the offense to minimize the things going through
my mind,'' Coates said. ``But when you go home at night and the
phone is ringing at 5 a.m., you don't have to answer it to know
what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   What it has been about since training camp is death and discord.
The chaos of a domestic assault charge filed by the mother of one
of his daughters and the slow, sad death of family members left
Coates often worried and weary, his life seeming to have spun out
of his control.
</P>
<P>
   It began when he was arrested in training camp and charged with
assault by Jennifer Marshall, a former girlfriend to whom he pays
$54,000 a year in child support. The charges were questionable from
the start, as neighbors insisted Coates did none of what he was
accused of, but eventually he would have to answer them in court at
the same time his mother was dying in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Coates had buried his aunt and his 38-year-old sister,
and while he was still reeling from all of that, he sustained
double ankle sprains that left him on the sidelines for the first
time in his career. As he stood in jeans and jacket while his
teammates played the Indianapolis Colts, Coates understood for the
first time that the sideline was no place for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking, `What the hell am I doing in street
clothes?''' Coates recalled. ``We've had a lot of injuries, but
there are four or five of us _ myself, Drew (Bledsoe), Bruce
(Armstrong) _ who are always there. We've always played hurt. If
something is really wrong with No. 87, you'll know because I won't
be out there. Otherwise, I play.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest blow
</P>
<P>
   Actually, plenty has been wrong with No. 87 this season but few
people knew because he has played. Despite a sore knee and two
painful ankles that limited his mobility and for a time robbed him
of his quickness and speed, Coates missed only one game.
</P>
<P>
   He was not physically himself for half a season yet he played
on, gaining momentum just as his detractors started suggesting that
he may be a little too old or a little too slow to be what he'd
once been. This was all nonsense, but as his body healed, Coates's
mind came under assault from the kind of troubles that come from
living a life, not playing a sport.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Colts game, Coates learned that his sister had
died suddenly less than two months after his aunt had died, and he
went home to South Carolina to bury another woman who had been
close to him. Not long after he came back, the worst news hit just
as he was learning that his lawyers had been unable to convince a
local prosecutor to drop the assault charges against him. Coates's
mother, Mozella, was found to have an inoperable brain tumor. At
56, her time was short.
</P>
<P>
   During most weeks, Coates would leave Foxborough each Monday,
fly home, return in time for Wednesday's practice, play on Sunday,
and then repeat the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was just a matter of time before she passed,''
Coates said. ``There was nothing anyone could do about it. You just
had to wait and hope she'd survive the season so I could go home
and be with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I had to go to court, all the pressure started to build.
I did find it hard to concentrate on the field. Defenses were
moving around to try and stop me and sometimes I had trouble seeing
what was going on. I had to get over that hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got to the point with my sister calling, telling me how
my mother kept getting worse, that I asked, `Why me?' My aunt had
passed. My sister had passed. Then the ultimate one, my mother. You
start to think, `Can't I get a break?' It's been a very difficult
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Smith said, Coates seldom showed the effects of
his stresses on the job. In the huddle, he would find his refuge.
There nothing bad could happen. No phones could ring. No bad news
could reach him. No lawyers could get to him with false charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would come and tell me when something had happened, so I
knew what he was going through,'' Smith said. ``Some days he'd be
pretty quiet but when he got on the field he was home. I think that
carried him through. That was the good time for him.''
</P>
<P>
   His day in court
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, Coates began to have more good times at his
opponents' expense. He had two touchdowns on two receptions against
Kansas City, which is about as efficient as you can get. He had a
10-catch game against the Colts when they thought rumors of his
demise might be true and tried to play him man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody tried that nonsense much after that, but Coates continued
to catch passes even as he was hauled into court to defend himself
in December, the same week his mother was breathing her last.
</P>
<P>
   He had 16 receptions against Buffalo and Pittsburgh leading up
to his trial date, then had to go sit for three days as his lawyers
told a jury that their client had assaulted no one but rather was a
250-pound victim of a woman who had threatened she would ``own his
contract and he would be running on the field for the rest of his
life for her.''
</P>
<P>
   One witness testified that Marshall ``started whaling on him''
after she confronted Coates outside his home about another woman.
Other neighbors testified that she went on a screaming rampage,
cursing and threatening Coates, saying she would call a police
detective she knew and have him arrested. Coates's guest, another
woman, testified that Marshall hit and threatened her, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a real estate agent said Marshall had phoned a week
after the July altercation to say that she wanted to see three
high-priced homes, one worth $749,900. After seeing them, the agent
testified, Marshall made the statement about owning Coates's
contract and advised the agent to watch the papers. A luxury car
dealer told a similar tale.
</P>
<P>
   After this, Coates's attorneys pushed for a dismissal that would
have allowed him to go see his dying mother immediately. The
request was denied and he went home on the evening of Dec. 9
knowing the case would go to the jury the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting in court that day, I had a bad feeling,'' Coates
recalled. ``Soon as I got home, my sister called. She never calls
unless something bad happens. She asked how soon I could get down.
She said it wouldn't be long now. I told her they wouldn't let me
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 6:30 or seven (p.m.), my brother called. He said my
mother was gone. It was a shock. It was devastating. I never saw
her again.''
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, after closing arguments, Coates left
Wrentham District Court immediately and flew home on Bob Kraft's
private jet to bury his mother. Less than an hour after he was
gone, the jury acquitted him. That nightmare was over but the end
had come one day too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been going down every Monday except when we played to see
her,'' Coates recalled. ``I'd be down there with her and sometimes
she'd know me and sometimes she wouldn't. It's hard to see your
mother in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very discouraging at times. Her temperature and her
blood pressure was rising and she was having real bad headaches.
Each time I came back I knew it was not going to be too much longer
but instead of me being there at the end I had to be in court when
an average person would have had that case thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they were trying to make a point because of who I was.
Maybe they couldn't dismiss it. I know there are guys who don't pay
child support or claim their own kids but I've never failed to pay
for her. The reason I don't see my daughter is because (Marshall)
always wants to do things as a family and we're not a family. It's
me and my daughter, not her. Maybe when my daughter is 18 I'll
explain to her how it was. But it's too much trouble now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big setup that didn't go the way she planned it. I
knew we'd win. I told my wife that but it still was embarrassing to
be sitting there when I should have been home with my mother for
her last few hours. When I finally got to South Carolina I told the
Patriots I couldn't make the game in St. Louis. I was totally not
into it. I wouldn't have helped them, even though we're a better
team when I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Long season prolonged
</P>
<P>
   After Coates returned last week, outwardly it was as if nothing
had happened. He is stoic by nature and inclination. A funny guy
when he lets his personality show, he seldom speaks to the media
although he's usually cordial enough when he declines to talk,
choosing mostly to speak on Sundays when footballs are coming his
way.
</P>
<P>
   So it was last weekend, a week after he'd buried his mother and
was acquitted in court, when he went out against the San Francisco
49ers on fourth and 2 with the game on the line. He went out and
did what he's well-paid to do. He made the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard what people were saying about me,'' Coates said. ``I
knew there were people saying I've lost a step. I didn't take that
to heart because when my team needs a touchdown or a first down,
who do they throw it to? Who do they go to in the Red Zone? On that
fourth and 2, everyone in the stadium knew (Scott) Zolak would
throw to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Niners did, as well, and they braced Coates with two
linebackers but he shielded them off with his body and caught the
ball to preserve a drive that would bring New England victory and a
place in the playoffs. What that catch also meant is that Ben
Coates's long season will be longer now.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as it drags on, the worst is finally over. The sadness
still exists when he thinks of his mother, sister, and aunt already
gone. The anger still exists when he thinks of the woman who
falsely accused him or of the court that refused to let him see his
mother one last time.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly he just counts the days until Jan. 1. It will not be
long after midnight that Coates rips that last page off his
calendar and puts behind him an All-Pro year of sadness. It is a
year whose end will bring no nostalgic thoughts. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben is a strong person,'' said his agent and friend, Michael
George. ``At his mother's funeral he was taking care of everyone,
but when they went to lower her casket, he grabbed his kids and
hugged them tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who takes care of things in his family. This has
been a trial for him. It's about as rough a period in your life as
you can have but he'll survive it. He'll be fine one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely he will. One fine day, maybe Jan. 1, maybe later. Until
then he'll think about 1998 and have to be satisfied just being a
fine tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't ever a day he didn't do what he needed to do,''
Smith said. ``He never had a down game, even when he was hurting.
Through all his troubles we knew he had a lot left. You could see
that down the stretch. When we had to win games, Drew went to him
because he's Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he was tired Ben. Sometimes he was injured Ben.
Sometimes he was frustrated Ben. Other times he was sad Ben. But
always on Sunday he was reliable Ben. Same as he'd always been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to New England I wasn't that aware of him,'' said
his old mentor, Bill Parcells, last week. ``I knew they thought he
was a good young talent. Bobby Grier had told me that. Once I saw
him in practice it didn't take too long to realize he's what we
wanted to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``That decision took about 15 minutes in practice. I'm not going
to take much credit for that. I'll give Ben all the credit. If he
never catches another pass, he's had a great career.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a career that didn't come to an end in 1998, even when it
seemed like the rest of his world was closing in on him. It didn't
end but it changed because after a year like this, everything
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole season has been lessened because of all these
things,'' Coates said. ``I don't know what to think about it. Maybe
it was a sign from the Man above to wake up. You go through these
things and it makes you change your priorities. You see it's time
to do the things you weren't doing, if you weren't doing them.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were things Ben Coates wasn't doing, it wasn't on
Sunday. Never on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
