<HEADLINE>
GAME HITS HOME IN MORE THAN ONE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glad to see The Tuna is as disingenuous as ever. But that's part
of the charm, no?
</P>
<P>
   The media makes more of this. I know a lot of players on that
team. I know what the relationships are. But what it really is is
good copy. I don't let the personal stuff get into it. I never
have. That's ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   No, Bill, that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   And you damn well know it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good rivalry. I expect the game to be clean and
hard-hitting. You acquire a respect for a quality opponent and
that's what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, and your great and good friend Bob Knight would care
just as much about beating Minnesota as he does Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   There may be meaningless games in Week 16, but this is not one
of them. Carolina (3-12) at Indianapolis (3-12), this ain't. When
the ball gets kicked off at the Meadowlands this afternoon, the
adrenaline will be flowing, and a great deal of it will be pumping
inside the ``dispassionate'' mentor of the New York Jets, who would
rather be sentenced to a veggie diet the rest of his life than lose
to the New England Patriots, the team owned by You Know Who, a.k.a.
the Connecticut Kid.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots very much want to win this game, and no one knows
this better than Parcells, who is the reigning expert on NFL
strategy and psychology. Were he coaching a team in the Patriots'
situation, he would be preaching the absolute necessity of a
victory, without which there will be no chance of a home game when
the wild-card phase of the playoffs begins next week. A Patriots
victory will not provide that home game unless the Dolphins
cooperate by losing at Atlanta, but it is mandatory if there is to
be any hope at all.
</P>
<P>
   So The Tuna knows what this game means to the Patriots, and
because it is the Patriots, he will care more about this game than
he would if it were against the Broncos, Vikings, or Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It just isn't cool to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   He can't slip this jive by us. We well remember the goings-on in
January and early February of 1997, when Parcells went to the legal
mattresses to extricate himself from New England. He had declared
war on Bob Kraft, and there is no way the passion has diminished.
In his mind, he is Athens and the Patriots are Sparta, and as long
as Kraft owns the team, that is never going to change.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffwise, the Jets are locked in, but Parcells has more than
enough incentive Sunday. He is on record as saying that he wants
the Jets to become the first team in franchise history to win 12
games. Is that really important? The 1968 team, which went on to
win Super Bowl III, was 11-3 in a 14-game schedule. Well, it
certainly seems to be important to Parcells, and if that's the
case, he doesn't want to blow his opportunity to become the Jets'
single-season coaching leader by losing to the, ugh, Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   This is likewise a very big game for Pete Carroll. The general
public perception is that he has yet to defeat Parcells in an NFL
game. Even some of his players have suggested that the only way for
the Parcells ghost to be exorcised is for the Patriots to win this
game.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the events of Sept. 14, 1997, never took place.
</P>
<P>
   The teams played in Foxborough on that Monday evening. The final
score was New England 27, New York 24, and you can look it up.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of curse, is that it sure didn't feel like a W.
With 16 seconds remaining in regulation, the Jets were encamped on
the New England 12-yard line in a tie game. All John Hall had to do
was ram home the perfunctory 29-yarder, and the Jets would win. But
Mike Jones got a hand on the kick, and the teams were forced into
OT. Adam Vinatieri's 34-yard field goal provided the Patriots with
a scary triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have won the last two meetings, and now people have it
in their heads that Carroll has yet to defeat Parcells. It may be
weird, but it's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, and Carroll, need this game even if Miami upsets
Atlanta and thus sends them on the road next week. Parcells's great
success in New York has enhanced the legend. The Patriots have got
to find a way to knock off The Tuna, Drew Bledsoe or no Drew
Bledsoe, or else Carroll will continue to be regarded as the
consolation prize in these here parts.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the Jets were 1-15. With a victory Sunday they
would be 12-4. Two years ago the Patriots were in the Super Bowl.
With a loss they will finish at 9-7 and will be serious underdogs
in the first round of the playoffs. It will be impossible not to
play the compare-and-contrast game, and it won't matter to most
people that the Patriots really have been whacked by injury this
season. It will be 12-4 vs. 9-7. It will be a team looking like the
biggest obstacle for Denver getting to the Super Bowl vs. a fairly
decent odds-on to be an over-and-out playoff participant.
</P>
<P>
   In a better world, Parcells would stop the nonsense and tell us
the truth. He would say, yeah, sure, I want to beat the Patriots in
the worst way. It would help me and hurt them, and what could be
better than that? But he would rather insult our intelligence by
pretending it's Just Another Game, when we know otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
