<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-FRYAR-BO     12-26 2197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-FRYAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREACHER ALWAYS DID HIS SUNDAY BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I've been a puppet, a pauper, a pirate, a poet,
</P>
<P>
   ``A pawn and a king.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been up and down and over and out, and I know one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I find myself flat on my face,
</P>
<P>
   ``I pick myself up and get back in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``That's Life,'' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; as sung by Frank Sinatra &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Irving Fryar has been flat on his face more often than Rocky
Balboa.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen more ups and downs than the Otis Elevator Co.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 years in the NFL, he's been not only a puppet, a pauper, a
pirate, a poet, a pawn, and a king but also a playmaker and a
prayer-taker.
</P>
<P>
   He's been to the Pro Bowl five times and to a jail cell once.
He's been roundly applauded and lustily booed. He's played in the
Super Bowl and in the Stupor Bowl. He's been on the best team in
one conference and the worst team in two. He's run pass patterns
for the leading passer of all time and for guys who passed out at
the thought of facing an NFL defense (anyone remember Jeff
Carlson?).
</P>
<P>
   When Sinatra sang ``That's Life,'' he could have had Irving
Fryar in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Through all those years and so many of his troubles, Fryar was
always a couple of things. He was, even in his worst moments, a
good guy who hurt only himself and he was always an unselfish
football player.
</P>
<P>
   Not an unselfish wide receiver. Fryar was an unselfish football
player, which is not something that can be said of every wide
receiver who ever played, including some of the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   On weekdays and too many nights during his nine years in New
England, Fryar was not always what a coach wanted, but _ with the
exception of one memorable afternoon when he became the only player
I've known in 24 years around the NFL to get into a car accident at
halftime _ he was that on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Irving Fryar was as unselfish a player as the
Patriots, Miami Dolphins, and now Philadelphia Eagles ever knew. On
Sunday, he ran as hard when he was a decoy as he did when he was
the primary receiver. On Sunday, he blocked as hard as he worked to
get open. On Sunday, Fryar played football the way it's supposed to
be played.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he will play his last. Although at 36 there is still a
place for him in the NFL, it is no longer the place he wants to
occupy. After too many hits and too many patterns run recklessly
across the middle, after too many kick returns and too many games
played for bad teams, Fryar has decided to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   His last team, the Eagles, is as bad and as rudderless as some
of the ones he once toiled for in New England before he escaped to
Miami in 1993 and began a run of four trips to the Pro Bowl in five
years. During his second coming in Miami _ where he first found God
and then found himself _ Fryar regularly put on the kind of
performances that had been projected for him in 1984, when the
Patriots made him the first wide receiver in history selected with
the first pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years of being drafted, he was to go to his first Pro
Bowl _ as a fearless punt returner _ and few thought it would be
eight years before he would return. By the time that next trip
came, few thought he'd ever make it there again.
</P>
<P>
   Too much happened between 1985 and his escape from New England,
and there's no need to repeat it all Sunday. Suffice it to say,
life was harder than football for Fryar in those years, but I can
still remember meeting him at his mother's house in Mt. Holly,
N.J., just after the draft and finding him to be as charming as a
young athlete could be.
</P>
<P>
   He remained that even in his darkest days, when drugs and a
fascination with street life he now admits could have been fatal
nearly consumed him. That afternoon in Mt. Holly, Fryar's mother
talked of her deep faith and so did her son. He had sung in the
church choir and learned to play five instruments there, and
fortunately a trail blazed on the right path by his mother when he
was young went deep enough to save him in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Fryar is one of only four licensed preachers in the NFL and,
reports say, one of its best. That comes as no surprise, because
when Fryar put his many God-given gifts to work at something, few
could stay with him. As things turned out, that was true even for
Beelzebub, because Fryar outmaneuvered even the Devil in his last
days in New England and then broke away from him and into the open
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Fryar the Fabulous was free to emerge, and he did,
registering 1,000 yards receiving four times in five years between
1993-97 and barely missing that mark (910) in the fifth. He even
got to do what few athletes ever do _ star for his hometown team in
Philadelphia for two years before age and the heavy weight of
defeat seemed to slow him this season.
</P>
<P>
   That brought him some criticism in a season when there was
little else for the Eagles, but this time he deserved none of it.
Perhaps he had grown too old. Perhaps his body took longer to heal
now than it used to, as Fryar's wife, Jackie, alluded to at his
retirement announcement. Perhaps he could no longer do on the field
what he once had done. But Fryar deserves no more criticism because
he has done what few of us ever do. He has made the most of
himself, not the least.
</P>
<P>
   He not only maximized his football skills but also became a man
instead of continuing to live the boy's life. He turned his life
around and then turned around more than a few others, and that has
meant more to him than all the pass receptions he ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he has made so many of the latter that they cannot be
ignored. Few football fans in these parts might guess that Fryar
ranks seventh all-time in receptions with 781, eighth all-time in
yardage with 11,947, 11th all-time in 100-yard games with 32, 15th
all-time in touchdowns with 77 and, perhaps most telling of all,
second all-time to Jerry Rice in receptions after the age of 30
with 473.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some in New England who will fume that had he
started his resurrection earlier, the Patriots might have won more
games and perhaps even a championship by now, but that is
small-time thinking. He did it his way, Fryar did, and it has
worked out and that's why everyone should be rooting for him to
become on the football field what he has never been before.
</P>
<P>
   On his last day, Fryar should be selfish. He needs to demand the
ball and the Eagles need to throw it to him because if he can make
five more receptions for 53 more yards he will reach two more
milestones. He will have made 50 catches or more for the ninth
straight season and become only the eighth player in history to
gain 12,000 yards on pass receptions.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Fryar could go into the Pro Football Hall of Fame with
those kinds of numbers. He'd already be a shoo-in in Cooperstown,
where numbers mean everything. It may be more difficult in Canton,
where your team's play counts for something, too, but it will be
difficult for anyone to justify keeping him out if he can reach
those final milestones and he can be sure he has at least one vote
when the time comes if he needs it because he's won it both with
the way he's played and with the way he's lived.
</P>
<P>
   Fryar has a lot to be proud of Sunday, his final day in the NFL.
He has numbers and the change he made from devil's disciple to
God's warrior and he has one more thing. He has the assurance that
his last request has already been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I want to be remembered?'' Fryar asked last week. ``As
a football player. Not just a receiver, but a guy who blocked, who
was a decoy when he was supposed to be, who tackled when he had
to.''
</P>
<P>
   He was all of that and more. He was a man Sinatra could sing
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record shows
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the blows
</P>
<P>
   ``And did it my way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was my way.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been the hard way sometimes but, in the end, it was
the right way, too, because look where it has led Rev. Irving
Fryar. It led him back home to Mt. Holly with the same wife and
four kids he started out with. It led him home with numbers they
can all be proud of beside his name.
</P>
<P>
   If that's life, it's been a good one, so here's hoping when the
last day of his NFL life is over, Irving Fryar will have those five
catches and the 53 yards he wants so badly.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows, he's earned 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Good omen for the Patriots Sunday. After a five-game stretch in
which the Jets' defense allowed only 206.4 yards a game, it has
given up an average of 366.7 the past three weeks ... Bad omen for
the Patriots Sunday. According to the Elias Sports Bureau,  &UR; Bill
Parcells's  &LR; teams are 48-0 when entering the fourth quarter with at
least a 10-point lead ... The Arizona Cardinals ran up the
inflation flag a bit higher last week when they signed 24-year-old
quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer  &LR; to a four-year extension that carried
with it the largest signing bonus in NFL history, $15 million. The
previous largest bonus was $12.99 million given to  &UR; Deion Sanders
 &LR; by the Dallas Cowboys and the largest ever handed out by the
Cardinals had been $10.491 million to No. 1 pick  &UR; Andre Wadsworth
 &LR; in September. Perhaps out of sympathy for Cardinals owner  &UR; Bill
Bidwell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Arizona fans went out and bought up more than 7,000
tickets for Sunday's game with San Diego that could put the
Cardinals into the playoffs for the first time since 1982.
Plummer's teammate  &UR; Chris Dishman  &LR; put into perspective just what
that bonus meant: ``He could buy my whole town (Cozad, Neb.). But
he deserves it. He's going to take the team a long way.'' Plummer
will receive the bonus in two parts. The first $11.25 million is
payable next year, and the remaining $3.75 million comes in 2000.
One reason Plummer got all that cash now is that he led the
Cardinals to eight come-from-behind victories in his first 24
starts, the last coming 24 hours before he signed his new deal when
he found a way to beat the New Orleans Saints, 19-17, last Sunday.
The other reason is that by getting the deal done before the end of
this season, Arizona can count $3 million of the bonus against this
year's salary cap ... For those of you keeping score at home,
 &UR; Terrell Davis's  &LR; quest to break  &UR; Eric Dickerson's  &LR; single-season
rushing record hit some major roadblocks the past two weeks and it
will take a gargantuan effort for him to make it now. Davis still
leads the NFL with 1,830 yards rushing but he has been held under
100 two of the past three games and fell far off the pace to match
Dickerson's 2,105 when he rushed for just 29 yards against the
Dolphins last Monday night. Davis needs 275 yards Sunday to tie
Dickerson. Don't count on that ... Being a No. 2 pick and a running
back does not bode well if you're a Saint. Last year, coach  &UR; Mike
Ditka  &LR; cut  &UR; Mario Bates &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a running back the Saints had taken on
the second round in 1994. This year he did the same to  &UR; Ray
Zellars &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the team's No. 2 selection in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's decision to go to a spread offense has paid big
dividends. Coach  &UR; Wade Phillips  &LR; believes spread formations have
been a big part of the Bills' remarkable resurgence under  &UR; Doug
Flutie &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who made them the first team in history to reach the
playoffs after starting 0-3. The spread, with one back and four
receivers or no back and five receivers littered from sideline to
sideline, gives Flutie a faster look at what defense he is facing
and hence more time to figure out how to beat it, Phillips
believes. Yet the spread hasn't hurt running back  &UR; Antowain
Smith &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is seventh in the AFC with 1,082 rushing yards. Bills
fullback  &UR; Sam Gash  &LR; concedes that 1,000 yards doesn't mean what it
used to because of the 16-game schedule but argues, ``What it does
mean is that your running game is effective. It's the barrier that
separates the good running backs from the average ones.'' ... As
many as nine new head coaches could be in the league next fall,
which shows just how dangerous a job it is running an NFL team. But
one who survived was St. Louis's  &UR; Dick Vermeil &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who sadly has
seemed overmatched since returning to the NFL. So why is he back?
It would have cost the Rams $5.7 million to buy him out, a
circumstance that made him look a lot better to  &UR; Georgia Frontiere
 &LR; and  &UR; John Shaw  &LR; than his record does ... It looks as though  &UR; John
Kent Cooke  &LR; will not succeed his father as owner of the Redskins.
Word is his bid to buy the team from his father's estate was not
among the top four offers last week. Two of the groups in the
bidding were also in the Cleveland horse race and a third has
ex-Redskin coach  &UR; Joe Gibbs  &LR; as a partner ... Apparently rookie
linebacker  &UR; Travian Smith  &LR; took a lot of heat in Oakland last week
for his zealousness. He had been promoted from the practice squad
and was so fired up to play against the Chargers that he was in
full uniform at his locker 90 minutes before the game. While
everyone else was still in shorts and T-shirts, Smith sat silently
in full gear, staring into space. ``When I looked over at him, it
just cracked me up,'' said receiver  &UR; Tim Brown &LR; . Reports are Smith
played well when he got the chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
