<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SELIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING GAPS A FULL TIME JOB FOR SELIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bud Selig probably wakes up a lot of mornings wondering why
anyone would agree to become the commissioner of baseball. Life was
a lot simpler when he had only the Milwaukee Brewers to oversee.
His six-year stint as acting commissioner was mostly a labor of
love.
</P>
<P>
   But while his relations are better now with the Players
Association, Selig is quick to admit that being full-time
commissioner is in many ways more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget that the battle between unrestrained owners
and overzealous players once boiled down to simple language. Owners
wanted salary caps, players didn't. Owners wanted revenue sharing
and high thresholds before the so-called luxury taxes kicked in.
But since the end of last season, clubs have tossed around millions
upon millions in pursuit of an elusive World Series trip. From the
commissioner's view, that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is a disparity problem,'' says Selig, who has
turned over the reins of the Brewers to his daughter. ``One that
has seriously escalated over the past 2-3 years and especially the
last few months. I have every confidence that we will deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we do have the process of putting revenue sharing
in place. I don't think people really realize what that means. It
becomes fully implemented in the year 2000 but it does jump up some
next year. That's when we'll send $140 million from the top six to
the bottom six. Plus, there are a series of internal controls that
will deal with this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the problem is in the eye of the beholder. You won't
find new Dodger Kevin Brown or his agent, Scott Boras, complaining
about the $107 million contract the pitcher signed to leave San
Diego. And why did anybody think Mo Vaughn would decline an $80
million offer from Anaheim? The stakes are too high. Both Fox
(which owns the Dodgers) and Disney (Angels) want baseball's
greatest show to come to Southern California. All the previous
regimes wanted was to win. The new bosses want to create a
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The moving of two New York teams to California decades ago is
peanuts compared with the maneuverings on the West Coast these
days.
</P>
<P>
   By reaching the World Series last season, the San Diego Padres
impressed their fans enough to get a new stadium. Yet by losing
several key players _ Brown, Steve Finley, Joey Hamilton _ the
Padres could find themselves relegated again to also-ran status.
According to figures calculated by management's Player Relations
Committee and reported by the Associated Press, San Diego had a
payroll of $52.9 million, ninth-highest in the majors. And in
January the Padres must go to arbitration to sign three pitchers:
Sterling Hitchcock, Dan Mecir, and Woody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That's show business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt that for many years baseball would repress all its
problems,'' said Selig. ``A kind of `we'll think about it next year
philosophy.' We can't do that anymore. Owners also have to
understand we can't have a work stoppage. So this has to be solved
in very creative ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there are people who are concerned about the
economics of baseball. It was one of the reasons I took this job. I
can promise one thing. The whole problem of disparity in economics
is something that has to be dealt with, and more importantly will
be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   The top six payrolls last year were Baltimore ($73.9 million),
New York Yankees ($73.8 million), Texas ($62.1 million), Atlanta
($61.7 million), Los Angeles ($60.7 million), and Boston ($59.3
million). The low six were Minnesota ($22 million), Cincinnati
($20.7 million), Florida ($19.1 million), Oakland ($18.5 million),
Pittsburgh ($13.6 million), and Montreal ($8.3 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been like this,'' said Selig. ``There was always
concern about disparity, but in the late '80s other teams were
winning. Minnesota was winning. Milwaukee and Kansas City were both
very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, there are a lot of things the commissioner can do to
try to deal with this. Like always, the solution will come from a
myriad of sources and I'm very confident we can do it. The clubs _
big, medium, and small _ all understand this is a problem that has
to be dealt with. I've had no resistance from anybody on that
concept. Now, when we get into separate plans, that's a different
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras recently said it does not surprise him that people are
upset about the high prices demanded by players. But it goes with
the territory, he added, and those seeking quality talent should
expect to be asked for the fair market price _ even if that price
is outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to shoot the messenger when the message is
frustrating,'' said Boras. ``But I operate in the area of truth.
When I said I had the offers (for Brown and Bernie Williams),
everyone scoffed and said, `That's crazy!' In the end, everyone
responded to the market and even exceeded the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet next time when we say we have certain years and terms,
teams are going to not question it. My job is to carry that
bulletproof vest and go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners will be going through it in their quarterly meetings in
San Diego in two weeks. The creativity necessary for modern
solutions could come from a new source. Central Baseball, as the
New York office is now called, is headed by Sandy Alderson and Paul
Beeston, former top executives in Oakland and Toronto,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've created for the first time in the central office
that not only a lot of momentum but a different attitude than we've
ever had,'' said Selig. Between the three of us we have 66 years of
experience in running franchises. Baseball has never had that
before. Each one of these people along with Rob Manfred and several
others really bring insight to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice part of doing this job after running a franchise is
that there are no secrets. I'm not surprised at anything and
neither are they. I had six years as commissioner before I took
this job. So nobody could go into a job with more knowledge and
understanding of the people problems. I feel a greater sense of
responsibility now. I understand that as painful as some of the
solutions may be, we've got to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the most innocent questions provoke the most
interesting answers. Asked if the Red Sox had any interest in
 &UR; Ramon Martinez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the older brother of Boston's ace, general
manager  &UR; Dan Duquette  &LR; said that, in a perfect world, he'd like to
have  &UR; Pedro &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Ramon, and a third brother,  &UR; Jesus &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has
pitched briefly in the majors, most recently with Cincinnati.
Trouble is, Ramon and Jesus are free agents recovering from
shoulder operations. Few clubs may gamble on them at  &UR; today &LR; 's
prices, although the Red Sox might be an exception. The Dodgers
don't think Ramon will be able to pitch until around the All-Star
break, and they are confident he will re-sign with them. ``You
never know,'' said Duquette. ``It would be great to see all three
brothers wearing a Red Sox uniform.'' Sure ... Hopefully,  &UR; Roger
Clemens  &LR; learned a valuable lesson in his failed attempt to escape
Toronto by forcing a trade. No matter how many Cy Young Awards he
wins, the bottom line is money, and if the numbers don't come out
right, the same people who were singing his praises will turn
against him. Still, he may wind up somewhere else, only this time,
he'll know it's not just because somebody out there likes him. He
should try Arizona. Ownership just spent $108 million for three
players _  &UR; Randy Johnson &LR; , &UR; Steve Finley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre &LR; .
We know that Diamondbacks owner  &UR; Jerry Colangelo &LR;  can afford it.
Remember, the Florida Marlins made it to the World Series in only
their fifth year of existence ... As far as I'm concerned, it's
still a dead heat between home run hitters  &UR; Mark McGwire  &LR; of St.
Louis and  &UR; Sammy Sosa  &LR; of the Cubs. Sosa showed his true grit in
going to the Far East and talking the Japanese into building 1,000
prefab homes for hurricane victims in his native Dominican
Republic. Last week, McGwire came through with the first donations
in an ambitious plan to provide $1 million annually for three years
to benefit abused children. McGwire sent out four checks of
$175,000, two to charities in St. Louis and two more in Southern
California. The two sluggers should have been on the cover of Time
magazine, not Sports Illustrated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
