</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA TRIES TO FORGET MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA guard Andy Meyers completed the purge
Wednesday afternoon when he grabbed reserve quarterback Drew
Bennett by the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers had no quarrel with Bennett, but his T-shirt had to go.
So after the Bruins' final pre-Christmas practice, dowsed in bright
sun and holiday spirit, Meyers playfully grabbed Bennett and ripped
the shirt off his back.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``Hurricane Bowl'' shirt, gray, with UCLA and Miami
logos on the back, along with the date that will live in infamy in
Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last one in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bennett didn't think I was serious at first, until I grabbed
him,'' Meyers said a few minutes later, the shredded T-shirt
dangling from his pants. ``I'm going to make sure it goes in the
trash.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Meyers hopes, the Bruins severed all remaining
physical ties to the costliest loss in school history _ a loss they
can neither forget nor explain, but must overcome. If they walk
into the Rose Bowl on Friday with Miami on their minds, they'll
have Wisconsin stamped on their foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear stories about teams getting embarrassed and not
getting up for the next game, and then getting embarrassed again,''
Bruins quarterback Cade McNown said. ``As soon as the past starts
affecting your future, you have to change your mindset . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in the Rose Bowl and how we respond will dictate
what sort of season it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been an easy month for the Bruins. After a 20-game
winning streak, they had forgotten what losing felt like. The 49-45
collapse in Miami on Dec. 5 unleashed a fury of emotion _ players
in shock, players in tears, offense blaming defense, defense
feeling the blame. Meyers, a senior captain, was smack in the
middle of it, angry, outspoken and critical as he sat by his locker
in the bowels of the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But Meyers was also one of the first to start the healing
process. On the long, quiet flight home, he walked the aisles and
spoke with several players about what had gone wrong and what was
ahead. He offered an honest critique and words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Meyers met with several defensive players in a
conference room in the Morgan Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't apologize,'' he said. ``It was more about what we had
to do to get tighter. Hey, they're used to me popping off. They
know what I said was not unfounded, and I didn't rip any
individuals. I think it helped the team. It brought us to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, the winning streak's over, the national
championship's over, but the Rose Bowl's not over.' That's what
we've got on our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The healing progressed at different rates for different players.
For some, the pain lasted a few days. For some, it lingered until
the following weekend, when the Bruins assembled for their first
Rose Bowl practice. A few needed the urgency of exams to break free
from the funk.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 23, when Meyers ripped off Bennett's T-shirt and the
Bruins scattered for Christmas, they seemingly had turned their
collective gaze from Miami to Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Out with the Fiesta, in with the Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids always bounce back; they're more resilient than
coaches,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be fine. The last game is so important to win.
For the seniors, it gives you a good feeling to finish your career.
And it's good for the younger guys going into the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Fiesta Bowl meant everything, the Bruins have come to
realize the Rose Bowl means (begin ital)something(end ital). It's a
chance to win a school-record 11th game. (Five UCLA teams have won
10.) It's a chance to win the school's first Rose Bowl since 1986
and a chance to improve on the No. 5 national ranking, hence
bettering last year's finish.
</P>
<P>
   For 105 players who have never participated in the Rose Bowl,
who have never eaten at Lawry's Beef Bowl or done Disneyland or
toured Universal Studios or run across the giant rose in the middle
of the field, the game has meaning. Until this year, after all, the
Rose Bowl was UCLA's No. 1 goal.
</P>
<P>
   The prestige hasn't faded. The Bruins just needed a few weeks to
put Miami in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flipping channels the other day and I found the 1980
Rose Bowl game with USC and Ohio State,'' said Bruins freshman
linebacker Ryan Nece, whose father, ex-Trojan Ronnie Lott, played
in that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this. It's No. 1 (Ohio State) against No. 3
(USC) and they're going at it. There are great players, Charles
White, Marcus Allen, my dad's in it. I saw the rose in the middle
and the stands were packed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm thinking, `We're going to be there.' It's what I
always wanted to play in since I was little. People ask us, `Are
you ready?' We're definitely ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-ART-2N     12-26 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: out censure. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And even Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has said that he wants
to see a vote on the two articles of impeachment sent by the House
before any talk of censure, could turn out to be the ultimate
pragmatist. He has denounced Clinton's ``reprehensible behavior.''
But as the head of the Senate Republicans' re-election effort in
2000, he will have 19 Republicans to shepherd to re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the Senate's strongest conservatives calculate that
they would rather see the president censured than simply acquitted,
says a Republican aide close to the social conservative movement.
Most lawmakers apparently think the Senate, with 55 Republicans,
will never be able to reach the 67 votes necessary to remove the
president from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't support censure to replace the trial process or in
any way impede us from moving to a trial,'' said Sen. Wayne Allard,
R-Colo. ``But once you've had the trial, then afterward I could
possibly support censure.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Democratic Party appears unified against Clinton's
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Passions have cooled since August, when the president first
confessed to an ``inappropriate relationship'' with Monica
Lewinsky, after seven months of denials. Lieberman, a longtime ally
in the ``New Democrat'' movement, called the president's conduct
``disgraceful'' and ``immoral.'' Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., often at odds with Clinton over policy, also criticized his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But both men are now supporting censure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, an 81-year-old Democrat from West Virginia and
the unofficial historian of the Senate, is another unpredictable
personality fiercely jealous of the prerogatives of the Senate. He
has already sent a sharp warning to the White House that any
censure measure that is worked out should not involve ``any entity
beyond the current membership of the U.S. Senate.'' But Byrd is
indeed speaking with Senate colleagues about the wisest course of
action.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also surprised Republicans who had predicted that he
would be a strict constitutionalist and insist the Senate have a
trial. Last week, he left the door open to the possibility that
there could be ``some other solution.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are Democrats who think there should
not be a censure deal _ or at least not unless Clinton first
defeats the two articles of impeachment in Senate votes.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said he had been telling the president's aides: ``You
guys have got to get a grip here. Quit pushing for censure. You
don't want to be the only president in history to be impeached and
have it hang over your head the rest of your life. You want to be
exonerated.'' (Andrew Johnson, the one other president to be
impeached, was spared conviction by the Senate.)
</P>
<P>
   For all the maneuvering, senators have been become cautious
about predicting events in the aftermath of the House's vote for
impeachment, once considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this trial starts, anything can happen,'' Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., said last week. ``I think that already we've seen
so many turns and twists in the road, and I think we're going to
see a lot more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
