<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7234 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTI-AGING-AZR &LR;      12-26 2081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-AGING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-AGING REVOLUTION GOES FAR BEYOND FACE LIFTS, VITAMINS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would it mean to the world, to our lives, to politics,
economics, culture, if growing old as we know it becomes a thing of
the past?
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if an elixir were discovered that, when
injected into the heart, the brain, the liver, the kid neys, would
rebuild old tissue with new cells?
</P>
<P>
   And what if such an elixir were to become plentiful long before
we were really ready for it _ before we under stood how to shift
the world from a culture based on limited life spans to one based
on extended lives?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that era is at hand. Over the next 20 years, new
elixirs are likely to revolutionize medicine and aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impossible is possible,'' said Richard Sprott, former head
of the Biology of Aging section of the National Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is a breakthrough announced last month. Researchers
in Wisconsin and Maryland said they have grown embryonic stem cells
that can form any of the 210 kinds of cells in the human body.
</P>
<P>
   Such cells are derived from the all-purpose tissue of very early
human embryos. The expectation is that when they are injected into
an aging or diseased organ, they will rejuvenate the tissue by
forming more new cells.
</P>
<P>
   New heart muscle, for example, could be generated with an
injection instead of a heart transplant. Subse quent injections
could keep the organ youthful. Eventually, scientists say, the
method could be used on and under the skin so that, for your 50th
high school reunion, you still look a lot like your graduation
photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Within the next five years, scien tists will be injecting
embryonic cells into animals to see if they renew heart muscles and
tissues of other organs. If science progresses at its current pace,
that therapy could be cheap and plentiful in about 15 years,
predicts Dr. Thomas Okarma, vice president of Geron Corp. in Menlo
Park, Calif., which is responsible for research that could affect
age-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The company says its cell immor talization technology could
supply ``an unlimited number of young cells and tissues for every
organ in the body.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Such scientific breakthroughs are part of a multibillion-dollar
race for the future of medicine being played out in private labs
around the world. Serious scientists are talking about cures for
cancer, controlling Alzhei mer's disease and advancing major
assaults on the processes of aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists are pepped up as I have never seen them,'' said
Arthur Caplan, director of the Center for Bioethics at the
University of Penn sylvania. ``They are somewhere between gaga and
drooling over the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic interviewed scientists, ethicists and
experts in volved in aging research, asking 10 questions aimed at
finding when the breakthroughs may affect our lives. At the very
least, they said, more of us are headed for a world of extended
life spans, with the prom ise of better health and improved mental
powers well into our 80s, 90s, 100s and beyond. Some of today's
children may live to be 130.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists said the advances stand to affect our aging in
ways that go far beyond vitamins and face lifts:
</P>
<P>
   Within five years we will have the blueprint of the gene
structure of the human body. Out of that will come new medicines
and gene therapies, individually designed for each of us.
</P>
<P>
   Not in five years, but in 25 years, computer chips could be
implanted in people's brains to enhance mem ory, Caplan predicts.
By 2025, he sees the start of the first implant technology.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs also could enhance memory and fire up neurons in the
brain, Caplan said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look just to the most touted areas of research for ad
vances, said Dr. Michael Rose, a geneticist at the University of
Cali fornia-Irvine who has doubled the lives of fruit flies in his
laboratory through gene therapy. ``Expect the unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Many older people are already healthier, feeling and looking
younger than their parents were at the same age because of
lifestyle and medical advances of the past 30 years. But now,
instead of simply understanding the ailments of old age, more
research is directed toward mastering their root causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attention is turning toward slowing, postponing or preventing
aging,'' said Dan Perry, executive director of the National
Alliance of Aging Research in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthroughs are so aston ishing that many involved, afraid
to sound like quacks or stock promot ers, are downplaying the
implica tions of their work. Things are moving faster than anyone
antici pated, Sprott notes.
</P>
<P>
   When the Human Genome Proj ect _ mapping the structure of human
DNA _ started 10 years ago, some scientists predicted that it would
require 50 years to complete the analysis of all 3 billion chemical
pairs that lay down the blueprints for the human body. Supercomput
ers and billion-dollar machines ded icated to the project have
moved up the finish date to five years from now.
</P>
<P>
   In the near future, doctors will be able to review your genes
and mix drugs especially suited to your DNA. People could find out
at 25 whether they are candidates for osteoporosis and take the
necessary steps to ward it off.
</P>
<P>
   From Perry's point of view, sci ence can't move too fast. The
advances, for example, could help society cope with the aging of
the baby boom generation without breaking the bank, he said. By
2030, the bill for Alzheimer's dis ease could quadruple if means
aren't found to control it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still debating how to pay for nursing home services
based on the biology of today's 80-year-olds, and we're debating
whether to more quickly raise the eligible retirement age from 65
to 67, or to make wealthy individuals pay more for Medicare. That's
just rearranging the deck chairs on the Titanic,'' he said. ``We
should be doing every thing we can to enhance the mental and
physical vitality of older peo ple . . . to avoid some diseases in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate can shift into a new gear, people will have to
understand the wild possibilities of the new medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people see aging as miserable _ not much can be done,''
Caplan said. ``That's why Jack Kevorkian looks more attrac tive
than all the stem cell research. People don't realize what the bio
logical revolution holds in terms of better old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Many older and ill people, fol lowing the action on new medicine
via Web sites and health magazines, are hoping science will provide
miracles in time for them.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so happy about the progress, especially when it
seems to touch on the use of tissue from donated human embryos, or
where it seems to horn in on God's job description. The scientists
claim they are playing God no more than did the doctors who
introduced antibiotics and vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're figuring all this out with the brains God gave us,'' one
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Because anti-aging techniques have attracted quackery since the
first wrinkle appeared on the first human, many people doubt that
any real victory over aging is possible. Separating the real from
the balo ney, especially in media reports, is difficult. Members of
Congress, charged with regulating the outer limits of medical
research, don't know what to believe either.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government currently will not fund biomedical
research involving the use of fetal tissues, which are essential to
stem cell advances. Congress is expected to revisit the question of
fetal tissue bans this coming year or face the loss of major
research labs to overseas locations. As material iden tical to
fetal tissue can now be reproduced in laboratories, the ban may
soon become a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beginning to occur to some members of Congress that they
may have jumped too quickly in blocking this research material,''
Sprott said.
</P>
<P>
   Fetal stem cells could someday help treat everything from
strokes to brain diseases, the promise of which will be politically
irresistible, ac cording to Caplan.
</P>
<P>
   The demographic arrival of the baby boomers has shifted interest
and funds toward aging research. The budget for the federally
funded National Institute on Aging has gone from $1 million to $590
mil lion in 25 years. Over the next five years the budget of the
National Institutes of Health is expected to double.
</P>
<P>
   But not all scientists are joyful about the new medicine and its
potential effects on our lives.
</P>
<P>
   There will be new worries, says Dr. Frank Williams of Rochester,
N.Y., scientific director of the American Federation of Aging Re
search, which funds biomedical re search. A former director of the
National Institute on Aging, he worries that the chemicals we will
load into our bodies to fight aging might do damage elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed concern about the widespread use of genetic
test ing. ``The question is, how will it be used and what
precautions will there be? What guidelines?''
</P>
<P>
   And he wonders who will have access to the new advances. Most
agree that the rich get better care now, and that is likely to be
true in the future. But Williams believes it ultimately might be
simpler and cheaper to inject someone with new cells than to treat
the conditions of ``old-fashioned'' aging.
</P>
<P>
   The gold rush for breakthroughs may cause a leapfrog problem,
according to Williams. Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, cancer and heart
dis ease might be controlled, allowing people to live longer. But
if the accumulating annoyances of an ag ing body, such as bladder
control, vision, hearing and digestion are not addressed, people's
quality of life may not be high enough to allow productive and
enjoyable living even if a few extra years are added to their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting these smaller, non-fa tal problems may get lost in
the shuffle of privatized, profit-based research efforts, he fears.
They won't offer short-term returns on the stock market as some of
the bigger developments will.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan also worries that just as Alzheimer's didn't show up
until people started to live longer, other diseases hiding in our
genes may show themselves as we continue to lengthen the human life
span.
</P>
<P>
   The end of aging as we know it will create enormous social
disrup tions, predicted Michael Fossel, a medical doctor, professor
at Michi gan State University and editor of the Journal of
Anti-Aging Medicine who is finishing a new book on that subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are things going to change, but they are going to
change in unpredictable ways,'' he said. ``Right now we have a
clear idea of what our life is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But as life spans soon increase, many more people will have
second and third careers, and as many marriages. Retirement may
lose its meaning in a world of brain boost ing and muscle and bone
restora tion.
</P>
<P>
   Williams hopes the promises of better health and a longer life
span will be accompanied by creative ideas about what to do with
the extra time.
</P>
<P>
   The medical establishment could be turned on its head, Fossel
said. Medical specialties in the future could be limited to two:
trauma (the treatment of injuries) and genetics.
</P>
<P>
   While most scientists surveyed were optimistic about all the ad
vances, Rose, of UC-Irvine, said progress will be slow,
particularly because of problems in the biotech marketplace and
with government regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither sector really cares about anti-aging, only dollars and
votes. But progress will occur because too many people want
anti-aging therapies and too much progress is being made,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The unanswerable question is: At what rate? said Dr. Leonard Hay
flick, who did landmark work on the cell 35 years ago. Only
recently have scientists built on his work, he points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Projecting back in time is a good way of projecting what the
future will be like,'' he said. ``In 1970 we thought we knew it
all, and now we look back and realize how little we knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back further in time: At the beginning of the 20th
century, air travel, television, radio and antibiotics were
unknown. They all came within the first decades of the century in
an avalanche of change.
</P>
<P>
   Leading scientists say another avalanche of change is under way,
opening the new century with a wholly new kind of medicine for an
aging world. &QL; 
 &UR; Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167 or Maureen.West &LR; pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
