<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-AGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-AGING CONVENTION BIG ON HYPE, SHORT ON RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ America's bio-medical community is closing in at a
feverish pace on the secrets of aging and disease. If its
methodical and well-funded approach looks like a NASA moon shot, be
advised that there are also others _ a Wild West fringe group of
anti-aging treatment promoters _ whose Las Vegas gathering earlier
this month at moments looked more like a Star Trek convention than
serious science.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Anti-Aging Medicine's annual program
drew 3,000 doctors, scientists and customers from around the world.
It was a free-for-all for the wilder thinkers and promoters of
anti-aging's robust frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the presentations and exhibits were credible and
professional in tone. Some left you speechless with their daring
claims and high prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider them the creative, right brain scientists,'' said
Doe Gentry, a sleek 58-year-old television personality from Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Elegant in black, with her blonde hair pulled back from a
glowing face, she is a walking advertisement for successful aging.
She cruised the convention in search of topics for her cable
television show, ``Single in LA,'' where she offers advice on
anti-aging to a potential audience of 4 million single Southern
Californians. &QL; 
`LOT OF HYPE HERE'
</P>
<P>
   She was a believer, though she rolled her eyes at some of the
pitches. One firm offering the latest embryonic stem cell
injections offshore for the modest fee of $10,000 to $25,000 made
her wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my doubts about that one,'' she said. ``How would you
ever know what you were really getting?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hype here,'' she said, adding that some
comment that money, not science, is a driving force behind the
show. Compared with last year, the number of new brain supplements
are the big new thing, she said. She thinks there are benefits to
be derived from some of the hormonal products, however.
</P>
<P>
   Many university and institute scientists avoid the meeting for
fear of being linked with ``the Las Vegas crowd.'' As it is, the
field offers any scientist enough opportunities to be branded as a
quack. The more sober scientists criticize the frontier folks for
having ``boundless enthusiasm tempered by a little research.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A word like ``immortality,'' rarely appearing in ``Science,
Nature'' or the ``Journal of the American Medical Association,'' is
frequently heard at the Vegas conference. &QL; 
TIME IS THE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   The Vegas participants, in turn, criticize mainstream science as
taking too much time to give the public the fruits of available
research. One current line in the sand between the two groups is
drawn over the use of human growth hormone: The American Academy of
Anti-Aging Medicine (sponsors of the Las Vegas conference) is
accrediting a new medical specialty _ anti-aging medicine, which
relies heavily on prescribing human growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
   Their proof that it works is largely based on a 1990 research
study by the late Daniel Rudman of the University of Wisconsin. He
reported that growth hormone injections over six months reversed
aging in a group of older men.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want more solid evidence, a 30-year study is under
way. That difference in caution vs. impatience is the primary
difference between traditional researchers and the anti-aging
wildcatters.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most baby boomers and older folks agree that waiting
30 years for an anti-aging miracle drug isn't any fun. If it seems
to work, let's get some and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular speakers in Las Vegas was Dr. Eugene
Shippen, author of ``The Testosterone Syndrome, ''which links the
maintenance of testosterone levels in men with the preservation of
youthful vitality and health. He was surrounded by men with
hundreds of questions for two hours following his talk. &QL; 
CLONING, FREEZING
</P>
<P>
   Keynote speaker Dr. Richard Seed of Chicago told the group that
human clones will ``be on the ground in two years _ two and a half,
tops,'' and he thinks they will be the key to the quest for
rejuvenation. As he spoke, a middle-aged woman in a miniskirt
hooted and howled approval, as if the 60-something Seed were Mick
Jagger at a rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   On the same panel was Fred Chamberlain of Scottsdale, president
of Alcor, a leader in the cryo-suspension technology. Alcor has 35
frozen heads or bodies in its high-tech fridges, and is considering
establishing a DNA archive, where a person could the blueprints for
future cloning.
</P>
<P>
   When Alcor started its business a decade ago, the possible
outcomes for a frozen head or body were uncertain at best. Science
seems to be catching up with the idea that something can be done
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Although most university scientists are notoriously tight-lipped
about their research until it has been tested and peer reviewed,
some Las Vegas exhibitors and conference goers routinely claim the
blue sky, giving the event a state fair atmosphere. Step right up,
ladies and gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Researchers in electro-medicine have not just treated but
CURED 1,000 people of AIDS _ for $5 each. But that news is being
stifled because big drug companies are making $100,000 per patient
now. But we can't just sit on these things while people are dying .
. .'' So goes a not too unusual claim by one conference goer.
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal stories of cancer patients who have been cured by this
or that product fall like snowflakes through the exhibit halls.
</P>
<P>
   For sale at the conference: A headband for $99 that gets rid of
depression and insomnia; a device that massages away your double
chin; a home oxidation kit to measure your oxidated stress level; a
gun-shaped home acupuncture kit for $129; your own oxygen chamber
for home or office. &QL; 
KEEPING AN OPEN MIND
</P>
<P>
   Among the skeptical but earnest shoppers was 42-year-old Thomas
Grauer of Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my present age, and I want to stay here,'' &UR; said Grauer,
a private investigator. At the booths he was putting his
professional skills to use, asking each vendor questions and
gathering information to take home and do follow-up research on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   You have to have an open mind about all of this, he said, adding
that he had found good information among the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to age well has to take it in their own
hands,'' he advised.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying all the sessions and exhibits at the American Academy
of Anti-Aging Medicine is ``time''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to die young, very late in life _ I think that is what
we are all searching for here,'' said Dr. Tom Allen of Oklahoma
State University, one of the more moderate voices on the program.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the attendees that knowledge about medical advances
doubles every 3{ years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be great if our wisdom did as much?'' he asked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
