<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA ANITA OPENS WITH BIG CROWD, BIG UPSETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ At least for one day, not all of the surprises at
Santa Anita Park came from Frank Stronach.
</P>
<P>
   The track opened its first season under Stronach's ambitious
ownership with an afternoon of upsets Saturday, including a Malibu
Stakes victory by New York's Run Man Run and jockey Mike Luzzi,
confounding the big crowd of 42,348.
</P>
<P>
   Run Man Run emerged from a four-way duel for the early lead and
won the 7-furlong race by 2{ lengths over Artax as unbeaten Event
of the Year finished two lengths back in third. Sea of Secrets
(fifth) and Old Topper (sixth) were the other stars in a 10-horse
field of 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year was favored in his first start since a knee
fracture kept him out of the Kentucky Derby, and after sweating
nervously on his way to the gate, he ran well to be beaten only by
fitter horses.
</P>
<P>
   Run Man Run (who paid $29.20) came out of a Nov.26 allowance
victory at Aqueduct. The son of Theatrical is only the second Grade
I stakes winner for trainer Anthony Margotta Jr. (who won the 1993
Whitney with Brunswick).
</P>
<P>
   ``The race went a little bit different than planned,'' said
Luzzi, who'd planned to drop in behind the front-runners after
starting from an outside gate. ``But that's what we're out there
for, to improvise, and I had to improvise a little bit down the
backstretch. He broke so sharp, I just threw our plans right out
the window.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Santa Anita victory for the New York-based
Luzzi _ on a day filled with firsts.
</P>
<P>
   Both maiden winners on the nine-race card were first-time
starters: Sasha's Prospect ($6.60) and Cape Canaveral ($12.80), D.
Wayne Lukas-trained sons of Mr. Prospector.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three turf-course winners were making their first
U.S. starts: French-bred Special Quest ($3.80) for trainer Richard
Mandella and Irish-bred Aliena ($11.80) for Ron McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   Special Quest was the only winning favorite. The day began with
BJ Ballet, the first of jockey Alex Solis' three victories, going
wire to wire at $20.20. It ended with Half Past Ten coming from off
the pace under Octavio Vergara to win at $54. And in the middle,
Mountain Bike and Laffit Pincay sprang a $34 surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The result might be that much of the crowd, the largest in four
years for a Santa Anita opener, will be back today to chase a
$212,430 carryover in the pick-six.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-day meet continues today when stakes winners Brulay, with
Corey Nakatani riding, and Magical Allure, with Gary Stevens, meet
for the first time in the La Brea, the fillies' equivalent of the
Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   On the 12:30 p.m. card, 1996 Santa Anita Derby winner
Cavonnier's on-again, off-again comeback from a tendon injury is
finally ``on.'' The 5-year-old from Bob Baffert's barn is entered
in a mile stakes called the Ack Ack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 2136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTS-AZR &LR;      12-26 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASING YOUR YOUTH ISN'T CHEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a kid I hated report cards. Now, several decades later, I
still felt nervous as Dr. Charlene DeHaven held my test results and
got a funny look on her face. I knew I was in for it.
</P>
<P>
   While my birth certificate and driver's license say I'm 46, my
anti-aging report card, based on a battery of tests comparing my
reactions and biological conditions with those of about 2,500 other
American office workers, said I should really be putting 52 candles
on my cake. Thank you, Doc. Thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the point of doing all this _ finding my ``biological
age'' _ is to bring that number down. That is what DeHaven does for
a living.
</P>
<P>
   Her anti-aging medical practice in west Phoenix, soon moving to
an upscale Biltmore office, specializes in tests that estimate each
patient's biological age. She then uses that bench mark as a basis
for prescribing nutritional changes, lifestyle changes, vitamin and
hormone supplements and, coming someday, gene therapies. The goal
is to help people regain and retain their prime, and to provide
ongoing monitoring and cheerleading. &QL; 
GET OUT THE WALLET
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like just what you need, get out your wallet _ it's
almost as expensive as having someone work on your car. The battery
of tests and consultations she gives costs about $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   After that, monthly products and services can cost from $100 per
month to $800 or more. Prescribed hormone replacement therapy,
including human growth hormones, is a key ingredient in most
anti-aging clinical programs, including DeHaven's.
</P>
<P>
   The tests include a long interview about personal habits,
examining of blood and urine samples, a physical exam testing
reflexes, hearing and vision, and a battery of mental reaction
tests. That latter area is where I got old; I have never been one
for remembering which playing card was where.
</P>
<P>
   I was born at the leading edge of the baby boom _ the
youth-is-everything generation that is expected to descend on
clinics to try to hang on, by fingernails if necessary, to that
all-important youth. People in their 40s and 50s are the main
market for anti-aging clinics. The next biggest group are those in
their 60s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who see me in general are focused on their health,''
DeHaven said. ``Others see themselves slipping and want to do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   I was, of course, not among the vain; I was just doing research.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in a long morning I was hooked up to a ``Bride of
Frankenstein'' electrical device that measured my body fat. The
fat-o-meter jumped to 20 percent, in the ``almost fabulous'' range.
Good machine.
</P>
<P>
   The whole deal required three visits, not including quarterly
follow-up appointments, which I did not sign up for because I am
not rich enough to stay that young. Note: Your health insurance
voice mail computer will laugh if you call to see if these tests
are covered. And when gene therapies come on the market that some
believe could really roll back aging, the only way to afford them
may be to own an anti-aging clinic yourself.
</P>
<P>
   DeHaven and the other physicians now opening such clinics are
not your average family doctors. They are the advance guard of an
emerging specialty accredited by the American Academy of Anti-Aging
Medicine. Along with more than 100 other doctors, DeHaven took
extensive certification tests at the academy's annual conference in
Las Vegas this month. It is not a specialty approved by the
American Medical Association, though many of the practitioners,
including DeHaven, are medical doctors and have specialties in
other areas. She is certified in internal medicine and emergency
medicine. &QL; 
WHAT TO EXPECT
</P>
<P>
   If you go in for the clinic experience, here's what to expect.
In addition to a family health history grilling, the physical exam
and the letting of various fluids, there are 12 tests that include
pushing a button when a zero turns to an eight, pushing a button
when a box stops vibrating, pushing a button when a tiny sound
stops, remembering a sequence of lights, that sort of thing. I was
horrible at it, and will try to be better about taking my vitamins
if I can please not have to do it again for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people enjoy the tests _ they find them fun,'' DeHaven
said.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe they weren't stressed out by their results that came
up instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 computerized tests, I only scored better than 50
percent, the average, &UR; on three.
</P>
<P>
   I did best in two tests where I blew into a tube and my lung
capacity and velocity were measured immediately. &QL; 
GETTING THE RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   My final appointment was two weeks later, and it was then that
DeHaven gave me the results of the blood and urine tests and
offered some medical advice on how to improve my longevity.
</P>
<P>
   This time the news was better. My risk factor for cardiovascular
disease _ or heart attacks and strokes _ was low based on blood
tests that measured levels of fats and antioxidants. I also had
great levels of growth hormone, folic acid and testosterone . . .
hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find a lot of career women have high levels of
testosterone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Had I continued with the program, based on the results of my
tests, DeHaven said she would have designed a special vitamin
regime for me costing about $50 to $150 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people spend that much on vitamins now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Your co-workers, if they hear that you have been going to an
anti-aging clinic, will talk among themselves and wonder if you
don't look a lot younger, even if you have only been filling out
questionnaires and pushing buttons on things that buzz. Their
reactions are the fun part. Worth every penny. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
