r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-FUTURE-AZ     12-26 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-FUTURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT NEXT FOR THE LOCKOUT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The NBA and its players have taken their labor war
into its final weeks. Commissioner David Stern has labeled Jan. 7
as the league's ``drop-dead'' date, the point of no return if the
season is to be saved.
</P>
<P>
   But already, considerable damage has been done. Most fans are
apethetic about the league, as evidenced by an ``Arizona Republic''
reader poll last week. Only three percent of respondents said the
end of a lockout would be a great sports Christmas gift.
</P>
<P>
   If the season is saved, there will be questions about its
legitimacy. It will be an abbreviated schedule. And if it is lost,
it would give the NBA the unenviable honor of being the first
professional league to lose an entire season to a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long fall from last summer, when Michael Jordan hit the
final shot of the season to win Game 6 and eliminate Utah from The
NBA Finals, putting the finishing touch on Chicago's sixth NBA
championship of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   There were many who wondered whether Jordan's shot would mark
the end of his career. Few would have believed that with Jordan's
final follow through he might also be waving goodbye to the NBA as
we have known it. At that point, the NBA had never even lost a game
to labor problems, much less a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has been some damage,'' said Suns Coach Danny
Ainge. ``Obviously. How much has to be determined by the quality of
play, the character of our players when we do come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization, the players, everybody has to be on their
best behavior and build it back up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns President Jerry Colangelo, as a member of the NBA Labor
Committee and an active participant in negotiations, was reluctant
to discuss the lockout or its ramifications with the deadline
drawing near.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I say right now isn't going to help,'' Colangelo
said. ``It's either going to happen, or it's not. This is
Armegeddon.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue is how to divide up annual revenues
approaching $2 billion now, and expected to grow in the coming
years with new television contracts the league signed with Turner
Sports and NBC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But sports fans, jaded by past strikes and lockouts in the NFL,
NHL and especially Major League baseball, apparently just aren't
interested. It won't be easy to win them back, as baseball learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with it every day,'' said Houston's Mario Elie. ``Fans
asking me when we're going to have basketball. I have to answer
those questions every day. It's tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to win the fans back. That's part of the
job. You just have to try and do some extra things, like hold some
free clinics. You have to do something to try to give back to the
fans. Once football is over, there's going to be nothing on TV, and
the fans are really going to be mad then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, I'm starting to watch rodeo and crap like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge said the fans do care. They're just frustrated, like
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the perception is out there,'' Ainge said. ``But
I've had a lot of people tell me they really miss the Suns. During
the fall with college football, pro football and then college
basketball all going on, it's easy to be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of issues still must be addressed, even if the owners
and players can work out their differences in the 11th hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If there is a season, how will it be structured?
</P>
<P>
   League sources indicate that the NBA has worked out a shortened
schedule. If the season began in the first week of February, teams
could play as many as nine games every two weeks. With that kind of
schedule, it would be possible to play a season of about 56 games.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, teams never play more than two nights in a row. They'll
have to play three nights in a row to make the scheduling work.
</P>
<P>
   And most, if not all games, will be played against conference
opponents. The Suns, for instance, might not play any Eastern
Conference teams such as the Bulls. The NHL did the same thing in
1994 during its shortened season. It provides an opportunity to
determine a truer conference championship, and then the NBA Finals
would pit the best of the East against the best of the West, as
usual. However, it could be their first meetings of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team will not be able to face each other on a
home-and-away basis,'' said Deputy NBA Commissioner Russ Granik.
``You'd see more of a conference-type schedule with some mixing of
intra-conference games, but no team is going to see every other
team at home. That's going to be virtually impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What about the next draft?
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the draft order is determined by how well a team
performed during the season. The top 16 teams reach the playoffs,
and the rest are included in a in a weighted lottery to determine
the order. The worst teams get the most chances in the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the draft is ordered according to record _ the team
with the best record picks last.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no season, there is no order of finish from which to
determine the order. And even if there is a season, if teams aren't
playing against every other league team, is the season enough to
determine a draft order?
</P>
<P>
   The league could hold a full lottery, and weight it according to
how teams have done over the past three or four seasons. Or it
could simply rank the teams according to their winning percentage
over several years. If the season isn't cancelled, a combination
might be used _ the team's record in the shortened season and it's
winning percentage over the past two or three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What can players do if the season is cancelled?
 &UR; Will those who were to be in the final years of their contract
become
 &UR; free agents?
</P>
<P>
   A number of NBA players have been approached by European clubs,
and agent James Bryant of Houston has filed a lawsuit to free up
players to sign with those clubs without restriction.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why the NBA announced a drop-dead date of Jan. 7.
Those European teams must, unless the governing body of
international basketball _ FIBA - provides an extension, have their
rosters complete by Jan. 5 for players to be eligible for the
European Championships tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency may be a bigger sticking point. This year, there are
about 200 free agent players. That number would go above 300 _
around three quarters of the league _ if the season is cancelled
and players who would have been free agents at the end of the
season are granted that status.
</P>
<P>
   It could lead to a court battle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is it all worth it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about disastrous repercussions for everybody _
the players, the owners, the league,'' said Carl Scheer, a former
executive with the Charlotte Hornets, Los Angeles Clippers and
Denver Nuggets in an interview with the ``Charlotte Observer.''
``It took baseball four years, plus an extraordinary season from
(Mark) McGwire and (Sammy) Sosa to recover from the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the so-called national pastime, and we don't even know
if baseball's recovery will be sustained. Basketball is popular,
but it has nothing like baseball's history and tradition. So you'd
have to assume it would take at leave five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheer said owners may have determined that it's worth risking a
season to roll back salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on what they end up with, what deal is made,
after the season is canceled,'' he said. ``If you stabilize your
costs on a long-term basis, if the tail stops wagging the dog, then
maybe it is (worth cancelling the season).
</P>
<P>
   ``But remember, it's not just money they're figting over. It's
the power. It's the side issues, like behavior and image. It's
ridiculous, for instance, that marijuana isn't already part of the
drug policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo has said the character issues are his greatest
priority in this round of collective bargaining negotiations. The
incident in which Latrell Sprewell allegedly choked Golden State
Coach P.J. Carlesimo was a galvanizing force for the owners.
</P>
<P>
   But already the owners have gotten considerable concessions from
the players, and whatever deal is made is likely to turn the clock
back somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this deal, they want to set the standard for deals in the
future,'' said Spurs guard Avery Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that the NBA may be making a stand for all
professional sports leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In the NHL, for example, Commissioner Gary Bettman _ who was
weened in the NBA _ reportedly is beginning to ammass a $300
million ``Labor Dispute Fund.'' And that league's collective
bargaining agreement does not expire until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   What the NBA is doing may be the wave of the future in
professional sports as owners try to stop salaries from spiraling
upward, and players attempt to retain their freedom to earn what
the market will bear.
</P>
<P>
   And ultimately, they may all pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is damage,'' Ainge said. ``I just hope it's not
irrepairable damage.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
