<HEADLINE>
IS DETROIT DYNASTY BEGINNING TO CRUMBLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In other sports, they call it a ``threepeat'' when a team wins
three straight championships.
</P>
<P>
   In hockey, they should call it a natural hat trick. That's what
the Detroit Red Wings are shooting for this season, a feat that
hasn't been accomplished since the New York Islanders won four
consecutive Cups from 1980 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, there are concerns in Hockeytown that the
``dynasty'' is showing signs of crumbling. It's early, of course,
but some of the worries are legitimate when considering the recent
slide by Detroit, which had lost four in a row for only the second
time since Coach Scotty Bowman's first season in 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than that, is Detroit's record against teams above .500.
The Red Wings haven't been able to beat anyone with a winning
record. Panic is starting to set in and sources close to the team
said General Manager Ken Holland is contemplating making a major
trade to jump-start the club.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the most intriguing story to follow in the NHL
during the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to be patient and hope in time things turn
around,'' Holland said, ``but certainly we're disappointed in our
play against top teams. ... It's still the regular season, but you
can't just all of a sudden turn it on come April 1 and find your
`A' game. You need to get it going at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   What's been the problem? You name it, Detroit's got it,
according to captain Steve Yzerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing ``anything'' exceptionally well,'' he said.
``You need more than 10 fingers to cover it. We're sruggling in all
areas right now.''
</P>
<P>
   They're giving up a ton of soft goals, No. 1. Part of that
problem stems from the fact the defensemen aren't clearing out the
front of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals we're giving up,'' left wing Brendadn Shanahan said,
``are atrocious. Just gifts. Giveaways. It's been far too easy for
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bad sign when you lose four in a row twice already in
the beginn
</P>
</TEXT>
