<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME AND FISH SHOULD SPEND WISELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - OK, so you're the Arizona Game and Fish Department,
and you have this money from the Heritage Fund, a piece of Arizona
lottery profits, and you must spend the $10 million a year or so to
help non-game species.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of land do you look for to do the most for the buck?
If you buy it, it better be good. If you lease it, you have to get
some perks.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the department didn't seem to know what to do. So it
hired more people to help manage non-game species.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, played right into the hands of critics.
Bureaucracy at its worse, they said. You hire people but create no
new resources. It's an attempt to perpetuate your agency. People
don't create wildlife, habitat does. For crying out loud, you're
biologists, you should know that.
</P>
<P>
   But the department grew in its understanding. Time also was
needed to present opportunities. You don't go out blind and buy
land to preserve wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Before you leap into an abyss, you must weigh important factors.
The Norvelle Decree, an enabling law established by Congress when
Arizona was made a state, sets up water rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to change those rights. And agricultural and
livestock interests were considered first. Industry wasn't an
issue. Neither was drinking water for the thundering herd of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, farmers draw huge quantities of irrigation water
from the Gila River and others when reservoirs such as San Carlos
are in peril of drying. These farmers own the water. They aren't
sneaking around to get it, the decree dictates that. Recreational
interests weren't an issue. And recreation might bring more money
to Arizona than agriculture and ranching. Some studies say it does.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress. Let's get back to purchasing land for wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish has to look at some major factors in purchasing
land. First, it has to come with water rights. That water can be
used locally or traded and used in other areas. It has to look at
riparian areas, where most wildlife, at least at some time in its
life, must have to thrive. It has to consider non-game or
endangered species, but if the land will support other wildlife,
that's even better. If it provides more recreation, the
desirability goes up more.
</P>
<P>
   The department's major purchases have been made in the White
Mountains. There are endangered fishes that must be protected
because the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is threatening to drop
the hammer if they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   And elk are a major controversy among ranchers as elk numbers
grow. The ranchers' major problem seems to be the winter range of
elk when they come down into lower, private land and eat the grub.
Buy good, private areas, and the problem can be solved.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's the deal: The Arizona Game and Fish Commission, at
its last meeting, authorized the department to buy 80 acres of land
in Cochise County. The land is irrigated and has water rights.
</P>
<P>
   This particular land has nothing to do with endangered species
or elk. This land will be purchased to enhance waterfowl and
aquatic bird habitat in the Whitewater Draw Wildlife Area near
Willcox. It also would help create sandhill crane habitat and help
the Chiricahua leopard frog.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, $80,000 to pay for this will come from the Waterfowl
Conservation Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same meeting, commissioners gave permission for the
department to negotiate for the Ocote and Cross L ranches in the
White Mountains near Springerville.
</P>
<P>
   The ranches are adjacent to each other and about four miles west
of Springerville. Ocote includes more than 1,000 acres of private
land and almost 4,000 acres of state land. It owns 50 percent of
the water storage rights to Carnero, Wiltbank, Norton and Sunnyside
reservoirs plus irrigation rights to 269 acres of land.
</P>
<P>
   Cross L includes about 1,635 acres of deeded land, 4,200 acres
of state land and 28,544 acres of leased land from
Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest. It owns about 28.5 percent of
the water storage rights in Carnero, 22.5 percent in Wilbank, 22.5
percent in Norton and 22.5 in Sunnyside. It also has water rights
to irrigate 160 acres of land.
</P>
<P>
   The property offers everything from winter elk grazing to
protection of the endangered Colorado River spindace. It also
offers an opportunity to create more cold-water trout fisheries in
the reservoirs. Additionally, it offers more habitat for Arizona's
dwindling antelope populations.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of funds could be used to purchase the ranches.
</P>
<P>
   These purchases have real possibilities. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
