<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CHARGERS-AZ     12-26 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CHARGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING FOR THE STARS: CARDINALS PLAY FOR PLAYOFF BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - This isn't about stadium building or ghost
busting.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about fence mending or score settling.
</P>
<P>
   A win today by the Cardinals that would put them into the
playoffs _ and that's what it really is about _ could have
ramifications for the players, the franchise and the community far
beyond playing in a 17th game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (8-7) have sprouted wings this week. They've
captured the imagination, if not the heart, of the community.
Finally. When they run onto the field at Sun Devil Stadium for the
2 p.m. game with San Diego (5-10), the Cardinals won't be hit by
the accustomed glare of sunlight reflecting off empty aluminum
seats. The stadium will be full of people wearing red.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have yet to play to a sellout that is ``their
crowd.'' Always when there has been a packed house a significant
portion contained Dallas fans, or transplanted fans of a rust-belt
team such as Chicago, Minnesota or Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley is not a hotbed of transplanted Chargers fans.
</P>
<P>
   Entering to the roar of a sellout crowd pulling ``for'' the home
team has been Vince Tobin's vision since he was hired in 1996 to
coach the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a dream of mine come true,'' Tobin said. ``This
is what the NFL is all about, having cheering fans there to support
your team and try to get you over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything at this point. Everybody is assuming
we've done something. All we've done is put ourselves into position
to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   A win not only would give the team its first playoff berth since
the strike-shortened 1982 season, it would give the Cardinals their
best record since moving here. That and having second-year
quarterback Jake Plummer under contract for four more years might
carry weight at the polls in May when voters in Mesa, Gilbert and
Queen Creek decide whether to help fund the Rio Salado Crossing,
which would include a retractable-roof stadium viewed as vital to
the long-term future of the team in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A winning record and a playoff berth wouldn't totally erase
scorn and skepticism that has accumulated over a decade, but it
would be a start.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have acknowledged that they haven't done the best
job _ on or off the field _ of making people want to be a Cardinals
fan. They've worked furiously over the past 18 months, largely
under the direction of Michael Bidwill, the team vice president, to
repair public relations. They went out of their way this week to
make tickets available at numerous locations, even on Christmas
day, and to try to get the sellout in time to lift the local
television blackout.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who continue to bash the organization of everyone
from owner Bill Bidwill on down, this is the Cardinals' chance to
quiet them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to look back years from now and say, `Here's where
it happened' or `Here's how it happened,' '' Bidwill said. ``But
there is a great deal of enthusiasm, the team is playing well, and
we're in the chase down to our final game. `Over the hump,' that's
a good expression but what we really have to do is get to a level
of competence and consistency. We're getting there. We have to
prove it in this game. In reality, it's win-or-go-home time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to get into the playoffs. A sellout is
a plus where the vast majority of the people there are Cardinals
fans. That means a lot to the players. After all, it still is an
emotional game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too emotional, Tobin hopes. He knows his players will be
pumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to play within the framework of our offense,
defense and special-teams structure,'' Tobin said. ``The thing you
always worry about in big games is that somebody is going to try to
do something outside of what their responsibility is and
consequently hurt you.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how important and how big a game might be, it's
still 11 people playing together doing their responsibility. I
certainly will remind them of that. It's not 11 individuals, it's a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge is the Chargers defense that is stingiest
in the NFL overall and against the rush. Led by Pro Bowl linebacker
Junior Seau, the Chargers have not surrendered a 100-yard afternoon
to an opposing back all season. The Chargers also rank eighth in
the NFL against the pass.
</P>
<P>
   While Plummer and the offense have moved well lately, reaching
400 total yards in four of the past six games, they have bogged
down after getting into striking distance, often watching a long
drive end with a turnover, or with a field goal rather than a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The offense's newfound ability to control the ball coincides
with widespread injuries that weakened the defense. Ball control
won't come as easily today. The Cardinals will need more from their
defense, which will have Ron McKinnon back at middle linebacker. He
missed three games because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me and the guys around me we're excited to face the best
defense,'' Plummer said. ``They're a ferocious group. They play
non-stop. They're great at stopping the run with Seau. He's the
catalyst of the whole thing. I think we can get some passing done
but that's tough, too, because they cover well. They're not going
to give us a lot so we have to be patient and careful with the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our defense will be ready to go full force and shut
them down because offensively we are going to have a challenge
ourselves. Defense is going to be key for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau said the Chargers are as motivated to knock the Cardinals
out of the playoffs ``as they are to knock our defense out of our
Number 1 ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yardage-wise, in the last quarter of the season, they're
probably the Number 1 offense out there,'' Seau said of the
Cardinals. ``They have a running game that went 100 yards-plus last
week, a passing game that went 300-some yards. That's something you
normally don't have against a defensive squad that's in the
professional ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, although in only his second season, seemed to speak for
those who've been around longer and suffered through many of those
dark years with a franchise that was neither successful nor
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be huge to win this one and get to the playoffs,
especially with a team that hasn't been there and has the longest
streak in the NFL,'' Plummer said. ``From the day I got drafted, I
set out to do that, to be part of a rebuilding of the whole
franchise to where getting to the playoffs is a yearly thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year (4-12) was tough playing football. Now we're
enjoying coming out here. Winning cures a lot out here. Even if
you're sore, you want to come to practice. It's fun out here. Our
success has come at a good time. We're ready for it. Guys who are
vets and have been here a long time are ready for it. We've just
got to go get it done. Win and we're in a great spot for this
franchise and these players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
