</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN LOVED SF, BUT WOULD HE RETURN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five victories in 33 games might not be enough to save
San Francisco Coach  &UR; Steve Mariucci's job.
</P>
<P>
   You can blame the Green Bay Packers for that.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, who have beaten the 49ers five straight times,
could eliminate them in the NFC playoffs for the fourth consecutive
year by winning next week's NFC wild-card game between the two
teams.
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers lose, they could fire Mariucci, who has three years
left on a contract that pays him $800,000 a year, and then make a
run at Packers Coach  &UR; Mike Holmgren, former offensive coordinator
of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren will have plenty of other options. Carolina plans to go
all out to try to hire him to replace  &UR; Dom Capers, who is expected
to be fired Monday. They'll give him the title of general
manager/coach and almost complete control.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also could make a run at Holmgren if the Redskins
fire Coach  &UR; Norv Turner, who might have saved his job by beating
every team except the Cardinals in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers aren't out of the picture, even though General
Manager  &UR; Ron Wolf repeated this week that he thinks there is only a
20 percent chance that Holmgren will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 20 percent because of the financial opportunities he'll
receive,'' Wolf said. ``But it's incumbent upon me to make sure he
never leaves the Green Bay Packers. I will do everything in my
power to make sure he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Packers already have offered Holmgren a multiyear contract
extension that averages over $3 million per year. It would make him
the highest-paid coach in the league. Denver's  &UR; Mike Shanahan and
the New York Jets' Bill Parcells currently are the highest paid at
about $2.4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Mike will stay in Green Bay unless there is
something of a phenomenal nature that is put in front of him,'' his
agent,  &UR; Bob LaMonte, said. ``It would take a truly wonderful offer.
It won't be just to become a general manager somewhere. He is very
happy in Green Bay. His heart is in Green Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's heart was in his hometown of San Francisco, where his
former boss,  &UR; Bill Walsh, is expected to return to run the team
once owner  &UR; Eddie DeBartolo is back in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's presence wouldn't keep Holmgren from getting the control
he seeks. But he didn't like the way the 49ers pushed former Coach
 &UR; George Seifert out the door, and he could be leery of the way
Mariucci, Holmgren's former assistant with the Packers, is getting
treated.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are the ones that initiated a contract extension for
Mariucci. Now, they're the ones who might pull it off the table. &QL; 
Bloody Monday
</P>
<P>
   The following coaches likely will get axed Monday _ Carolina's
Capers, Philadelphia's  &UR; Ray Rhodes, Seattle's  &UR; Dennis Erickson and
Baltimore's  &UR; Ted Marchibroda.
</P>
<P>
   Still up in the air is the status of Chicago's  &UR; Dave Wannstedt
and Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Interim San Diego Coach  &UR; June Jones will take over duties at the
University of Hawaii after today's game against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The job at expansion Cleveland remains open, but Denver
offensive coordinator  &UR; Gary Kubiak appears to be the top choice
there.
</P>
<P>
   If Carolina officials can't get Holmgren, they'll go after
Seifert, who appears to be the No. 1 candidate in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's top choices are Pittsburgh offensive coordinator
 &UR; Jim Haslett and Jacksonville offensive coordinator  &UR; Chris Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens owner  &UR; Art Modell also likes Seifert and wants to talk to
UCLA's  &UR; Bob Toledo, who is expected to stay with the Bruins. A dark
horse for the Baltimore job could be Capers.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego will consider Minnesota offensive coordinator  &UR; Brian
 &UR; Billick, Stanford Coach  &UR; Tyrone Willingham and former UCLA Coach
 &UR; Terry
 &UR; Donahue.
</P>
<P>
   An 0-7 start was thought to have doomed Turner. But the team has
rallied, and the uncertainty of the ownership situation might play
in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   Bears owner  &UR; Mike McCaskey hasn't made up his mind whether to
retain Wannstedt, who hasn't had a winning season since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt didn't help his popularity in Chicago when he referred
to running back  &UR; James Allen, who rushed for 163 yards against
Baltimore last week, as  &UR; Tremayne Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Tremayne Allen is a tight end on the Bears' practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Changing his story
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the 49ers noticed the $29.7 million deal the Cardinals
gave
 &UR; Jake Plummer last week because he could have been playing in the
Bay area instead of the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dwight Clark, the former 49ers executive who bypassed Plummer
in the 1997 first round to take Virginia Tech quarterback  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Druckenmiller, has been under siege over the move.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, now with the expansion Browns, said the 49ers had
questions about Plummer's ability to read defenses. He also
questioned reports that Walsh, who was a consultant, had
recommended the team draft Plummer instead of Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it a long time,'' Clark said. ``Whether Bill
Walsh wants to admit it or not, he thought Druckenmiller had more
ability than anybody in the draft. He really liked Plummer because
he said his mobility reminded him of  &UR; Joe (Montana).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake's in his second year, and he's played a lot more than
(Druckenmiller). He still makes the mistakes of zeroing in on one
guy and either throwing it or scrambling. That was our big knock
against him. It's incredible how he makes things happen, but
reading the field is where we thought he would have problems. That
will take time. Once he gets to where he can learn that, I think
he'll be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark acknowledges that Druckenmiller has some problems. ``He's
very immature and he's already 26 years old. . . . As far as arm
strength, poise in the pocket . . . Druckenmiller won as many games
(in college), maybe more. You could see how he would read the field
and stick the ball in there. He's got ability, but, to me, he
doesn't seem to want to watch while he's the backup. He loses
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do things in practice that are awesome. He's got to play
and be the guy. I don't know that he'll ever be a great player like
 &UR; Steve Young, but he'll be a starter someday.'' &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals Coach  &UR; Joe Bugel, now offensive line coach at
San Diego, is building a home in the Valley near Fountain Hills.
``I'm going to be a Zonie,'' said Bugel, who has two daughters who
live in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams never would have retained Coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil
if it didn't cost $10 million to fire him and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins wide receiver  &UR; Michael Westbrook sure isn't a student
of football history. As he waited to do a post-game radio interview
with Hall of Famer  &UR; Sam Huff, Westbrook asked him, ``Hey, man, you
ever play the game?'' &QL; 
ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Cardinals: Sure, this isn't a great team. There are warts on
offense. The defense is beat-up and just trying to hang on. But the
Cardinals are exciting as they try to end the NFL's longest playoff
drought. Their games usually aren't decided until the last two
minutes and often come down to the last play. Second-year
quarterback Jake Plummer is a thrill a minute. He'll try to lead
them to their third straight victory today, which would put them in
the playoffs for the first time since 1982. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Denver Broncos: They've had a wonderful regular season,
regardless what happens today against Seattle. Starting the season
with 13 consecutive victories is quite an accomplishment. Running
back Terrell Davis might be the league's Most Valuable Player. Wide
receiver Ed McCaffrey has 10 touchdown catches. Quarterback John
Elway has been slowed by injuries but still has been brilliant at
times. But nobody likes to limp into the playoffs, and the Broncos
have lost two straight.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Bengals Coach Bruce Coslet, knowing the Buccaneers are 0-16 when
the
 &UR; temperature is below 40 degrees, on today's game in Cincinnati: ``I
hope it's 5 degrees and snowing like hell.'' &QL; 
ARE 'BOLTS DOLTS? &QL; 
Chargers quarterbacks Craig Whelihan and Ryan Leaf each have been
intercepted 15 times this season. That's the biggest reason why the
Cardinals, who own San Diego's No. 1 choice, could pick in the top
10 of next year's draft. At least Whelihan has thrown for seven
touchdowns. Leaf has only two touchdown passes, which is two more
than Philadelphia's Bobby Hoying has this season. Hoying didn't get
a five-year, $31.25 million rookie contract or an $11.25 million
signing bonus. Leaf needs a big off-season to get the players
behind him. &QL; 
SHORT SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This isn't good news for the 49ers and Packers, who will play an
NFC wild-card game next week. During the 1990s, only two of the 48
teams that played a first-round playoff game made it to the Super
Bowl. The Bills did it in 1992 and the Broncos last year.
</P>
<P>
   Every Raiders home game has been blacked out this season.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants have sacked opposing quarterbacks 53 times,
most in the league. The Bengals have the fewest sacks with 26.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon of the Seahawks is 903 passing yards away from
becoming the third quarterback in league history to pass for 50,000
career yards, but he said he will retire rather than return next
season as a backup. ``I don't want to come back to this,'' said
Moon, who has lost his job to Jon Kitna. ``I wouldn't want to stick
around just to try to accomplish a milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Jets Coach Rich Kotite, fired after a 1-15
season two years ago, admires the job Bill Parcells has done since
replacing him. In fact, Kotite thinks the Jets will go a long way
in the playoffs. ``When it comes to crunch time, I'll take
Parcells,'' Kotite said.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to St. Louis, the Rams have gotten worse each year.
They've gone 7-9, 6-10, 5-11 and are 4-11 going into today's game
at San Francisco. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
