<HEADLINE>
SCOTT INVESTIGATES TURNING PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Arizona junior  &UR; Yusuf Scott, a leading offensive
lineman, has taken a preliminary step toward making himself
eligible for the next NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Saturday he has sent the NFL an official letter of
inquiry in an attempt to determine the round in which he might be
picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inquiry just tells underclassmen about where they'd go,''
said Scott, a 6-foot-3, 337-pound guard and second-team selection
to the ``Football News'' All-America team. ``Six to seven general
managers will tell you whether its the first or second, third or
fourth and fifth to seventh (rounds).''
</P>
<P>
   Scott indicated he would give serious consideration to forgoing
his senior year if he is projected to go in the second round. He
does not expect to be a first-round projection.
</P>
<P>
   ``First-round would be a no-brainer, of course'' he said. ``But,
as an offensive lineman, I don't figure that will happen.
Second-round would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott expects a response from the NFL on Jan. 4 or 5. He said
he'll make his decision after talking to his mother and Arizona
Coach  &UR; Dick
 &UR; Tomey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to do what is best for Yusuf Scott and his family,''
said the junior, who said he comes from a 16-member family that
lives in a three-bedroom house in LaPorte, Texas. ``I love the
University of Arizona. My best friend is a teammate. I'd like to
come back, but I have to consider all my options.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott's friend, Arizona running back  &UR; Trung Canidate, is also a
junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trung is a terrific athlete,'' Scott said after a workout for
Wednesday's Holiday Bowl game against Nebraska. ``I don't think
he'll pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Canidate has a better chance at improving his
position in the draft with another college season because he plays
a skill position. This season, Arizona senior cornerback
 &UR; Chris McAlister improved his prospects from a mid-round pick last
year to perhaps a spot among the first 10 at the next draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``But offensive linemen are different,'' Scott said. ``We pretty
much go in our senior year where we would go in an earlier year.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
The 11-1 Wildcats played in front of many empty seats at Arizona
Stadium, despite their march to a No. 5 national ranking. But
apparently a bowl appearance has sparked some interest. Arizona
sold its 11,500 ticket allotment one day before Nebraska did,
according to Holiday Bowl executive director  &UR; John Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona went to Sea World Saturday. The crowd impressed
linebacker  &UR; Marcus Bell, who is from tiny St. Johns in northeastern
Arizona. ``In one day, there were more people at Sea World than
there is in all of St. Johns,'' Bell said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
