<DOCNO> NYT19981226.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLIDAY-UA-CANIDA     12-26 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLIDAY-UA-CANIDATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS UA'S TRUNG A CANIDATE FOR HEISMAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ On his driver's license, there have been no changes.
He's not suddenly named Heisman Canidate on the freeway to the 1999
New York Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   He still calls himself Trung.
</P>
<P>
   As a Canidate, he doesn't have much control over the name game
that has helped to put him among the early possibilities for next
year's Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing it all the time now and it's just because people
are having some fun with my name,'' Arizona's junior running back
said Saturday after a workout for Wednesday's Holiday Bowl game
against Nebraska at Qualcomm Stadium. ``People have always had some
with my name. I know it's kind of unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``But talk about this award this is something a lot different. I
hear it, but I don't think about it. I mean, how could anybody
legitimately think about something that big?''
</P>
<P>
   But Canidate, a former Central High School star, has created the
right to dream. Through the second half of Arizona's 11-1 season,
he emerged as one of the nation's most exciting running backs.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up leading the nation in yards per carry at 7.3. Not
even Texas' Ricky Williams, the 1998 Heisman winner, could keep
pace with that average.
</P>
<P>
   The element that separates Canidate from other running backs,
and nearly all defenders, is his explosiveness. He steps through a
seam in defenses as though he's been launched. The result has been
15 career touchdowns of 28 yards and longer.
</P>
<P>
   Those runs make the highlight films, and highlights are pretty
powerful ads in the Heisman campaigns that have come to resemble
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Canidate name is just another element that provides a
marketing edge. Canidate wouldn't be the first to capitalize. Joe
Theisman was the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Theisman name is actually supposed to be pronounced
``Theeseman.''But the former Washington Redskins quarterback told
the Notre Dame publicity department to start pronouncing it so
would rhyme with the trophy. It worked. Theisman won the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that either Canidate or Arizona would be so bold.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Arizona coach Dick Tomey dislikes glossy
publicity campaigns for national awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that can backfire,'' Tomey said. ``Look, we have kids
win national awards all the time without campaigning. Chris
McAlister won the special teams award this year.''
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, Arizona doesn't have to launch a campaign
that plays off the Canidate.
</P>
<P>
   The media are already doing it. There were newspaper headlines
after Canidate ran for 288 yards against Arizona State to capture
the Pac-10 Conference's rushing crown. ESPN started playing the
name game two nights later as it repeatedly showed clips of
Canidate touchdown runs of 80, 66 and 48 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The talk is mounting. And so are the expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids wouldn't be able to handle it,'' Tomey said.
``But Trung is tough. He's got a lot of wisdom for a young guys.
I'm confident he can keep it all in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a degree of uncertainty. With the media
attention, there also is some speculation about whether Canidate
will forgo his senior season for a shot at the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be back,'' he said Saturday. ``I should be back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canidate also hedged. The comment about his planned return
included a suggestion that he could change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything holds true, I should be back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A friendship with offensive lineman Yusuf Scott could be a
powerful factor. Scott, an underclassman, said Saturday that he is
considering making himself eligible for this spring's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, it's about whatever is best for him and his
family,'' Canidate said. ``That's how you got to play it. You
always got to weigh your options. But, yeah, I love college
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomey said he has yet to speak to Canidate about his options.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will talk about it after this (the Holiday Bowl) is
over,'' Tomey said. ``I really believe that Trung knows what
another year can do for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Tomey pointed to McAlister. Arizona's
all-American cornerback had decided to go pro last year, but he
missed the deadline to file for eligibility. Last year, McAlister
probably would have been a mid-round NFL pick. This year, he's
projected to go in the first 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lesson in that for every talented player,'' Tomey
said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Tomey thinks Canidate still is not fully recovered
from an off-season surgery for a stress fracture that sidelined him
for a season-opening victory at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think he's 100 percent,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, forget the game. This Canidate is a contender.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-26-98 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
