r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN     12-26 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGER MITCHELL RETURNS TO PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most of the Bruins were stretching and waiting for
practice to begin Saturday when No. 3 trotted onto Spaulding Field.
</P>
<P>
   At first, they couldn't identify the mystery man. Was it a
scout-team player? Was it a joke?
</P>
<P>
   No, it was receiver Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after breaking his left femur in a gruesome fall at
Houston, Mitchell returned to practice and gave every indication
he'll play in the Rose Bowl. He has been cleared by UCLA's
physician, Dr. Gerald Finerman, leaving the final decision to coach
Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll get him in there for three, four or five plays,''
Toledo said. ``We'll put some plays in for him. . . . (Wisconsin)
better be aware of where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's recovery has surprised everyone but himself. After he
underwent emergency surgery in Houston to implant a stabilizing rod
and two interlocking screws, the UCLA medical staff predicted he'd
be ready for spring practice in April. Toledo wasn't sure Mitchell
would ever return and certainly didn't expect him to do it three
months early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my wildest dreams,'' Toledo said. ``This is a
miracle. I was wondering if he'd ever play again, it was so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell credited his recovery to a calcium-rich diet, eight
hours of rehabilitation per day, and effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is where most players wish (theirs) was,'' he said.
``I did it in three months. It was supposed to take six-to-eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell ran with a slight limp Saturday but said his 40-yard
dash time has improved to 4.6 seconds. After he caught a touchdown
pass, the Bruins celebrated and quarterback Cade McNown yelled to a
group of reporters: ``Freddie Mitchell's back. Print that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was back, doing what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually talked some trash,'' he said, smiling. ``It felt
good, just to let the boys know I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   He's no freak: Junior tackle Kris Farris, considering a jump to
the NFL, spoke by telephone to several NFL personnel directors last
week in Toledo's office.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus: He'd be a late first- or early second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has assumed an advisory role and will help Farris gather
the information he needs to make a sound decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's a high No. 1 (pick) and he feels he needs to go, he
should go,'' Toledo said. ``I'm not here to hold anybody back. I'm
here to counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Toledo made it clear that Farris isn't among the elite
linemen he's coached _ a group that includes UCLA's Jonathan Ogden,
USC's Anthony Munoz and Oregon's Gary Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Farris) is good, but he's not at that stage yet,'' Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fun and functions: The Bruins visited Disneyland last week as
the first of several Rose Bowl-related events. (One highlight:
315-pound guard Andy Meyers nearly crushed McNown on the
Matterhorn.) They'll dine at Lawry's tonight for the Beef Bowl.
Monday, it's Universal Studios. Tuesday, it's City of Hope Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line,'' Toledo said. ``You want to reward them
for getting to the Rose Bowl and have some fun. It shouldn't be
drudgery. We're going to work hard, meet, and practice, but we're
going to have some fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
