<HEADLINE>
A FEW TROJANS ARE LEFT BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ USC left several players at home Saturday as
the Trojans arrived for their game against Texas Christian in
Thursday's Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Windrell Hayes, bothered by a sprained toe, did
not make the trip and will not play in the Sun Bowl. The status of
tailback Frank Strong is also in doubt after he suffered back
spasms while spending Christmas with his family in Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Strong is scheduled to arrive today but probably will not
practice, USC coach Paul Hackett said. Whether he will play in the
game is also in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman quarterback Jason Thomas was also left home and will
not be with the team this week, because Hackett said Thomas has
been ill and bothered by a sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was best if he not come and stay home,'' Hackett
said. ``He couldn't come to practice. I'm very disappointed. I
wanted him here to run the option. He expressed an interest in
coming here. I wanted to bring all the redshirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Thomas' absence is not disciplinary related. With
his absence, USC had freshman tailback Miguel Fletcher of Alemany
play quarterback on the scout team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes was expected to make the trip and try to practice this
week, but his toe never improved.
</P>
<P>
   Starting cornerback Antuan Simmons arrived late Saturday night
from Sacramento because his grandmother died. Simmons will practice
today.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance policy: USC junior offensive lineman Travis Claridge
said he has no intention of turning pro but is thinking about
obtaining an insurance policy for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't go pro. I've got to get better,'' Claridge said. ``But
I want to talk to Coach Hackett about what I should do for next
season. A lot of people are telling me I should get an insurance
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton may rest: Tailback Chad Morton may rest his sore ankle
today and miss practice after going on the Sun Bowl's hard
artificial surface Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was ginger,'' Hackett said. ``I'm not sure he will
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Activity of the day: El Paso wasn't exactly the players' first
choice for a bowl destination, but the Sun Bowl has arranged plenty
of daily activities.
</P>
<P>
   The big event Saturday was a barbecue at the Sheriff's Posse
Barbeque Dinner at an El Paso horse-racing track.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans plan to spend part of Tuesday attending a bloodless
bullfight in Juarez, Mexico, which is next to El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Although the players have some free time, bowl officials are
advising them not to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing they recommend is to make sure if you cross
the border to do it together,'' assistant coach Larry Petroff said.
``Because of that, it was recommended to stay here. It was strongly
recommended to stay here and I think they understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
