<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTTSDALE-AZR &LR;      12-26 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTTSDALE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRINKWATER WOULD HATE WHAT'S GOING ON IN SCOTTSDALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER AND CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ A year after the death of Herb Drinkwater,
the city is embroiled in twin scandals and public squabbling that
are attracting headlines the beloved mayor would have hated.
</P>
<P>
   And leaders, many of them tutored by ``Mr. Scottsdale,'' are
trying to salvage the one thing that was most dear to him: the
coveted image of the West's Most Western Town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two things Herb hated the most: damage to
Scottsdale's image; the second thing he hated equally was
incivility to each other,'' said former Scottsdale City
Councilwoman Diane Cusack. ``We've seen both in spades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Herb were here today or could come down like the ghost of
Christmas present, he would be heartbroken.''
</P>
<P>
   The city Drinkwater cherished is under investigation by a
federal grand jury, and the Scottsdale school district has been
rocked by financial mismanagement and violations of the Open
Meeting Law. There is talk of recalling two elected officials in a
nasty fight over an ice hockey arena, and growth, a Scottsdale
trademark, is constantly under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Drinkwater, the four-term mayor affectionately known as Mr.
Scottsdale, died at age 61 of cancer Dec. 28, 1997, at his home at
the foot of the McDowell Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   A full year after his death, residents and city leaders still
mourn him and are grappling to come up with a tribute to the man
remembered for his optimism, humor, penchant for pleasing and role
in shaping the city.
</P>
<P>
   And they wonder how the mayor, who made it his life's work to
put Scottsdale on the map, would react to the year's events. &QL; 
WHAT WOULD DRINKWATER HAVE DONE?
</P>
<P>
   The city and district's current guards quietly battle the
negative publicity and questions about their brand of governing.
But a question resounds through the city: What would the man in the
silver Stetson have done?
</P>
<P>
   Drinkwater, observers say, would have used the sheer force of
his popularity and personality to try to save his city's soul.
</P>
<P>
   He believed that he ``could bring all sides of a debate together
and find the common ground,'' said zoning attorney John Berry.
``And he had a unique God-given ability, that I've never seen
replicated, to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most say the turmoil in Scottsdale hasn't tarnished the
reputation of a city that lures visitors from around the world to
its resorts, golf courses and mountain vistas. But some privately
worry that the federal investigation will affect the city's bond
rating or ability to lure new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them are ones that affect Scottsdale's international
stature,'' Berry said. ``But we don't want to live off our past
glories. We want to continue to be a leader and build off those
successes.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry fears the investigation will deter people with
Drinkwater's vision and leadership from running for public office.
And that would have troubled Drinkwater, who told nearly every
person he met to run for City Council or school board, join a
commission or volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scottsdale has a history, for better or for worse, for
being a leader. And sometimes when you are a leader you get shot
out of the saddle,'' he said. ``A loss of leadership is what can be
a result. And that is something that can have ramifications for a
lot of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry was referring to an ongoing months-long federal grand jury
investigation into high-level police and city officials' efforts
against a controversial night club. Investigators widened the probe
to determine if police and city officials launched a campaign to
shut down the former Club Tribeca because it attracted a mostly
minority clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Drinkwater, who kept an ear glued to a scanner and responded
personally to emergency calls, ``would feel especially chagrined
about what the Police Department is going through,'' said
Drinkwater's successor, Mayor Sam Campana.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be particularly hurtful to him, to see his Police
Department under any kind of cloud,'' Campana said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some say Drinkwater would have led the effort, which a
federal prosecutor is calling into question, to banish the club.
Like current police and city officials, Drinkwater would have
wanted to eliminate violence that police said the club drew to the
corner of Scottsdale and McDowell roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been as adamant about getting rid of it because
the neighbors were so adamant. He would have been interested in
supporting the neighbors,'' said former Councilwoman Susan Bitter
Smith. &QL; 
SCHOOL FLAP SADDENING
</P>
<P>
   And Drinkwater, whose wife was a longtime Scottsdale teacher,
would have been saddened by the chaos that has tarnished the school
district this year. The school board admitted to more than three
dozen Open Meeting Law violations. Investigators for the state
Auditor General's Office also said administrators broke laws and
district policy by favoring vendors, accepting gifts and splitting
bids.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, the former councilwoman, believes that, even though
school and city politics don't usually mix, Drinkwater might have
used his ``personal contacts with the board to ease that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale has faced other challenges in the year since
Drinkwater's death. An impassioned battle is brewing over a
proposed arena in south Scottsdale for the Phoenix Coyotes. Angry
neighbors vow to recall Campana and Councilman Robert Pettycrew, a
south Scottsdale resident, who both support using state tax dollars
generated by the redevelopment of an aging mall to help build the
arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellman Cos. and the Phoenix Coyotes want to build a
20,000-seat arena as part of a $624 million redevelopment of Los
Arcos Mall. The plans have sparked heated debate, because the
developer wants to use a state tax break to pay for $219 million of
the total tab.
</P>
<P>
   Drinkwater, many say, would have supported the 75-foot-tall
arena, and likely would have gotten outraged neighbors to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would have gone down there all day long and evening
long to those neighborhoods and talked them into seeing sweet
reason and the viability of the mall redevelopment as a total
package,'' Cusack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to Sam, this was Herb's magic to do that.
Even if they didn't like it, he would have really tried to take the
acid out of the argument.'' &QL; 
COALITION DEMANDS RESTRAINT
</P>
<P>
   Some say, though, that even the amenable Drinkwater may not have
been able to calm the increasingly intense debate over Scottsdale's
rapid development. The late mayor is often considered the architect
of the city's fast-growing profile. But he was rarely challenged,
and didn't have to face a new, politically powerful coalition
demanding restraint.
</P>
<P>
   That group cemented its position this year when it elected two
slow-growthers to the council.
</P>
<P>
   The election of George Zraket and Cynthia Lukas is considered a
major break from the traditional Drinkwater style of shaping the
city.
</P>
<P>
   His strength clearly was in coaxing people into seeing things
his way. Now the old guard is being challenged at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Drinkwater lamented that his beloved desert was engulfed
in red-tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the end, Herb wished he'd done more sooner when it
came to preservation because his heart truly was there,'' said
Carla, a key preservationist who uses no last name. ``And the
important thing to remember is he always encouraged us.''
</P>
<P>
   Campana has proclaimed Monday ``Mayor R. Herb Drinkwater
Remembrance Day.'' As part of his memorial, city officials will
decide in the next several months whether to name Wingate Pass, a
scenic saddle in the McDowell Mountains, after him or to dedicate
part of the downtown Civic Center Mall to the late mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Current debates aside, Campana said Drinkwater, her friend and
mentor, would still proclaim Scottsdale the greatest place on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his bedrock.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
