u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-GREATEST     12-26 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-GREATEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Williams has case for niche in pantheon of great backs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Texas' Ricky Williams had set all the records, earning the
distinction as the most prolific running back ever in college
football. He had taken all the awards, making the speeches and
accepting the congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   He had stood at the podium of the Downtown Athletic Club and
accepted the Heisman Trophy in front of a room full of former
Heisman winners including his childhood hero, Marcus Allen.
</P>
<P>
   He would ring the bell to begin trading on the New York Stock
Exchange. In the coming days, he would chat up David Letterman, and
take a seat in one of the comfy chairs on the Good Morning America
set.
</P>
<P>
   But as he looked around the room the night of the Heisman
dinner, saw all the heroes of past seasons, all the greats, he
turned to a friend and said, ``I can't believe I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had joined many clubs this season, and Heisman winners
traditionally return to New York to welcome the newest member to
their fraternity each December. But even his collection of records
and awards did not &UR;  &LR; automatically earn him recognition as a member
of the most exclusive of circles.
</P>
<P>
   To be called the greatest running back of them all, or to at
least earn a place in the argument, Williams would require more
subjective qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   His place as college football's all-time rushing and scoring
leader would seem to earn Williams consideration. But numbers alone
cannot do that. Does anybody argue LeShon Johnson or Anthony
Thompson was a greater player than say, Gale Sayers or Jim Brown?
</P>
<P>
   For college football's all-time leading rusher to be considered
college football's all-time best rusher, more discriminating judges
than the editors of record books would have to offer their
blessing. With that in mind, a panel of an All-American, all-timer
and old-timer, a longtime NFL executive and a longtime college
coach served to determine a place for Williams in college football
lore.
</P>
<P>
   Legends take time to mature, to evolve in the retelling. But
rather than wait, opinions were gathered from a panel of experts:
Craig James, the former SMU running back and CBS college football
analyst; Allen, the Southern California Heisman winner and longtime
NFL star; John David Crow, the former Texas A&AMP;M Heisman winner and
NFL veteran; Gil Brandt, the former Cowboys vice president; and
Grant Teaff, the former Baylor coach and American Football Coaches
Association executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly have to put him in the same category with
the great runners, the greatest players that ever played,'' Crow
said. ``He gained more yards, but that doesn't put him in that
greatest-player-that-ever-played category. You have to watch him to
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of great players, a lot. The ones that I
remember, like Doak Walker who is the ultimate, Jim Brown, from my
era, Gale Sayers, Earl Campbell _ Ricky will be remembered in that
same light. Now there's (Barry) Sanders and you say, `How can you
get any better than that?' But then Ricky Williams comes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't pass judgment on who the greatest that ever played is.
But Ricky can sit at that table.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the afternoon after he announced he would return to
Texas for his senior year, Williams wore a Barry Sanders Lions
jersey, as if he felt closer to the fans who now wear his burnt
orange than to the stars to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   But after Williams surpassed the statistical achievements of
every predecessor, even if he still seemed in awe of the group of
players he had joined, members of that group saw the qualities that
separate the merely prolific from the all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him play and I could see certain things that make
him special,'' Allen said. ``They're all innate. The way he
maneuvers, the balance and speed. And then there's a certain grace
the way guys do things. It's just a part of their makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the speed, power and moves, and I see a guy as
powerful as Earl, but more elusive. The great backs all possess the
same thing, and that's natural ability, natural instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most runners tell you what they're doing. Most of the great
runners just do it. They have one quality above all, and it's
natural instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   With Williams' unusual combination of strength and speed, his
physical tools are most often mentioned as the source of his
success. But the record books are filled with backs with great
physical talents. The less tangible qualities elevate a few to that
rarer group of legends, the players fans watch with awe and
proclaim the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys that have been great runners just have God-given
ability,'' Allen said. ``They just work hard on getting stronger
and faster. But most of it is so natural. You can put a fine
athlete, a great athlete and try to teach him those things and you
can't. It can't be learned. Guys would ask me, `What did you see,
why did you do it?' I didn't have a clue. Most of the great runners
just do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there running thinking about things, that's
the worst thing you can do. Most runners are just instinctive. When
you think about it, it's almost contrived. You have to be
liberated. You just do your thing. That's the way it is with Ricky.
What he does is just him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that point when a back moves beyond the total of his
athletic parts that he joins the likes of Allen, Campbell, Walker,
Sanders, Sayers, Brown, O.J. Simpson, Herschel Walker, Tony
Dorsett, Archie Griffin, Eric Dickerson and Bo Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big Notre Dame fan asked me what was the difference between
Autry Denson (who became Notre Dame's all-time leading rusher) and
Ricky Williams,'' James said. ``I told him Ricky Williams can make
a play, can make an offense. Autry Denson complements the offense
and Autry is a good player. In order to be the difference-maker,
you have to be able to break tackles. What Ricky does after
somebody hits him makes him as good as anybody that ever played the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue Williams is the absolute greatest from among
that group, or for that matter that any member of that list is the
definitive best. But many observers believe that as time passes and
tales of Williams' achievement are repeated, there will be those
who maintain that the running back of their time was the greatest,
just as others will forever argue in favor of the back from their
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some making the argument in his favor,'' Teaff
said. ``That's rightly so. What you have when someone says he's the
very best, he has to be in that upper ledger to start off and
that's something. Then it depends on time and circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can dine at the head table. He's got all the
characteristics any good running backs coach would like to have.
He's mentally tough, very smart. He's humble, which helps an awful
lot with linemen and the people working to make you successful.
That came through loud and clear. His combination of strength and
speed is among the very best. He has all the qualities you'd look
for.''
</P>
<P>
   As years pass, Teaff said, Williams' popularity during his time
would enhance his legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody in 10, 15 years, so many people wanted
to win the Heisman Trophy,'' Teaff said. ``I noticed coaches in the
conference, players in the conference, folks around the country
wanted him to win it. That might be because he didn't just go out
and win it at the finish line, he blew it out, particularly with
his performance against A&AMP;M. People will remember that for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if a back's place in college football history is determined
in part by how he is remembered, his success after his college
football career can help determine his reputation over time.
Griffin is the only back to twice win the Heisman. But because his
NFL career could not rival his collegiate success, his reputation
even as a college player seems diminished, at least in the company
of the all-time greats who added the confirmation of professional
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm Cleveland, I would take him first in the draft,''
Brandt said. ``You watch him on the field and off and he works as
hard as anybody, catches the ball, pays attention. He has the
speed, quickness and acceleration to be a great back, all the
qualities you need to be a top-flight football player, to be a
perennial All-Pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style is somewhere between Herschel and Sanders and
Dorsett. I'd have a hard time comparing him to anyone. I think
that's a great compliment. He belongs in that category. A true
superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains if Williams with the greatest numbers
should be considered the greatest back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way: It's totally unfair for anybody not to put
him with the top backs all-time in college,'' James said. ``He
earned that.''
</P>
<P>
   But picking one will have to remain subjective.
</P>
<P>
   As Crow said: ``That's the reason they make chocolate, vanilla
and other flavors. It's what fits your style and your taste.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
