<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Some free advice to sort out bowls
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here, we'll try to make it easier on you.
</P>
<P>
   We are on the verge of 16 college football games invading the
airwaves in a span of five days. It is an overwhelming proposition,
sure, even for the most avid and experienced veteran of
remote-control clicking.
</P>
<P>
   But we are here to help. In the 16 bowls that will entertain us
between Tuesday and the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl for the national
championship Jan. 4, there are things we know will happen, games we
know we shouldn't miss and others that probably should be clicked
into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, may we offer a few insights, not to be confused with
Insight.coms, for the upcoming matches.
</P>
<P>
   Quotes we'll never read:
</P>
<P>
   From Bill Snyder, coach of the Alamo Bowl's Kansas State
Wildcats, who came within a whisper of playing for the national
championship before screaming bloody murder about the bowl system:
``We're just happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   From Tim Couch, the junior sensation who leads the Kentucky
Wildcats against Penn State in the Outback Bowl: ``I don't care
that my entire offensive line won't be back next season I WILL!''
</P>
<P>
   From any Mississippi State player: ``Well, you see, it was the
funniest thing. Coach Sherrill brought this longhorn steer to
practice one day. And then he pulled out this great, big knife. And
then he gathered us all around that steer and talked about taking
the manhood out of the 'Horns and ''
</P>
<P>
   Say, can I have the remote?
</P>
<P>
   Games that, like brussels sprouts, are one part of this holiday
feast we probably could do without:
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian Bowl: If these folks truly were humanitarian, they
would get rid of that hideous blue AstroTurf. And on top of that,
Southern Mississippi will make potato pancakes out of Idaho in a
yawner.
</P>
<P>
   Music City Bowl: Normally, Virginia Tech-Alabama would be worthy
of this bowl's name _ sweet music. But this year, Roseanne Arnold
might as well sing the national anthem. Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest Sun Bowl: USC-TCU? R.U.KIDDING?
</P>
<P>
   Gator Bowl: NBC is counting on Notre Dame sweeping to high
ratings on New Year's Day, despite featuring this unimaginative
team going head-to-head with Penn State-Kentucky, Michigan-Arkansas
and Texas-Mississippi State. The only way the Irish could pull off
this ratings battle would be if Jerry Seinfeld was coach, Elaine
Benes a cheerleader and Art Vandalay started at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Games that might not be for the whole enchilada, but should pack
an entertaining kick:
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Bowl (Arizona-Nebraska): One of these teams could be
playing for the national championship if not for one sloppy half of
football. The other team is Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Orange Bowl: Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb firing bullets
and sprinting away from the athletic Gators defense is a match made
in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   A Peach of a bowl
</P>
<P>
   Chick-Fil-A Peach Bowl: Virginia-Georgia quite possibly is the
best matchup of teams this year, although something needs to be
done about the matchup of the game and the sponsor. Or are you
comfortable with Chick-Fil-A sponsoring a game in a city known for
the Dirty Bird?
</P>
<P>
   Games you might consider taking if you were a point-spread
player, which, of course, you're not. And neither am I. But if I
were, these would be the teams I would take:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (plus-3) vs. Nebraska: The normally dominating
Cornhuskers offensive line has been on a Holiday all season. Now
the players have the official windbreaker and travel bag to prove
it. It'll be the 'Cats.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (plus-6{) vs. Penn State: You only thought Nittany
Lions coach Joe Paterno wore high-water pants before. Wait until he
gets a load of Couch flooding the field with more passing yards
than Paterno might ever have seen.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (minus-6{) vs. Mississippi State: Ricky Williams will more
than make up for past Longhorns losses, not to mention other lost
Longhorns things, at the hands of Jackie Sherrill.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M (plus-12{) vs. Ohio State: Heck, this one should be
easy! With Florida State, Nebraska, Missouri, Texas and Kansas
State among the eight bowl teams A&AMP;M faced this year, the Aggies'
only worry should be overconfidence. OK, maybe not. But they'll be
tough on the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State (minus-5) vs. Tennessee: Call it Operation Desert
Fox. No one gets a team better prepared for a big game than Bobby
Bowden and his staff. This one is for it all. It's in the desert.
It's another chance for Bowden to take a title. We have to believe
the old fox will find a way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
