</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALAMO-KSTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kansas State promises post-A&AMP;M funk has lifted
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ As the Kansas State Wildcats behold the Riverwalk,
their toughest task may be to keep their minds out of the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the Big 12 Championship Game at St. Louis, the Wildcats
had an outside shot at a Fiesta Bowl berth and, with a win there,
the national championship. By halftime, with UCLA having lost, they
looked like a shoo-in for the Fiesta. By game's end, having lost
36-33 in double overtime to Texas A&AMP;M, they were also-rans _ at
least when it came to national-championship consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But at 11-1, Kansas State was still one of the top eight teams
in the country, which made it especially maddening when the
Wildcats were passed over for an at-large berth in the Bowl
Championship Series, then snubbed by the Cotton and Holiday bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Their eventual destination was the Alamo Bowl. And while the
matchup with Purdue is a far cry from a Fiesta Bowl matchup for the
national title, coach Bill Snyder said the game presents him with
the toughest coaching job he has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks his team will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the air clears and we have some time, this football team
will want to compete again,'' he said. ``I trust the competitive
nature of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's competitive nature, however, has been just part of
the battle. Ron Hudson, the Wildcats' offensive coordinator and
quarterbacks coach, said that before Snyder could prepare the
Wildcats, he had to recover himself from the loss to A&AMP;M and the
vanished shot at the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This upset him personally,'' Hudson said. ``We have lost some
big games in the past, but to get to where we were at the
particular point and kind of understand the commitment and hard
work we had and to come so close _ it's difficult on anybody. But
he's fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said losing in overtime was what stung so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come as close as we did and have a chance to win the game
and not execute at the end, then that is disappointing when you
know that you have got the people to get it done,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This not only falls on the players, but falls on us as
coaches. It's a direct reflection on what we have done in terms of
preparation, and we didn't get it done. The impact that game had on
this program was resounding. You go from a high to not
understanding why.''
</P>
<P>
   Other blows followed. Defensive coordinator Mike Stoopes agreed
to become defensive coordinator on his brother Bob's new staff at
Oklahoma. Linebackers coach Brent Venables also will join Stoops at
OU, and defensive ends coach Jon Fabris might leave for South
Carolina to reunite with Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kansas State players asked Stoopes and Venables to
remain with the team through the Alamo Bowl, and both agreed to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the players who went to coach Snyder and requested that
Mike Stoopes and Brent Venables remain and help us prepare for this
game,'' Hudson said. ``They want to win this game, and they knew if
they brought in new coaches for their position, it might cause some
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players recognize that these people have to live
their lives and make hard decisions. Mike Stoopes is still getting
in their faces in practice. You just have to realize that this is
part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other consolation prizes followed. Michael Bishop won the Davey
O'Brien Award as the nation's top quarterback and was second in the
Heisman balloting. Snyder won the Bear Bryant Coach of the Year
Award presented in Houston. Both were badly needed morale boosters,
said linebacker Jeff Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice _ all the awards,'' Kelly said. ``It really helped
because you had everybody who knew a lot about football telling you
that you had a great season. That was a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   So, slowly but surely, Kansas State is building the same sort of
game-day attitude that made the Fiesta Bowl such a real possibility
before the loss to the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to finish the season with a victory,'' Bishop
said. ``It will be the last time for the seniors to go into battle
and do this one last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no pressure on us. We know what kind of team we have.
We don't have to go out and prove that. We feel we don't have to
prove anything to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go out with a win. But if we go out with a loss, I
think everything happens for a reason. It would be great to win
your last college game ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever it may be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
