u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OILERS-VIKINGS-HN     12-26 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-VIKINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Vikings claim record; Oilers mark transition
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The postgame scene outside the dressing rooms at
Vanderbilt Stadium on Saturday was almost surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before, Minnesota had defeated Tennessee 26-16 to become
the highest-scoring team in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings owner Red McCombs celebrated Minnesota joining the 1984
San Francisco 49ers and the 1985 Chicago Bears as the league's only
15-1 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been chasing this dream for 30 years,'' said McCombs, San
Antonio's favorite son who bought the Vikings in the offseason for
$245 million. ``To have a dream season like this is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, Tennessee guard Bruce Matthews and line coach
Mike Munchak, two of the greatest players in franchise history,
posed for a picture with the other linemen because it was their
last time together in an Oilers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be strange being called something besides the Oilers,''
said Matthews, who was voted to the Pro Bowl for the 11th
consecutive year. ``Being part of the Oilers has been special to
me. Who knows, someday this game might be the answer to a trivia
question.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2:44 p.m., a 39-year era ended when Houston/Tennessee played
its last game as the Oilers. But owner Bud Adams didn't make the
trip from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotional day for me,'' Adams said. ``I just
thought it was better to spend it with our family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked the name in 1959. That's a lot of time and memories,
but we're ready to start our new era as the Titans. We're excited
about moving into our new stadium next year. We can give people
some new memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, for a team known for choking in the playoffs when it
made the playoffs at all, the Oilers blew two leads, including a
13-8 halftime advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the sellout crowd of 41,121 came to Vanderbilt Stadium
to see Minnesota and such stars as quarterback Randall Cunningham,
receivers Randy Moss and Cris Carter and defensive tackle John
Randle. After a slow start, the Vikings didn't disappoint them.
</P>
<P>
   With Cunningham throwing for 235 yards and two touchdowns to
Carter and Moss, the Vikings finished with 556 points, breaking
Washington's 1983 record of 541.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this could be a record-setting offense back in the
spring when we re-signed everybody and added Randy to the mix,''
said running back Robert Smith, who rushed for 73 yards. ``I knew
that if this offense stuck together, we could have an unbelievable
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's like being a great quarterback. They're not
considered great quarterbacks until they've been to the show and
won it. This is a great team, but this (scoring record and
finishing 15-1) won't mean a thing if we don't get to the big show
and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The big show is the Super Bowl, and the Vikings never have won
it. Now Minnesota is favored over anything the AFC has to offer,
including Denver, the defending Super Bowl champion that has lost
its past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we have home-field advantage, and we
have to take advantage of it,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Green desperately wanted to finish 15-1. He started all of his
regulars who were healthy other than offensive tackle Kory
Stringer. When the Oilers led 13-5 on two Al Del Greco field goals
and Eddie George's two-yard run, the Vikings were not concerned.
That's called confidence, and they have it by the tons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were overconfident,'' said Cunningham, who
signed a five-year contract extension this past week. ``It's
amazing, really. We struggled to score 26 points. Some teams would
think 26 points is great, but expectations are so high for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 15-1 record is awesome, but we want to be 18-1. We made too
many mistakes today, and it's important for us to keep plugging and
stay with our style of play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who might have surpassed Denver's Terrell Davis as
the leading candidate to be the NFL's Most Valuable Player,
completed six passes for 78 yards to Carter and five for 32 to
Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who finished with 17 touchdown catches, is expected to be
named Offensive Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touchdowns, yards, making things happen, tearing it up _ I
expected all that from myself as a rookie,'' Moss said. ``I didn't
think too much about the winning side, but now that we're 15-1, it
doesn't really mean much until we reach the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are the first dome team with the home-field
advantage. They get a well-deserved break by sitting out the first
round and hosting a second-round game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about history; I'm thinking about the
playoffs,'' said Randle, a Hearne native who lives in Houston in
the offseason. ``Being 15-1 is great, but we have a bigger goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, all this hasn't really sunk in. It might be April
before it does. All I know right now is that we have a week off for
everyone to get healthy. We have a chance to relax, but we want to
enter the playoffs with a winning edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we could have lost in this game is the feeling
of victory,'' said defensive tackle Jerry Ball, a Beaumont native.
``You want to go into the playoffs and build, and you would rather
win than lose. Our focus is on the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the season, the Vikings took a back seat to Denver
when it came to the national spotlight. The Broncos were trying to
finish 16-0. Now, the spotlight is on Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I didn't follow Denver,'' Randle said. ``I followed The
Young and the Restless. Now, if you want to know anything about
that ''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
