</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-OHIOST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ohio State coach still claims shot at No. 1
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ Maybe he didn't invent it, but unfettered optimism
undoubtedly got its anthem from an infamous utterance of Major
League Baseball Hall of Famer and philosopher Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it is over, someone is likely to say, ``It ain't over
'til it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Ohio State football coach John Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   He still believes, or at least he still sounds like he believes,
his Buckeyes are in the hunt for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the same third-ranked Buckeyes, who arrived here Saturday
to begin preparations for a tilt with No. 8 Texas A&AMP;M in the Sugar
Bowl on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the No. 1-ranked team (Tennessee) will face the
No. 2-ranked team (Florida State) in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4, in
what the Bowl Championship Series bills as the national
championship game, Cooper says, ``This thing's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the door is not shut on us yet,'' Cooper said. ``We
have just as much claim to the national title as Florida State
would, if we beat Texas A&AMP;M and they beat Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State (10-1) was the preseason No. 1-ranked team and spent
10 weeks of the season atop the national rankings.
</P>
<P>
   But it fell out of the national championship picture with a
28-24 loss to Michigan State at home on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes hope a huge win over the Aggies coupled with a
Florida State victory over unbeaten Tennessee could get them a
share of the national crown, since Florida State and Ohio State
would each end the season with one loss.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State lost by 17 points on the road to unranked North
Carolina State, but the Wolfpack will at least play in a bowl game
(Micron PC), while Michigan State will not.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper sold his argument fast and furiously just after Texas A&AMP;M
and Miami did his Buckeyes a huge favor by knocking off Kansas
State and UCLA the last Saturday of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   How many have bought into it is difficult to determine. The
ESPN/USA Today coaches poll has agreed to vote the winner of the
Fiesta Bowl as its No. 1 team. The Associated Press media poll has
no such automatic alliance, but Ohio State would likely have to be
more than just impressive against Texas A&AMP;M to jump Florida State
in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take nothing away from Texas A&AMP;M and (coach) R.C. Slocum,
because I know they will be prepared to play and they are a very
good team,'' Cooper said. ``We know it's a long shot, but there is
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's proposal of a mini-playoff system would work in his
Buckeyes' favor this season. He would like to see a one-game
playoff after the end of the bowl season, pitting the top two
remaining squads two weeks after the New Year's Day bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has been a proponent of that long before this year's
predicament, but in the current system, there is only one way Ohio
State can claim a share of the national title _ by miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M has heard it before.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State was No. 1 in one poll and No. 2 in the other
entering the Big 12 Championship Game, but with its third-place
standing in the BCS ratings, the Wildcats figured they needed a
huge win over the two-touchdown underdog Aggies to possibly get an
invite to the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Kansas State not get a huge win, it got beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Ohio State wants to talk about how they can possibly
win a national championship by blowing us out, but I'm pretty sure
Kansas State thought the same thing,'' A&AMP;M linebacker Warrick
Holdman said. ``We can't worry about that stuff. We're going out
there to try and win the game just like they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Cooper may try as hard as the street vendors here to sell
his product, the Buckeyes know their hopes probably went down the
drain with the devastating loss to Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the quietest, coldest feeling I've ever been a part
of in that stadium,'' Ohio State senior safety Damon Moore said.
``You could hear a pin drop _ even on grass you could have heard
it. It was just a sick feeling. It was something about that 8-0
start at that time and all of a sudden it was gone, just like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like it was the second week of the season, where we
can still get back (in the national title hunt). We pretty much
knew (it was over). Everybody was feeling it, the seniors, the
fans, the people collecting tickets, the cheerleaders _ it was a
bad feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper felt it as well, but he still hopes the loss doesn't mean
it's over, because as you know, ``It ain't over 'til it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
